<B> Next:</B> <A NAME="tex2html207" HREF="node5.html">CRS4 in the EC </A>
<B>Up:</B> <A NAME="tex2html205" HREF="node3.html">Introduction</A>
<B> Previous:</B> <A NAME="tex2html199" HREF="node3.html">Introduction</A>
<BR> <P>
<H2><A NAME="SECTION00031000000000000000">Framework of the Project</A></H2>
<P>
The project EV5V-CT94-0446,
<EM>Spatial and temporal soil moisture mapping from ERS-1 and J-ERS-1 SAR
data and macroscale hydrologic modeling for regional climate models</EM>, is
financed in part by the European Community (EC) and involves four hydrological 
test sites in Europe. This
project is set up to research the possibilities of deriving soil moisture
data from the European remote sensing satellite (ERS-1) and the Japanese
Earth resources satellite (J-ERS-1). Fundamental knowledge about the
behavior of water in the top soil layer will contribute to our
understanding of fundamental processes in the hydrologic cycle, such as
the partitioning of rainfall into runoff and infiltration
components.
<P>
The project is a collaboration between 6 research groups in Belgium,
Italy, France, and England. The four test sites are:
<UL><LI> Zwalm catchment, Belgium <A NAME="gent">&#160;</A><LI> Virginiolo catchment, Italy<LI> Naizin catchment, France<LI> Sele calibration site, Italy
</UL>
Ground truth data collection campaigns are organized to coincide with 
selected satellite overpasses of the test sites.
These campaigns produce a large amount of data of various types that need
to be managed and processed, for instance to locate the position 
with respect to the
satellite remote sensing images obtained from the European 
or Japanese Space Agencies.
The positioning of these data is the first step in the processing of
the images, and is an important preliminary for future uses of the
image data in the project, such as to calibrate and validate 
simulation models, to produce soil moisture maps, and to investigate
issues of scaling and spatial variability in hydrologic processes.
<P>
A geographic information system (GIS) allows the user to position 
projected and unprojected data in digital form. 
It stores the absolute position of the data, 
is able to link all related data to this position, and allows 
manipulation of either the position or the data itself. 
The data are in either array or point format, in the latter case
eventually linked to lines or polygons. 
Because of the complexity of positioning a point on the surface
of the Earth, GIS systems use mathematical algorithms to combine 
data with neighboring points. 
With these and other sophisticated algorithms, a GIS is 
able to make a dataset scale independent. The scale depends only on 
the scale in which the data are digitized.
<P>
<HR><A NAME="tex2html206" HREF="node5.html"><IMG WIDTH=37 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="next" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/next_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME="tex2html204" HREF="node3.html"><IMG WIDTH=26 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="up" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/up_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME="tex2html198" HREF="node3.html"><IMG WIDTH=63 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="previous" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/previous_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME="tex2html208" HREF="node1.html"><IMG WIDTH=65 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="contents" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/contents_motif.gif"></A>  <BR>
