<B> Next:</B> <A NAME="tex2html374" HREF="node19.html">Quantitative Hydrologic Data </A>
<B>Up:</B> <A NAME="tex2html372" HREF="node17.html">Time Dependent Data: Continuous </A>
<B> Previous:</B> <A NAME="tex2html366" HREF="node17.html">Time Dependent Data: Continuous </A>
<BR> <P>
<H3><A NAME="SECTION00043100000000000000">History</A></H3>
<P>
In 1991 the Research Team Zwalm Catchment, coordinated by
Prof. F. De Troch of the University of Gent, was set up
with the aim of investigating
the qualitative and quantitative aspects of the hydrologic cycle in
the Zwalm catchment. A network of measuring 
stations was established. Most stations log into permanent files the
main hydrologic parameters (e.g., water levels, precipitation,
meteorological parameters, groundwater levels, etc.). Some
of the stations register the values by means of a clock-driven
recorder on paper. These data are digitized in the Laboratory of Hydraulics
at the University of Gent.
Qualitative parameters are monitored at the outlet of the Zwalm. This
monitoring station
includes a sampler and a permanent probe for measuring chemical properties of
the water. Samples are analyzed in the Laboratory of Agrochemistry.
A fourth member of the Research Team Zwalm Catchment is the Laboratory of
Hydrogeology. This 
lab monitors groundwater levels continuously, and groundwater quality
sporadically along a transect of one
of the second order channels of the Zwalm (Wijlegemse beek).
<P>
<BR> <HR>
<P><ADDRESS>
<I>Bart Cosyn <BR>
Thu Jul 25 13:19:15 MDT 1996</I>
