<BR> <P>
<H2><A NAME="SECTION00052000000000000000">Description of the Remote Sensing Campaigns</A></H2>
<P>
In the summer of 1994 (April-October) three major soil moisture 
remote sensing campaigns were held in the Zwalm catchment.
<DL ><DT><STRONG>European and Japanese remote sensing satellites 
      (ERS-1 and J-ERS-1)</STRONG>
<DD>
The European remote sensing satellite (ERS-1) was launched in 
1991 and carries on
board different advanced instruments for Earth observation. 
Of interest for hydrologic applications is the active microwave instrument
(AMI) which consists of two separate radars: a synthetic aperture radar 
(SAR) and a wind scatterometer.
The AMI-SAR instrument is a 5.3&nbsp;GHz radar using vertical 
polarization. SAR images are
collected on strips of high resolution imagery ( <IMG WIDTH=92 HEIGHT=25 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="tex2html_wrap_inline2829" SRC="img10.gif"  > &nbsp;m), 
100 km in width, to the right of the satellite track. 
The mid-swath incidence angle of the system in normal operation is 23 <IMG WIDTH=7 HEIGHT=6 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="tex2html_wrap_inline2831" SRC="img11.gif"  > .
The Japanese Earth resources satellite (J-ERS-1) was launched 
in 1993 and carries on
board a 1.2&nbsp;GHz (L-band) SAR instrument with horizontal polarization. 
The spatial and temporal resolution of this polar orbiting satellite are 
comparable with the ERS-1 satellite. The
incidence angle of this system in normal operation is 35 <IMG WIDTH=7 HEIGHT=6 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="tex2html_wrap_inline2831" SRC="img11.gif"  > .
The 20 SAR PRIs collected from April to October 1994 for the Zwalm
are in the so-called geodetic phase of ERS-1 (repeat cycle of 268
days). Therefore each frame (1017 for ascending orbit and 2583 for
descending orbit) are taken from slightly different positions of view.
Ground truth data were collected on the following days: April 6, April 9, 
June 16 and August 29. In addition to the ERS-1 SAR images, satellite
image data were from the J-ERS-1 satellite have also been requested
but not received yet. Ground truth data for these images were 
collected on April 6 and September 10.
<P>
<DT><STRONG>European Multi-sensor Airborne Campaign (EMAC)</STRONG>
<DD>
EMAC&nbsp;94/95 is a collaborative programme of the European Space
Agency (ESA) and JRC (Joint Research Centre of the EC). 
The objectives of EMAC&nbsp;94/95 are multi-disciplinary,
with interests including
agriculture, forestry, hydrology, snow and ice, and coastal and ocean studies. 
The airborne instruments used in the programme include synthetic aperture 
radar (SAR), imaging spectrometer, and microwave radiometer. 
The campaign plan for 1994 addressed some of the requirements of four 
thematic groups (NOPEX; Ocean, Coastal and Inland Waters; Agriculture 
and Forestry; and Vegetation and Soils). The Zwalm catchment was 
selected as a test site within the Vegetation and Soils thematic group. 
Multi-temporal EMAC SAR (ESAR)
and reflective optics system imaging spectrometer (ROSIS)
flights were held during the summer of 1994 over the catchment.
The ESAR is an ``experimental'' multi-frequency, dual polarization 
SAR, designed for
medium-sized turbo prop aircrafts. It was developed and built by the DLR 
Institute for Radio Frequency Technology (Germany), 
and is mounted on board of a twin engine Do-228 owned
and operated by DLR. The maximum flight altitude is about 6000&nbsp;m 
and the maximum flight duration of the fully equipped aircraft is approximately 
5 hours. During EMAC the ESAR was working in 
4 frequencies (X, C, L, and P band) 
with vertical and horizontal co-polarization. Since there is single 
channel data acquisition, the flight track has to be flown separately
for each combination of frequency and polarization. Frequency and 
polarization are switchable during the flight. Cross-polarization 
is unavailable. For EMAC only wide swath
mode is flown (standard scene size:  <IMG WIDTH=42 HEIGHT=25 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="tex2html_wrap_inline2835" SRC="img12.gif"  > &nbsp;km; geometric resolution: 
4.5&nbsp;m; operating altitude: 3600&nbsp;m; incidence angle: 23 <IMG WIDTH=7 HEIGHT=6 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="tex2html_wrap_inline2831" SRC="img11.gif"  >  (near edge), 
52 <IMG WIDTH=7 HEIGHT=6 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="tex2html_wrap_inline2831" SRC="img11.gif"  >  (center swath), 65 <IMG WIDTH=7 HEIGHT=6 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="tex2html_wrap_inline2831" SRC="img11.gif"  >  (far edge)).
ESAR flights were held on April 9, June 30, and August 19. 
Only one successful ROSIS flight was held, on July 12. 
ROSIS can operate in different modes. 
For the collection of remote sensing data in the Zwalm catchment 
only the imaging mode is used. In imaging mode 32 channels are 
selected out of 84 available in the visible and near infrared range 
(from 440 to 850&nbsp;nm).
<P>
<DT><STRONG>Shuttle Imaging Radar-C (SIR-C)</STRONG>
<DD>
SIR-C is part of the Shuttle Imaging Radar-C/X-Synthetic Aperture 
Radar (SIR-C/X-SAR) joint project of the National Aeronautics and 
Space Administration (NASA), the
Italian Space Agency (ASI), and  the German Space Agency (DARA).
SIR-C/X-SAR is the
next step in a series of spaceborne imaging radars, beginning 
with Seasta in 1978 and continuing with SIR-A (1981), 
Germany's Microwave Remote Sensing Experiment (1983),
and SIR-B (1984). It is the precursor of the Earth Observing 
System (EOS) SAR and Global Topography Mission (GTM) planned for 
later in this decade.
The SIR-C antenna is developed by the Jet Propulsion 
Laboratory (JPL) and the Ball Communication Systems Division for NASA and is a 
two-frequency radar including L-band (23&nbsp;cm wavelength) and C-band
(6&nbsp;cm wavelength) with four polarizations. Two
SIR-C/X-SAR missions on board the space shuttle
Endeavour were organized in
1994. During the first mission (STS-59), SAR data were collected
over the Zwalm
catchment on April 10 and 11. The second mission (STS-68) 
was planned for August but
was delayed considerably. Images were collected over the Zwalm catchment 
on October 1 and 2.
<P>
