 <A NAME="tex2html476" HREF="node27.html"><IMG WIDTH=37 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="next" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/next_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME="tex2html474" HREF="node24.html"><IMG WIDTH=26 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="up" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/up_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME="tex2html468" HREF="node25.html"><IMG WIDTH=63 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="previous" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/previous_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME="tex2html478" HREF="node1.html"><IMG WIDTH=65 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="contents" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/contents_motif.gif"></A>  <BR>
<B> Next:</B> <A NAME="tex2html477" HREF="node27.html">Hydrologic and Meteorologic Data </A>
<B>Up:</B> <A NAME="tex2html475" HREF="node24.html">Ground Truth Data Collection</A>
<B> Previous:</B> <A NAME="tex2html469" HREF="node25.html">Soil Moisture</A>
<BR> <P>
<H3><A NAME="SECTION00053200000000000000">Surface Roughness</A></H3>
<P>
Information about surface roughness is essential in order to infer 
soil moisture data from radar backscattering values&nbsp;[<A HREF="node63.html#eo94"><EM>Bolognani and Altese, </EM><EM>Bolognani and
  Altese</EM><EM>1994</EM></A>]. 
Surface roughness characteristics are described by the root mean 
square (rms) height difference <I>s</I> from a given datum,
the correlation length <I>l</I>, and the correlation function.
The method used during the field campaigns to estimate these three 
variables is the following: a gridded thin metal plate of length 
1&nbsp;m is introduced into the ground; then a photographic slide is
taken showing the ground surface intersection with the gridded 
plate. From this trace the rms <I>s</I> values, correlation length, 
and correlation function can be calculated after manual digitalization.
The advantage of this system is that it is portable and easy to use. 
The main disadvantages are that it is time consuming and gives 
low spatial coverage (only 1&nbsp;m along one
direction is observed). This last flaw is overcome by taking many slides 
at different locations in the field.
<P>
<BR> <HR>
<P><ADDRESS>
<I>Bart Cosyn <BR>
Thu Jul 25 13:19:15 MDT 1996</I>
