 <A NAME="tex2html487" HREF="node28.html"><IMG WIDTH=37 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="next" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/next_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME="tex2html485" HREF="node24.html"><IMG WIDTH=26 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="up" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/up_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME="tex2html479" HREF="node26.html"><IMG WIDTH=63 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="previous" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/previous_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME="tex2html489" HREF="node1.html"><IMG WIDTH=65 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="contents" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/contents_motif.gif"></A>  <BR>
<B> Next:</B> <A NAME="tex2html488" HREF="node28.html">Vegetation Characteristics</A>
<B>Up:</B> <A NAME="tex2html486" HREF="node24.html">Ground Truth Data Collection</A>
<B> Previous:</B> <A NAME="tex2html480" HREF="node26.html">Surface Roughness</A>
<BR> <P>
<A NAME="bowen">&#160;</A><H3><A NAME="SECTION00053300000000000000">Hydrologic and Meteorologic Data </A></H3>
<P>
The permanent hydrologic data acquisition network described in 
section&nbsp;<A HREF="node19.html#logging">2.3.2</A> observes the most important hydrologic 
and meteorologic variables, 
such as rainfall, evaporation, and streamflow. 
During the various remote sensing 
campaigns, micro-meteorologic stations (Bowen ratio
stations) and eddy correlation stations were mounted in the two 
subcatchments. These stations yield very detailed energy flux measurements 
at the field scale. This allows the determination of actual evapotranspiration 
over the field.
<P>
The Bowen ratio method is a technique for partitioning the energy 
budget to determine evaporation. The energy budget for a surface can 
be written as
<P> <IMG WIDTH=500 HEIGHT=20 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="equation1703" SRC="img26.gif"  > <P>
where  <IMG WIDTH=22 HEIGHT=28 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="tex2html_wrap_inline2873" SRC="img27.gif"  >  is the net radiation for the surface, 
<I>G</I> is the rate of storage of heat in the soil or water, <I>H</I> is the 
flux of sensible heat and  <IMG WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=14 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="tex2html_wrap_inline2879" SRC="img28.gif"  >  is the latent heat flux due 
to evaporation.
Provided certain conditions are met with regard to the siting and 
exposure of the measuring equipment, the latent heat flux can be estimated 
from
<P> <IMG WIDTH=500 HEIGHT=45 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="equation1705" SRC="img29.gif"  > <P>
where  <IMG WIDTH=12 HEIGHT=29 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="tex2html_wrap_inline2881" SRC="img30.gif"  >  is the Bowen ratio, defined as
<P> <IMG WIDTH=500 HEIGHT=41 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="equation1709" SRC="img31.gif"  > <P>
Practically,  <IMG WIDTH=12 HEIGHT=29 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="tex2html_wrap_inline2881" SRC="img30.gif"  >  can be estimated from
<P> <IMG WIDTH=500 HEIGHT=44 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="equation1713" SRC="img32.gif"  > <P>
where  <IMG WIDTH=11 HEIGHT=18 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="tex2html_wrap_inline2885" SRC="img33.gif"  >  is the psychrometric constant, 
 <IMG WIDTH=17 HEIGHT=28 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="tex2html_wrap_inline2887" SRC="img34.gif"  >  and  <IMG WIDTH=17 HEIGHT=28 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="tex2html_wrap_inline2889" SRC="img35.gif"  >  are air temperature 
and  <IMG WIDTH=14 HEIGHT=18 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="tex2html_wrap_inline2891" SRC="img36.gif"  >  and  <IMG WIDTH=14 HEIGHT=18 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="tex2html_wrap_inline2893" SRC="img37.gif"  >  are vapour pressure at two different 
levels  <IMG WIDTH=14 HEIGHT=18 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="tex2html_wrap_inline2895" SRC="img38.gif"  >  and  <IMG WIDTH=14 HEIGHT=18 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="tex2html_wrap_inline2897" SRC="img39.gif"  > .
The Bowen ratio system allows accurate measurements of the 
temperature and vapour pressure differences at two heights in the boundary 
layer. These are sufficient to determine  <IMG WIDTH=12 HEIGHT=29 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="tex2html_wrap_inline2881" SRC="img30.gif"  >  and hence calculate
 <IMG WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=14 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="tex2html_wrap_inline2879" SRC="img28.gif"  >  from additional measurements of net radiation and soil heat flux.
<P>
The portable Bowen ratio system used by LHWM
during the various campaigns includes all the equipment needed for 
routine and
automatic estimation of surface evaporation. Measurements of air temperature,
relative humidity, soil heat flux, average soil temperature, net 
radiation, wind speed, wind direction,
and precipitation are made at regular intervals and the recording 
and subsequent calculations are carried out by a Campbell 
Scientific (CS) 21X Micrologger. The stored data can
subsequently be transferred to a PC for further analysis.
<P>
Two aspirated psychrometers (Vector Instruments H301) are supported on 
two arms which in turn are mounted on a tripod and mast. 
The height of the arms can be adjusted between 0.5 and 3&nbsp;m. 
These psychrometers deliver dry and wet bulb temperature values which can 
be used to calculate the Bowen ratio. The additional terms of the energy 
balance are measured using the CS Q-6 net radiometer, 
two CS HFT soil heat flux plates burried in
the soil at approximately 10&nbsp;cm depth, and four averaging soil 
temperature probes. The soil
heat flux plates measure the heat flux by responding to the 
temperature difference between
the upper and lower surface of the plates. The average soil 
temperature in the soil layer above the plates is measured to 
correct for energy storage. All of these variables are measured 
every 10 seconds and the average value is stored every 10 minutes.
<P>
These instruments were deployed in the field during three campaigns,
April 4-12, June 15-July 5 and August 10-October 10, 1994: 
<UL><LI> During the first Zwalm campaign, the Bowen ratio 
system was positioned in the subcatchment of the Passemarebeek
on a bare soil field
at  <IMG WIDTH=77 HEIGHT=16 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="tex2html_wrap_inline2903" SRC="img40.gif"  > &nbsp;N  <IMG WIDTH=68 HEIGHT=16 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="tex2html_wrap_inline2905" SRC="img41.gif"  > &nbsp;E. Values of net radiation, ground heat flux, 
average soil temperature, and wet and dry bulb temperature
at two levels were stored every 10 minutes.<LI> During the second campaign, 
the Bowen ratio system was positioned in the subcatchment of the 
Sassegembeek at  <IMG WIDTH=77 HEIGHT=16 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="tex2html_wrap_inline2907" SRC="img42.gif"  > &nbsp;N  <IMG WIDTH=68 HEIGHT=16 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="tex2html_wrap_inline2909" SRC="img43.gif"  > &nbsp;E on a sugar beet field.
Values of net radiation, ground heat flux, average soil 
temperature, wet and dry bulb
temperature at two levels, wind speed, and wind direction were 
stored every 20 minutes.<LI> During the third campaign, the Bowen ratio system
was positioned in the subcatchment of the Passemarebeek
in a pasture field at  <IMG WIDTH=77 HEIGHT=16 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="tex2html_wrap_inline2911" SRC="img44.gif"  > &nbsp;N  <IMG WIDTH=68 HEIGHT=16 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="tex2html_wrap_inline2913" SRC="img45.gif"  > &nbsp;E. Values of net radiation, 
ground heat flux, average soil temperature, wet and dry
bulb temperature at two levels, wind speed, wind direction, and 
precipitation were stored every 10 minutes.
</UL>
During the first and third campaigns 
additional stations (Bowen ratio and eddy correlation) from the 
University of Basel were also positioned in the catchment.
<P>
