<B>Up:</B> <A NAME="tex2html609" HREF="node34.html">The Use of GRASS</A>
<B> Previous:</B> <A NAME="tex2html603" HREF="node37.html">The GRASS File Structure</A>
<BR> <P>
<H2><A NAME="SECTION00064000000000000000">GRASS from the Shell</A></H2>
<P>
One of the powerful aspects of GRASS is the ability to run all commands
from a regular C-shell. Starting GRASS invokes a subshell of your main shell.
At login GRASS asks you which database (mapset and location) you want
to access. If you name a nonexistent mapset or location GRASS will
create a new one asking you to supply the characteristics of this new mapset. 
Creating a new location, GRASS will ask you in which coordinate
system you want to work. It will also ask you to define the extreme outer
coordinates of the new mapset. Invoking a new mapset will be done
automatically after confirmation of your intentions. Once this is done
GRASS reads the ``.cshrc'' file in the location and 
afterwards the ``.grass.cshrc'' file
in your home directory.
<P>
The file ``.grass.cshrc'' is a useful way
of setting your environment variables and aliases.
For instance, <code>alias map 'cd \$GISDBASE\$MAPSET\$LOCATION_NAME'</code>
defines the alias ``map'' as a command to change directory to your
database directory. 
As another example, if you get
bored of always having to type <code>d.mon select=iris</code>
to open the display ``iris'',
simply put this command in a script called ``iris''.
These are 
trivial examples of how GRASS is like shell scripting, and can easily be
extended to more complicated scripts. This way of handling the program
allows an easy interface with data from external programs. Reformatting
output files to GRASS files is easy using special software or UNIX scripts
that make use of ``sed'' and ``awk''.
<P>
GRASS stores only two types of
data in binary format: raster array data in the ``cell'' subdirectory and
vector data in the ``dig'' subdirectory. Apart from these two datatypes
everything is readable and easy to manipulate using any editor.
The two datatypes stored in binary have the advantage that they
can be easily imported and exported using GRASS commands such
as ``v.in.ascii'', ``v.out.ascii'', ``r.in.ascii'', and ``r.out.ascii''.
<P>
<HR><A NAME="tex2html610" HREF="node39.html"><IMG WIDTH=37 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="next" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/next_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME="tex2html608" HREF="node34.html"><IMG WIDTH=26 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="up" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/up_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME="tex2html602" HREF="node37.html"><IMG WIDTH=63 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="previous" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/previous_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME="tex2html612" HREF="node1.html"><IMG WIDTH=65 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="contents" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/contents_motif.gif"></A>  <BR>
