<HEAD>
<TITLE>How to Start Up GRASS</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="How to Start Up GRASS">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="paper">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">
<LINK REL=STYLESHEET HREF="paper.css">
</HEAD>
<BODY LANG="EN">
 <A NAME="tex2html619" HREF="node40.html"><IMG WIDTH=37 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="next" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/next_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME="tex2html617" HREF="node34.html"><IMG WIDTH=26 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="up" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/up_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME="tex2html613" HREF="node38.html"><IMG WIDTH=63 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="previous" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/previous_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME="tex2html621" HREF="node1.html"><IMG WIDTH=65 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="contents" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/contents_motif.gif"></A>  <BR>
<B> Next:</B> <A NAME="tex2html620" HREF="node40.html">Projection Systems and Transformations</A>
<B>Up:</B> <A NAME="tex2html618" HREF="node34.html">The Use of GRASS</A>
<B> Previous:</B> <A NAME="tex2html614" HREF="node38.html">GRASS from the Shell</A>
<BR> <P>
<H2><A NAME="SECTION00065000000000000000">How to Start Up GRASS</A></H2>
<P>
Some of the instructions given here are specific to the GRASS setup
at CRS4. For more general information see the reference and beginner's
manuals&nbsp;[<A HREF="node63.html#grassref93"><EM>CERL, </EM><EM>CERL</EM><EM>1993</EM>b</A>, <A HREF="node63.html#grassbeg93"><EM>Van&nbsp;Leusen, </EM><EM>Van&nbsp;Leusen</EM><EM>
  1993</EM></A>].
<P>
Preparing your terminal and login shells:
<DL ><DT><STRONG>.grass.cshrc</STRONG>
<DD>
If you do not have a ``.grass.cshrc'' file, you can create one by copying
and modifying the one in directory ``/usr/people/grass'' on workstation
``saturn''<A NAME="tex2html16" HREF="footnode.html#1986"><IMG  ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="gif" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/foot_motif.gif"></A>.
<DT><STRONG>DISPLAY</STRONG>
<DD>
Before starting GRASS you need to set your DISPLAY environment variable.
Due to the fact that the current version of
GRASS has problems restoring the display after
overwriting an X-display, it may be useful to use a second terminal for
visualization.
<P>
 </DL>
<P>
GRASS and X-GRASS are started up using the
commands ``grass4.1'' and ``xgrass4.1'', respectively.
At startup you will be asked to define the database, location, and mapset
to use. Care must be taken of UNIX permissions in GRASS. You can
only enter a mapset if you are the owner of the mapset. If you are in the
same location and the location is writable you can read the data of another
location and user but all resulting files are written to your current
location. Some programs will not work when you need to write a file in the
location where the data reside.
<P>
A display is opened using the commands ``d.mon start=x0'' and
``d.mon select=x0''.
There are 14 displays available: 12 X-displays (``x1''-``x12'') that 
can be exported to any machine running X-windows, 1 display (``iris'') 
for use only on a Silicon Graphics, and the CELL display (``CELL'').
There are a few points to keep in mind when working with displays:
<UL><LI> Using the ``g.region'' command
  you can define the working area. Your display connects
  the relative coordinates starting from the left upper corner (0-100) to
  absolute coordinates. To use a new region you must first erase your display.<LI> Changing the dimensions of the display automatically erases your
  display, or in the case or ``iris'' deselects it.<LI> Most of the ``d.mon'' functions are contained in scripts located in
  the directory
  ``/usr/people/grass/shells''. The scripts ``s0''-``s12'' and ``siris'' 
  start the monitors, ``x0''-``x12'' and ``iris'' select the monitors,
  and ``stop0''-``stop12'' and ``stopiris'' stop the monitors.<LI> The CELL display is not an actual display but an image dump.
  You can start up the CELL display and select it like all other
  displays, but nothing will appear on your screen. You can display raster and
  vector data and use any other display command. Upon stopping the 
  CELL display, a raster file called ``D_cell'' is created,
  which can be displayed as a regular raster file on one of the visual
  displays. In addition, this raster file can be exported using
  ``r.out.ppm'' or similar modules.
  These files can be handled using the ``pbmplus'' conversion package 
  that is compiled with GRASS.
</UL>
<P>
The names of GRASS modules and commands are quite logical.
The first character (usually followed by
a ``.'') is assigned according to task or type of data. All module
and command files reside in subdirectory ``$HOME/Grass4.1/bin''.
<DL ><DT><STRONG>d.</STRONG>
<DD> Display functions; output the screen; sometimes interactive by use
            of the mouse;
  <DT><STRONG>g.</STRONG>
<DD> General management functions; listing and searching in files;
  <DT><STRONG>i.</STRONG>
<DD> Image processing modules;
  <DT><STRONG>m.</STRONG>
<DD> Data processing modules; conversion and reading of typical
            datatypes;
  <DT><STRONG>p. and ps.</STRONG>
<DD> Paint and print modules to external output;
  <DT><STRONG>r.</STRONG>
<DD> Raster oriented modules;
  <DT><STRONG>s.</STRONG>
<DD> Site oriented modules;
  <DT><STRONG>v.</STRONG>
<DD> Vector oriented modules;
  <DT><STRONG>x...</STRONG>
<DD> xgrass4.1 modules.
<P>
 </DL>
<P>
Shells written for your own purposes are best placed in your ``bin'' directory
or in some other directory accessible through your path settings. 
More general
scripts will be put in ``$HOME/shells'' by the local GRASS administator.
These are accessible to anyone working in GRASS
because this path is added to the user's path settings at login.
A list of available shells can be found in Appendix&nbsp;A.
<P>
