<H2><A NAME="SECTION00071000000000000000">GRASS and Transformations</A></H2>
<P>
GRASS is mainly developed in the U.S., and provides only limited
utilities for conversion from one geographic projection to another.
GRASS asks the user to work either in UTM coordinates or in
non-projected Geographic coordinates. 
These two coordinate systems are fully supported.
Use of other (e.g., European) standardized systems
generally requires user-written programs in combination with 
GRASS modules in order to be able to 
transfer files from one projection to another.
<P>
In this chapter we give an overview of the projection system 
and transformation utilities used in GRASS for the Zwalm catchment.
We start with a brief introduction
to the usual projection system for Belgium.
A good knowledge of the projection systems to be used in an application 
is a basic part of setting up a GIS. 
Before setting up a GIS, it is useful to collect all 
necessary information about the projections of the various input data
(maps, images, external data, etc.).
<P>
<BR> <HR>
<P><ADDRESS>
<I>Bart Cosyn <BR>
Thu Jul 25 13:19:15 MDT 1996</I>
