<BR> <P>
<H3><A NAME="SECTION00072100000000000000">Reference Systems</A></H3>
<P>
Three-dimensional positioning of a point on Earth is defined by two reference 
systems:
<DL ><DT><STRONG>Planimetric reference system</STRONG>
<DD>
  Defined by a mathematical model of
  the Earth (i.e., convolution ellipsoid) attached to a three-axis system. 	
  Each point on earth is planimetrical, defined 
  by two coordinates  <IMG WIDTH=44 HEIGHT=30 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="tex2html_wrap_inline2937" SRC="img51.gif"  > . The system 
  is defined by the form and the dimensions of the ellipse (excentricity 
  <I>e</I> and the big half axis <I>a</I>) and the orientation 
  of the mathematical ellipse in the physical model of the Earth. The
  orientation of the ellipse and the corresponding axes depends 
  on local reference points. For local or national reference systems the
  center of the ellipse does not coincide with the middle mass point of the
  Earth. Generally a local point is chosen where the 
  mathematical and physical models coincide. The orientation of the 
  ellipse is determined by some geo-astrodetical points.
<P>
  <DT><STRONG>Altimetric reference system</STRONG>
<DD>
  Defined by a physical model of the Earth
  (i.e., equipotential plane). The altimetric coordinate of a point on Earth 
  is given by the altitude of the point according to the reference plane. 
  The choice of reference plane is usually determined by the average sea level 
  in a country or a by fixed point. The equipotential plane going 
  through this point is considered as the 0-level.
<P>
 </DL>
Until recently locally-defined systems were commonly used,
but the advent of satellite remote sensing has encouraged the use of
internationally accepted reference systems.
<P>
<BR> <HR>
<P><ADDRESS>
<I>Bart Cosyn <BR>
Thu Jul 25 13:19:15 MDT 1996</I>
