 <A NAME="tex2html959" HREF="node69.html"><IMG WIDTH=37 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="next" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/next_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME="tex2html957" HREF="node65.html"><IMG WIDTH=26 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="up" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/up_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME="tex2html951" HREF="node67.html"><IMG WIDTH=63 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="previous" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/previous_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME="tex2html961" HREF="node1.html"><IMG WIDTH=65 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="contents" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/contents_motif.gif"></A>  <BR>
<B> Next:</B> <A NAME="tex2html960" HREF="node69.html">Compile Notes for IRIX </A>
<B>Up:</B> <A NAME="tex2html958" HREF="node65.html">Appendix B: Compiling GRASS</A>
<B> Previous:</B> <A NAME="tex2html952" HREF="node67.html">Compiling GRASS4.1</A>
<BR> <P>
<H2><A NAME="SECTION000113000000000000000">Compiling New Modules and Updating</A></H2>
<P>
Often there are new modules contributed by third parties, announced
on the GRASS mailing lists and newsgroups.
Obtain the source (usually an archived
file) from the network and ``tar'' or ``cpio'' the files. It is convenient
to keep contributed software in a common directory, for instance
``$GISBASE/src.contrib/OTHERS''.
In the best scenario, running ``gmake4.1'' 
should be the only thing to do. Of course
it is also advisable to read any documentation supplied with
the software too. If compilation was successful,
run ``sh MAKELINKS.$ARCH'' to link all the new executables to 
the directory where all
GRASS binaries reside. If compilation errors occur, check for bad links
or undefinded directories, which can be resolved by editing 
the makefile or Gmakefile. If still not successful, post a message to
the mailing list or newsgroup.
<P>
Release updates are well organized and come with thorough documentation
in the form of ``README'' files, and often with an appropriate shell 
script to perform the entire installation.
<P>
<BR> <HR>
