<BODY VLINK="#ff0000" LINK="ffff00" bgcolor="42426f" TEXT="ffffff">
<h1> GIS systems </h1> <HR>
<h2> <a href="http://www.intergraph.com/index.html"> Intergraph </a> </h2> <HR>
<h2> <a href= "http://www.cecer.army.mil/grass/"> Grass </a> </h2>
<h3>What is GRASS ?</h3>
The geographical resources analysis support system (GRASS)
is a geographic information system developed by the U.S. Army's
Construction Engineering Research Laboratories (USA-CERL). GRASS can be
used for preparing geographical data obtained from other systems, for
processing and analyzing geographical data, and for
basic visualization of geographical data.
For some of these jobs,
functionality from other public domain software packages
(for example RIM, gnuplot, gctp and PBMplus) is used.
Scripts can be written for well defined jobs that need be
performed repeatedly. <p>

The current version is GRASS4.1 and is available in the public
domain. On the server where GRASS resides one can also find
tutorials, manuals, and references, both from the GRASS developers and from
people currently working with the system.
GRASS is used world wide, and the user base includes
programmers who create new GRASS modules to perform additional functionality.
New modules and new releases of old modules are posted on the GRASS server. <p>

GRASS handles data in raster, vector and point format and is primarily intended
to work with UTM coordinates. The main limitation is that the system
only supports processing of data at one of the 60 UTM
zones at a time.
It also handles Geographic coordinates in a
limited way (some tools do not accept this projection). <p>

GRASS is often used as an exchange GIS system and includes basic conversions
to other GIS formats. Because of the way UNIX shells and environment
variables are used, it is easy for the user to
set the environment according the needs of each project separately.
Although GRASS is command line driven and somewhat user unfriendly,
it has the advantage of being easily linked with locally created programs. <p>

<h3> How to Introduce Yourself to GRASS </h3>
GRASS contains a large amount of tutorial data and there are many
helpful sites (mailing lists, World Wide Web sites, etc.) to
introduce people to GRASS. 
<dl>
<dt> [GRASS users list]:  <p>
    A mailing list to which
    GRASS users can post any questions on compiling, using,
    and adapting GRASS to their needs. The address of the mailing list 
    is grassu-list@moon.cecer.army.mil; <p>
<dt>[GRASS newsgroup] <p>
    For those who have access to a news server, the
    contents of the GRASS users list are available in
    [news:info.grass.user] and
    [news:listserv.grass.user] <p>
<dt>[World Wide Web (WWW)] <p>
    GRASS has a 
    <a href= "http://www.cecer.army.mil/grass/GRASS.main.html"> [http://www.cecer.army.mil/grass/GRASS.main.html] </a>
    on WWW. 
</dl> <p>

For true novices to GRASS or for handling new modules in GRASS it is
advisable to start by using X-GRASS. 
As X-GRASS is not yet completely alpha tested it is likewise not advisable
to use X-GRASS for more advanced work.
<HR>
<h3> Implementation of Grass for our test site: <a href="/members/bart/paper/paper.html"> <blink>The Zwalm catchment. </blink> </a></h3> <HR>
At LHWM Grass runs on 2 platforms. First Grass was compiled for <a HREF="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/~bart/paper/node69.html">Silicon Graphics (Irix5.2 and Irix 5.3) </a> and recently Grass was compiled on <a href="sun.txt">Sun </a>. 
<HR>
<h3> Grass related sites </h3>
    <DL><p>
        <DT><A HREF="http://www.cecer.army.mil/grass/GRASS.main.html" ADD_DATE="
782158272" LAST_VISIT="806569757">GRASS info</A>
        <DT><A HREF="http://soils.ecn.purdue.edu/~mccauley/grassu/" ADD_DATE="79
