<h1> Spatial and Temporal Variability of Evapotranspiration
by means of a water and energy balance model </a></h1> <HR>

<b>
Luc Debruyckere <p>
Laboratory of Hydrology and Water management <p>
University of Ghent, Belgium </b> <HR>

<h2>Abstract</h2>

The recent developments in the field of remote sensing have resulted in applications in a
wide range of scientific disciplines. One of the appealing applications of this technique is
the study of the soil moisture content at the regional scale and its effect on regional
evapotranspiration. It has become apparent that remote sensing techniques can provide
spatially integrated surface parameters to study the surface-atmosphere processes from a
regional perspective. <p>

The objective of this research is to derive information about the spatial variability of
evapotranspiration at the regional scale using satellite observations, in combination with a
statistical-dynamic hydrologic modelling approach.
Obtaining reliable and representative ground-based measurements of evapotranspiration at
the regional scale remains an unsolved problem. As a result of satellite remote sensing,
evaluation of regional evapotranspiration can now be made by combining the remote
sensing data with ground-based meteorological measurements. In combination with
conventional ground-based meteorological measurements, remote sensing observations
have the advantage of providing spatially representative values of some parameters needed
for modelling evapotranspiration. <p>

The approach used in this study is based on a simple Soil-Vegetation-Atmosphere Transfer
Scheme (SVATS). Local hydrological fluxes are modelled by coupling simple
representations of atmospheric forcing, vertical soil moisture transport and plant control of
transpiration. The model is computationally efficient, yet detailed enough to capture the
essential physics of hydrologic response at the land-atmosphere interface. <p>

A geographic information system (GIS) approach is used to aggregate the local physical
processes to the catchment scale. The local model is applied at each grid element of a
spatially-distributed hydrological balance model where spatial variability in atmospheric
forcing and soil and vegetation properties are represented explicitly, leading to spatial
variability in the modelled water and energy fluxes. <p>

Finally, a macroscale hydrological model is used where spatial-variable hydrologic process
controls are represented statistically. The local model is aggregated to this regional model
to yield a statistical representation of the variability in the water and energy fluxes. <p>
------ <p>
Keywords: Hydrology, Meteorology, Evapotranspiration <p>
------ <p>
Acknowledgement:
This research is financed with a specialization grant of the Flemish Institute for the
Promotion of Scientific Technological Research in Industry (IWT, Belgium) <p>
<p> <HR>
<a href="/~luc">Back</a> to Luc's homepage
