<B>Up:</B> <A NAME="tex2html283" HREF="node9.html">Description of the Site</A>
<B> Previous:</B> <A NAME="tex2html277" HREF="node9.html">Description of the Site</A>
<BR> <P>
<H3><A NAME="SECTION00041100000000000000">Physical Characteristics of the Zwalm Catchment</A></H3>
<P>
The drainage divide of the Zwalmbeek expands 
from  <IMG WIDTH=78 HEIGHT=16 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="tex2html_wrap_inline2767" SRC="img1.gif"  > &nbsp;N to  <IMG WIDTH=78 HEIGHT=16 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="tex2html_wrap_inline2769" SRC="img2.gif"  > &nbsp;N
latitude and  <IMG WIDTH=69 HEIGHT=16 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="tex2html_wrap_inline2771" SRC="img3.gif"  > &nbsp;E to  <IMG WIDTH=69 HEIGHT=16 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="tex2html_wrap_inline2773" SRC="img4.gif"  > &nbsp;E longitude 
(Figure&nbsp;<A HREF="node10.html#zwalmps">1</A>). The Zwalmbeek is a
tributary of the Schelde river. The Zwalm catchment is situated in
the province of EAST-Flanders. The outlet of the basin is situated south of
Gent near the village Nederzwalm. The total 
drainage area is 114&nbsp;km <IMG WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=9 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="tex2html_wrap_inline2775" SRC="img5.gif"  >  and the total
length of perennial streams is estimated from topographic maps, 
scale 1:10000, to be 177
km. Therefore, the drainage density is 1.55&nbsp;km/km <IMG WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=9 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="tex2html_wrap_inline2775" SRC="img5.gif"  > , 
a value characteristic for humid
catchments. The topography of the basin is characterized by 
rolling hills and mild slopes.
The maximal elevation difference in the basin is 150&nbsp;m. The mean slope of first
order streams (Strahler order) is 3.8&nbsp;%. 
The catchment is situated in the sandy-loam area
of Flanders (Belgian nomenclature). The Belgian soilmap 
(scale 1:20000) shows that
almost 80&nbsp;% of the surface consists of deep loam soils (A-texture) but 
individual sampling [<A HREF="node63.html#patroch93"><EM>Troch, </EM><EM>Troch</EM><EM>1993</EM></A>] has shown that most of the top layer 
of the soil profile has sandy loam
texture. The depth of this eolic cover is estimated to 
range between 0 and 10&nbsp;m.
<P>
Climatic conditions can be described as humid temperate. 
The mean yearly rainfall is 775&nbsp;mm and is distributed 
almost uniformly over the year. Most of the land use is agriculture
(arable crops and permanent pasture) but the south of the catchment is
forested (Brakel-bos). The degree of urbanization is about 10&nbsp;% with 
urbanized areas mainly situated in the Northeast (Zottegem) 
and Southeast (Brakel).
<P><A NAME="1583">&#160;</A><A NAME="zwalmps">&#160;</A><A NAME="tex2htmlfigure1581" HREF="img6.gif"><IMG WIDTH=103 HEIGHT=125 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="figure1580" SRC="Timg6.gif"></A><BR>
<STRONG>Figure 1:</STRONG> The Zwalm catchment.<BR>
<P><BR> <HR>
<P><ADDRESS>
<I>Bart Cosyn <BR>
Thu Jul 25 13:19:15 MDT 1996</I>
