<B> Previous:</B> <A NAME="tex2html377" HREF="node18.html">History</A>
<BR> <P>
<A NAME="logging">&#160;</A><H3><A NAME="SECTION00043200000000000000">Quantitative Hydrologic Data </A></H3>
<P>
The main monitoring network consists of 10 
permanent logging stations (see Figure&nbsp;<A HREF="node10.html#zwalmps">1</A>). 
In Table&nbsp;<A HREF="node19.html#station">1</A> the different stations are listed along with their
<I>X</I> and <I>Y</I> coordinates in the Lambert72 and UTM projections. The codes
used in this report are codes given to the stations in the database 
HYMOS at LHWM<A NAME="tex2html5" HREF="footnode.html#1616"><IMG  ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="gif" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/foot_motif.gif"></A>. 
HYMOS is a hydrologic database software package, 
developed by Delft Hydraulics (Holland),
and is used at LWHM for managing all the data of the
monitoring network. For file transfer the data files are 
converted to ascii format. The database software includes 
utilities for resampling of data, conversion from
waterlevels to discharge rates, evaluation of calibration curves, elementary
calculation of evapotranspiration, and calculation of the spatial distribution
of the data.
<P><A NAME="1618">&#160;</A><A NAME="station">&#160;</A> <IMG WIDTH=555 HEIGHT=294 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="table1617" SRC="img8.gif"  > <BR>
<STRONG>Table 1:</STRONG> Permanent Logging Stations at the Zwalm Catchment and Their
           UTM and Lambert72 Coordinates<BR>
<P>
<P>
<P><A NAME="1634">&#160;</A><A NAME="datatypes">&#160;</A> <IMG WIDTH=613 HEIGHT=411 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="table1633" SRC="img9.gif"  > <BR>
<STRONG>Table 2:</STRONG> Overview of Data Measured at the Permanent Logging Stations
           (A=Accumulated, I=Instantaneous)<BR>
<P>
<P>
At each of the stations different data are measured. An overview of the 
characteristics of the data is given in Table&nbsp;<A HREF="node19.html#datatypes">2</A>.
The stations and data are described in more detail below:
<DL ><DT><STRONG>100 Elst</STRONG>
<DD>
This station is situated in the the middle west of the 
catchment. It consists of a complete weather station. The station is equipped 
with a digital logger and storing module. The weather station has a 10&nbsp;m high
mast. The raingauge, belonging to the Flemish Administration for the
Environment, is connected with the data logger.
Data logging began in September 1991.
The following data are measured:
Three groundwater piezometers (data codes G1,G2,G3). These are positioned 
500&nbsp;m from the weather station; <BR> 
Air temperature (TP) at 2&nbsp;m above the surface; <BR> 
Relative humidity (RV) at 2&nbsp;m above the surface; <BR> 
Wind direction at 2&nbsp;m (RL); <BR> 
Wind direction at 10&nbsp;m (RH); <BR> 
Wind velocity at 2&nbsp;m (VL); <BR> 
Wind velocity at 10&nbsp;m (VH); <BR> 
Incoming radiation at 2&nbsp;m  (RI); <BR> 
Reflected radiation at 2&nbsp;m (RO); <BR> 
Precipitation (PR).
<P>
<DT><STRONG>101 Neder</STRONG>
<DD>
This station is situated near the catchment outlet, 
positioned 200&nbsp;m from the actual
outlet of the Zwalm in the Schelde river. Waterlevels are monitored and
stored in digital format and on paper. In this way loss of data is
minimized. From time to time water velocity measurements and profile data 
are taken in order to calibrate the limnigraph. These data allow
calculation of flow discharges. This procedure is executed repeatedly under
different conditions so that a best fitting curve can be found to evaluate
discharge from the continuously monitored water levels.
Water quality is also continuously monitored (see section&nbsp;<A HREF="node20.html#qual">2.3.3</A>).
Measured parameters are:
Waterlevel (WL), with derived discharges (DC); <BR> 
Three groundwater piezometers (G1,G2,G3); <BR> 
Water quality data.
<P>
<DT><STRONG>102 Mater</STRONG>
<DD>
This station is situated several hundred meters upstream of Peerdestok creek. 
The creek is situated in the eastern part
of the catchment. This limnigraph records the
data in the same way as 101 Neder. Data are stored digitally as well as on
paper. No piezometers are connected as yet.
Waterlevel (WL), with derived discharges (DC).
<P>
<DT><STRONG>103 Francis</STRONG>
<DD>
This station is similar to the other limnigraphs. It is situated in
Michelbeke upstream of the Zwalmbeek. In this part of the catchment slopes
become significantly steeper than in the northern part.
Waterlevel (WL), with derived discharges (DC); <BR> 
Three groundwater piezometers (G1,G2,G3).
<P>
<DT><STRONG>104 Velzeke</STRONG>
<DD>
This is the first of 5 raingauges. The raingauges are of tipping bucket type.
The data collected are accumulated during a period of 10 minutes. The bucket
empties after collecting 0.2&nbsp;mm of rainfall. This station is situated in
the Passemare subcatchment.
Precipitation (PR).
<P>
<DT><STRONG>105 Blasius</STRONG>
<DD> 
This station is situated between the Peerdestokbeek and the Zwalmbeek in the
northern part of the catchment. 
Precipitation (PR); <BR> 
Three groundwater piezometers (G1,G2,G3).
<P>
<DT><STRONG>106 Beren</STRONG>
<DD>
This station is situated in the central-eastern part of the catchment.
Precipitation (PR).
<P>
<DT><STRONG>107 Schor</STRONG>
<DD>
This station is situated in the southwestern part of the catchment, close
to the Sassegem subcatchment.
Precipitation (PR).
<P>
<DT><STRONG>MFopbrakel</STRONG>
<DD>
This is the first of two flumes. These flumes are constructed and
calibrated in the Laboratory of Hydraulics at the University of Gent.
The calibration curve to derive discharges from waterlevels
is known. The data are continuously registered on paper. These
plots are changed every week and digitized in the lab. 
This station is situated at the outlet of the
Sassegem beek in the southern part of the catchment.
Waterlevel (WL), with derived discharges (DC).
<P>
<DT><STRONG>MFvelzeke</STRONG>
<DD>
This flume is situated at the outlet of the
Passemare beek in the northern part of the catchment.
Waterlevel (WL), with derived discharges (DC).
<P>
 </DL><HR><A NAME="tex2html384" HREF="node20.html"><IMG WIDTH=37 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="next" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/next_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME="tex2html382" HREF="node17.html"><IMG WIDTH=26 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="up" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/up_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME="tex2html376" HREF="node18.html"><IMG WIDTH=63 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="previous" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/previous_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME="tex2html386" HREF="node1.html"><IMG WIDTH=65 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="contents" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/contents_motif.gif"></A>  <BR>
<B> Next:</B> <A NAME="tex2html385" HREF="node20.html">Qualitative Hydrologic Data </A>
<B>Up:</B> <A NAME="tex2html383" HREF="node17.html">Time Dependent Data: Continuous </A>
<B> Previous:</B> <A NAME="tex2html377" HREF="node18.html">History</A>
