<B> Previous:</B> <A NAME="tex2html680" HREF="node43.html">Reference Systems</A>
<BR> <P>
<H3><A NAME="SECTION00072200000000000000">Map Projections</A></H3>
<P>
Geodetical, planimetric coordinates  <IMG WIDTH=44 HEIGHT=30 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="tex2html_wrap_inline2937" SRC="img51.gif"  >  are widely used 
for sea and air navigation but impractical for science and cartography. 
Geodetic coordinates are therefore transformed
to a flat projection in a plane. The coordinates  <IMG WIDTH=44 HEIGHT=30 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="tex2html_wrap_inline2937" SRC="img51.gif"  >  have to
be projected to plane (<I>X</I>,<I>Y</I>) coordinates. The transformation from an ellipsoid 
to a plane is done through intermediate projections on an aid plane. 
Possible options are:
<UL><LI> cylindrical projections;<LI> conical projections;<LI> azimuth projections.
</UL>
The intermediate projection determines the possible distortions.
<UL><LI> conformic projections: angles are maintained, areas are changed;<LI> equivalent projections: areas are maintained, angles are changed. 
</UL><BR> <HR>
<P><ADDRESS>
<I>Bart Cosyn <BR>
Thu Jul 25 13:19:15 MDT 1996</I>
