<BODY LANG="EN">
 <A NAME="tex2html752" HREF="node51.html"><IMG WIDTH=37 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="next" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/next_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME="tex2html750" HREF="node48.html"><IMG WIDTH=26 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="up" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/up_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME="tex2html744" HREF="node49.html"><IMG WIDTH=63 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="previous" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/previous_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME="tex2html754" HREF="node1.html"><IMG WIDTH=65 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="contents" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/contents_motif.gif"></A>  <BR>
<B> Next:</B> <A NAME="tex2html753" HREF="node51.html">Transformation of Vector Data </A>
<B>Up:</B> <A NAME="tex2html751" HREF="node48.html">GRASS and the Different </A>
<B> Previous:</B> <A NAME="tex2html745" HREF="node49.html">Transformation of Points </A>
<BR> <P>
<H3><A NAME="SECTION00074200000000000000">Transformation of Raster Data in GRASS</A></H3>
<P>
Transformation routines to convert from European (local) to
UTM systems are not standard in GRASS. However, since
GRASS has a fairly open structure, there is a way to get around the
problem of transforming raster data. First, some explanation of
how GRASS data are stored and how GRASS handles raster data
is necessary. The main idea is to georeference the raster data based on a
list of data that is calculated by the program ``coord''. Knowledge about 
the following modules in GRASS is needed&nbsp;[<A HREF="node63.html#grassref93"><EM>CERL, </EM><EM>CERL</EM><EM>1993</EM>b</A>]:
<DL ><DT><STRONG>i.group</STRONG>
<DD> Group identical files in order to rectify them together;
  <DT><STRONG>i.target</STRONG>
<DD> Define a new target location in GRASS;
  <DT><STRONG>i.points</STRONG>
<DD> Georeferencing based on raster data;
  <DT><STRONG>i.vpoints</STRONG>
<DD> Georeferencing based on vector data;
  <DT><STRONG>i.rectify</STRONG>
<DD> Linear rectification program;
  <DT><STRONG>i.rectify2</STRONG>
<DD> Polynomal rectification program;
  <DT><STRONG>r.support</STRONG>
<DD> Building the support files for raster data.
<P>
 </DL>
<P>
Before starting the transformation, ``i.group'' has to be run 
in order to tell GRASS which files you want to convert. It creates a file
called ``POINTS'' in the subdirectory
``$GISDBASE/$MAPSET/$LOCATION_NAME/group/name/''.
GRASS will take the maximum possible region
of the smallest file, so it is suggested that only
files having a similar region of interest are transformed during 
any one session.
The module ``i.target'' must be run in order to define the
target location and mapset of the resulting files. This file can also be
read as ascii, and is accessible.
<P>
Instead of running ``i.points'' or ``i.vpoints'', 
you have to make the file POINTS.
This file can be generated by the program ``coord'' 
by using one of the existing
modules. The program must be run in the same subdirectory where POINTS
resides. The file POINTS has a simple form. It consists of 5 columns 
containing base <I>x</I>,<I>y</I> coordinates and reference <I>x</I>,<I>y</I> coordinates. 
The fifth column is zero if the point is neglected in the 
referencing or one if included. This allows you to build a list of 
reference points for further images. Points used for one
referencing can be used for other referencing. As it is recommended to have 
a well-distributed number of points over the image, 
the value of the last column 
in the POINTS file can be adapted either manually or by using ``i.points'' 
or ``i.vpoints''. Using these interactive and menu driven GRASS modules gives
a better view of the positioning of the points on the images.
This strategy can also be used for converting from Lambert to UTM or
vice versa, and also for referencing from
a row column projection, such as ZWALMrc, to one of the other projections. 
It is important to know the exact coordinates of points in both 
projections<A NAME="tex2html17" HREF="footnode.html#2033"><IMG  ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="gif" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/foot_motif.gif"></A>.
<P>
<HR><A NAME="tex2html752" HREF="node51.html"><IMG WIDTH=37 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="next" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/next_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME="tex2html750" HREF="node48.html"><IMG WIDTH=26 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="up" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/up_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME="tex2html744" HREF="node49.html"><IMG WIDTH=63 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="previous" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/previous_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME="tex2html754" HREF="node1.html"><IMG WIDTH=65 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="contents" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/contents_motif.gif"></A>  <BR>
<B> Next:</B> <A NAME="tex2html753" HREF="node51.html">Transformation of Vector Data </A>
<B>Up:</B> <A NAME="tex2html751" HREF="node48.html">GRASS and the Different </A>
<B> Previous:</B> <A NAME="tex2html745" HREF="node49.html">Transformation of Points </A>
