<BR> <P>
<H2><A NAME="SECTION00082000000000000000">The Different Mapsets, Filenames</A></H2>
<P>
The mapset ``PERMANENT'' is a default mapset of GRASS. The idea is to
put in this mapset time independent (static) data, such as digital
elevation models, the locations of permanent logging stations, digitized
maps, etc.
<P>
The mapset ``IMAGES'' will contain time dependent images and campaign
related data, including ground truth data.
It may become necessary to split this mapset into
different parts, but in any case this mapset can be used to store images
as they become available to CRS4.
<P>
GRASS allows one to look
at other mapsets during a session, but all processed data from the session is
stored in the current mapset. Connecting and disconnecting different mapsets
to eachother can be done via the command ``g.mapsets''.
In order to avoid confusion and to minimize file browsing,
it is recommended to incorporate some information
about a file in the filename extension. The following convention is
suggested:
<DL ><DT><STRONG>.dig</STRONG>
<DD> These are files digitized in vector format and
    transformed to either a GRASS vector format or a GRASS raster format.
<DT><STRONG>.usgs</STRONG>
<DD> Files retrieved through the USGS software and
    tools. The tools are for conversion to different formats and for calculation
    of some useful parameters such as slopes and topographic indices.
<DT><STRONG>.</STRONG>
<DD> Files without an extension are those files which require no
    special processing for importing them into GRASS.
<DT><STRONG>.res</STRONG>
<DD> Rescaled images of the original raster files. These files are
    mainly set up to have a better visualization in GRASS. Some
    applications appear to have problems with widely spread values,
    therefore a resampling up to 64 colors (``d.colormode=float'') or 
    255 colors can
    be needed. Even though reclassifying is not needed, a rescaling of the
    original values to the limits of the color pallette 
    can be helpful. Rescaling does not affect the data,
    but creates a new file that refers to the
    original data. Reclassifying, on the other hand, creates a new file.
<DT><STRONG>.flip</STRONG>
<DD> These are files (mainly images) processed by 
    flipping the image (``i.flip'').
<DT><STRONG>.raw</STRONG>
<DD> Original image data without any processing. These will mostly
    reside in the location ``ZWALMrc''.
<DT><STRONG>.swab</STRONG>
<DD> In order to be able to read properly any files created
    or processed on Intergraph workstations, a swapping of bytes is needed. 
    The UNIX command ``dd'' can handle this problem. 
    This extension indicates that
    it needs to be swapped in order to use it on standard UNIX machines.
<DT><STRONG>.rgb</STRONG>
<DD> Red-green-blue color composite images.
<P>
 </DL>
Other filenames can be introduced as needed.
<P>
<HR><A NAME="tex2html837" HREF="node58.html"><IMG WIDTH=37 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="next" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/next_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME="tex2html835" HREF="node52.html"><IMG WIDTH=26 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="up" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/up_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME="tex2html829" HREF="node56.html"><IMG WIDTH=63 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="previous" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/previous_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME="tex2html839" HREF="node1.html"><IMG WIDTH=65 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="contents" SRC="http://taoren.rug.ac.be/lat2html/contents_motif.gif"></A>  <BR>
