<body text="#FFFFFF" bgcolor="#000000" link="#FFFFFF" vlink="#FFFFFF"
alink="#FFFFFF">

<center><h2>The New Tech Galleries - Innovation</h2><img src="inside.gif" border=0></p></center>

<table>
<br clear=left>

<tr>
<td valign=top>
<center><p><img src="innovations_entrance.gif" hspace=20 border=0
align=left>
<br clear=left><i>View of Entry</i></p></center>

<center><p><img src="innov_front.gif" hspace=20 border=0
align=left>
<br clear=left><i>View from Loggia Door </i></p></center>
</td>

<td width=300><b>INNOVATION </b>
<p><b>Perspective </b></p>

<p>The Perspective area introduces visitors to the Innovation gallery and
its presentation of a series of &quot;postcards&quot; from Silicon Valley.
The focus here is on this future-oriented, inventive place where technology
and people from around the world combine to create the innovations that
change our lives. Large projection screens, kiosks, historical graphics,
live video feeds, and other media capture the unique aspects of this area,
engage visitors in its diverse people and cultures and show how the region
itself has been changed by its position at the forefront of high-tech
innovation.
</p>

</td>
</tr>

<br clear=left>

</table>

<p>

<b>Postcard One: Pushing the Envelope</b> </p>

<p>Silicon Valley has long been known for the innovations that come from
its research laboratories. Researchers and scientists are constantly exploring
new technologies whose future consequences are only partially known, and
the impacts of which will not be felt for some time. Hands-on, open-ended
workbench experiences stimulate and challenge visitors working alone or
with others to tinker and experiment with some of the basic science and
technology fundamentals that underlie even the most complex technologies
developed in Silicon Valley today: lasers, electromagnets, and sensors.
Here, too, visitors will be able to explore new innovative technologies
under development, such as moving atoms with a scanning tunneling microscope.
Exhibits explore the relevance and applications of each technology, as
well as their anticipated and possibly unexpected impacts on our daily
lives. Throughout the area interactive videos and inventors' log books
help visitors see the real people behind the innovations. </p>

<p><b>Postcard Two: Miniature Revolution </b></p>

<p>In this exhibit area visitors gain an understanding of the science and
technology behind one of the world's most important innovations: the microchip.
Silicon Valley historically has played a major role in developing more
and more powerful microprocessors. Here, visitors explore what happens
in a typically isolated &quot;alter&quot; of high technology-the Clean
Room. Visitors can compare the cleanliness of a typical room to that of
a clean room, termed &quot;the most artificial environment on the planet.&quot;
No Chips emphasizes the pervasiveness of the tiny microchip in virtually
every part of our daily lives, from automobiles to appliances, and explores
what life would be like without them. Ghost in the Machine, Virtual Stepper,
and SEM take visitors through some of the complex, high-tech manufacturing
processes that occur in Silicon Valley, while Workers 'n the Room presents
the real people whose exacting skills make these wonders possible. </p>

<p><b>Postcard Three: Virtual Worlds </b></p>

<p>Sophisticated hardware and software, each developed in Silicon Valley,
help us model the way the world works. We can now create and manipulate
virtual objects and realms as if they were real, and test them under different
conditions by mimicking the laws of physics and forces of nature. Our daily
lives are filled with ordinary and complicated objects, each one designed.
Visitors can try firsthand the complex systems now available to design
different products from bicycles to aircraft carriers. Other interactives
feature technologies used to create compelling realistic models of objects
that until now could only be imagined. </p>

<p><b>Postcard Four: In Our Image </b></p>

<p>We create robots that imitate human abilities for many jobs that would
be impossible, too repetitive, or too dangerous for people to do. Some
day, robots may mine helium 3 on the Moon or operate a space station. New
technologies that use robots for such tasks as welding, cutting, and assembling
are increasingly common in Silicon Valley. The robots in these exhibits
help visitors understand what these innovations are, what they can do and,
importantly, what they still cannot do. Interactives allow visitors to
test their performance against a robot's. Others illustrate the engineering
achievements that allow robots to perform intricate or difficult tasks.
</p>

<hr>
<table>
<tr>

<td valign=top>
<img src="/images/git.gif" align=left alt="Get Into Technology!" width=120 height=68>
</td>

<td valign=middle>

