<html>
<head>
<title></title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#000000" text="#ffffff" link="#ffffff" vlink="#ffffff" alink="#ffffff">

<center><h2>The New Tech Galleries - Explorations</h2><img src="inside.gif"></center>

<table>
<tr>
<td valign=top>
<img src="explor_entry.gif" align=left hspace=20>
<br clear=left>
<center><i>View of Entry</i></center>

<p>


<img src="explor_bridge.gif" align=left hspace=20>
<br clear=left>
<center><i>View from Lobby Bridge</i></center>


</td>
<td width=400>
<b>E<font size="-1">XPLORATIONS</font></b>
<p>

<b>Perspective</b>
<p>
In the Perspective area visitors discover the content focus of the
Explorations gallerythat technology, coupled with human motivation
and curiosity, greatly expands our ability to reach and understand new
worlds. Here, too, visitors employ some of their own exploratory
tendencies and sample a few of the technologies they'll encounter in
the rest of Explorations.
<p>

</td>
</tr>
<br clear=left>
</table>

<p>

<b>Living on a Restless Planet</b>
<p>
This area focuses on the technologies used to study and monitor the
movement of the Earth's crust, with particular emphasis on Bay Area
earthquakes. The Parkfield Experiment exhibit encourages visitors to
analyze live data gathered from a research station on the San Andreas
fault, and discover the principles behind the instruments that detect
and measure earthquakes. At other exhibits, visitors gain online
access to recent seismic activity in the region, and try to build
earthquake-proof structures on a large shake table. Each exhibit in
Restless Planet reinforces the idea that earthquakes are the normal
result of our planet's dynamic nature, and by studying them we can
better prepare for their potentially destructive effects.

<p>
<b>Deep Frontier</b>
<p>
Technology is giving us new ways to explore beneath the ocean, in
regions once thought completely inaccessible. The experiences in Deep
Frontier underscore the crucial role technology plays in helping us
understand the ocean environments that make up over two-thirds of our
planet. Interactive exhibits emphasize the special challenges of
manned underwater research and illustrate the inventions, such as
advanced diving suits, that protect humans in high- pressure
environments. Visitors cooperate to maneuver a remotely operated
vehicle in a large aquatic tank, demonstrating some of the specialized
technologies available for working underwater without risking human
lives.

<p>

<b>Earthview</b>
<p>
Here, the technologies that enable us to sense, picture, and analyze
global systems and detailed features provide a multidimensional
portrait of our planet.  Exhibits such as the Earth Theater and Eye on
the Earth illustrate how images of our planet, new mapping techniques,
and technologies such as satellites and on- site sensors help us
observe, monitor, and understand large-scale phenomena.  Visitors use
colorful Geographic Information System visualization programs to
create three-dimensional maps or make predictions about the effect of
global warming on a specific environment. Hands-on activities
demonstrate the principles behind satellites, sensors, and the
computers that turn raw data into colored images.
<p>
<b>Probing the Heavens</b>
<p>
Our ability to study and understand the universe is enhanced
dramatically by new tools and techniques used in astronomy. Visitors
experience scientific exploration firsthand as they use a real
telescope and the astronomical image- processing software employed by
astronomers. Interactive exhibits clarify the principles of optics,
the electromagnetic spectrum, and how spectrometers work, pointing out
their applications in space exploration. The latest discoveries and
dramatic images from the Hubble Space Telescope are available to
search online, and visitors can explore the instrument's features and
capabilities through a computer interactive.
<p>
<b>Destination: Space</b>
<p>
A surprising amount of research and practical work relevant to life on
Earth, as well as our future in space, takes place in the space
environment. Visitors can explore basic technologies such as space
suits and specialized tools for use in zero gravity, as well as space
stations and other innovations pushing the frontier of manned space
exploration. Interactive exhibits show the technologies that enable
humans to work in space, such as life support systems research
instruments, and robotic devices. Technology Spin-offs reveals widely
available products and devices that originated in the space program,
ranging from everyday devices to specialized instruments used in
medicine.

<p>

<b>To Other Worlds</b>

<p> This immersive environment takes visitors to a
generic planetary base that could be on the Moon or Mars, two possible
workplaces of the future. Here, the hows and whys of recent, current,
and future exploration of these two destinations captivate visitors
with real-life science that sounds like science fiction. Visitors
learn how orbiters and sensors provide critical long-distance
information about these remote environments, discover what a lunar or
Mars base might be like, and maneuver a remotely controlled planetary
rover. In addition to revealing the science and technological planning
behind establishing a future on these new worlds, this exhibit area
voices some of the ethical questions that will come up when we venture
to other worlds.

<p>

<b>Mysteries of the Universe</b>

<p>

This area
addresses the issue of creating a context for humankind in a universe
too vast for us to fully understand. Powers of Ten takes the vastness
of the universe down to subatomic scale with a video zoom-in from
space into a person's hand. Besides providing us with remarkable tools
that can help us explore our universe, technology is also helping us
answer some of the most fundamental questions about human
existence. Are We Alone? uses the real tools designed to explore the
likelihood of other intelligent life forms in space.

<hr>
<table>
<tr>

<td valign=top>
<img src="/images/git.gif" align=left alt="Get Into Technology!" width=120 height=68>
</td>

<td valign=middle>

For more info about The Tech, call us at
408-279-7150 or send mail to <a href="mailto:info@thetech.org">info@thetech.org</a>.

<p>

<center>The Tech Museum of Innovation</center>
<center>145 West San Carlos Street</center>
<center>San Jose, CA, 95113, USA</center>
</td>

</tr>
</table>


