<html>
<head>
<title></title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#000000" text="#ffffff" link="#ffffff" vlink="#ffffff" alink="#ffffff">

<center><h2>The New Tech Galleries -<br>Communications and Information</h2><img src="inside.gif"></center>

<table>
<tr>
<td valign=top>
<img src="comm_entrance.gif" align=left hspace=20>
<br clear=left>
<center><i>View of Entry</i></center>

<p>


<img src="comm_atrium.gif" align=left hspace=20>
<br clear=left>
<center><i>View from Lobby Bridge</i></center>

</td>
<td valign=top>
<b>C<font size="-1">OMMUNICATIONS AND</font> I<font size="-1">NFORMATION</font></b>

<p>
<b>Perspective</b>
<p>
The Perspective area orients visitors to the exhibits they will explore in the Communications and Information gallery and engages them in the process of communicating with one another.  Perspective previews the physical and conceptual layout of the Communications gallery, which is organized around different ways that technology is broadening and transforming how we work together, form social and political communities, express our creativity, do business, and stay informed.  

</td>
</tr>

<br clear=left>
</table>





<p>
<b>Networking a Planet</b>
<p>
An increasing number of global and local information networks connect the machines and services we use every day, and many of them are invisible to us. Networking a Planet enables visitors to discover networks which they may not realize are a part of their daily lives, and reveals aspects of this network web now linking  entertainment, business, education, government, and science, around the world. The exhibits allow visitors the chance to explore the science underlying the newest tools and materials, from cell phones to fiber optics. Networking a Planet will also open discussion of such issues as privacy and the security of information, and explore the increased efficiency and ensuing vulnerability that result from an increasing dependence on networks.

<p>
<b>Redefining Community</b>
<p>
We're changing our definition of "community" as new technologies help us forge unexpected social groups, create and maintain relationships, and explore innovative ways to work together. Redefining Community provides many opportunities for Tech visitors to interact with each other and with "visitors" beyond the walls of The Tech, collaboratively solving challenges, playing games, or creating art, despite physical distances or language barriers. Exhibits here offer an in-depth look at some of the inner workings underlying the technology needed to hook into the communications network. Woven throughout Redefining Community are important questions about the positive and negative impacts of the disappearance of geographical boundaries that have traditionally defined communities, and about the unprecedented application of such technologies as teleconferencing, e-mail, and shared virtual spaces.

<p>

<b>Harnessing the Explosion</b>
<p>
New technologies now bring us an unparalleled flood of information, but they also help us sift through it for the information that is personally relevant or useful. Each of us can now access an astonishing number of television channels, online databases, and special interest bulletin boards. Interactive TV and other digital technologies promise to empower us to take advantage of the available resources and put them to our use. Harnessing the Explosion includes stations for exploring the Internet; sampling some of the vast databases now accessible; trying out the latest software, user interface tools, and search agents; and exploring the technologies that store the vast quantities of data. However, this proliferation of electronic data and easy access to it also means privacy is less secure. Visitors here find out what kinds of information are available about themselves, what corporations do with it, and how they can control access to the information. Here, too, important issues such as censorship and controlling access to online pornography are explored. 
<p>
<b>Digital Expressions</b>
<p>
New technologies for capturing, manipulating, outputting, and networking sound, images, and text offer astonishing opportunities for creativity in media ranging from personal Web pages to movie special effects. Activities in Digital Expressions give visitors a chance to understand and use advanced technology to produce original work, experiencing the process of creating, editing, and exchanging documents over a network. Just as technology gives us the ability to modify imagesto place Forrest Gump in the Kennedy White Houseit also makes it easier to deceive with those same images, manipulating video footage to twist a news story's emphasis. Visitors will  have an opportunity to fashion illusions that show how easily one can trick the eye or misconstrue meaning. Social and ethical questions point out that we need to be discerning critics, rather than accepting consumers, of these new amalgamated media. 

<hr>
<table>
<tr>

<td valign=top>
<img src="/images/git.gif" align=left alt="Get Into Technology!" width=120 height=68>
</td>

<td valign=middle>

For more info about The Tech, call us at
408-279-7150 or send mail to <a href="mailto:info@thetech.org">info@thetech.org</a>.

<p>

<center>The Tech Museum of Innovation</center>
<center>145 West San Carlos Street</center>
<center>San Jose, CA, 95113, USA</center>
</td>

</tr>
</table>


