<title>The Imaginative Chip</title> 
<h1>The Tech Museum of Innovation Presents...</h1>
<h1>The Imaginative Chip, an audiokinetic sculpture by 
George Rhoads</h1>
Check out our new <a href="/exhibits/rhoads/map/">clickable imagemap</a>,
choose from a list of <a href="/exhibits/rhoads/images/">digital images</a>
from the sculpture, or take a look at our
<a href="/jpgs/fotoman/events/ball_machine.jpg">build-it-yourself ball machine</a>.
<hr>
<a href="/gifs/exhibits/rhoads-2.gif">
<img src="/gifs/exhibits/rhoads-2.gif" alt="[Image of the Rhoads sculpture]" board=0></a>
<p>
<hr>
<pre>
Description:    Billard balls moving through a clever maze of familiar 
                objects create surprising sound and motion as they go.  
                This dynamic sculpture can imaginatively suggest, on 
                very large scale, the movement of information through 
                an integrated circuit chip.
  
Size:           16 feet tall, 12 feet long, and 3 feet wide
   
Location:       "The Imaginative Chip" serves as the front entrance
                attraction for The Tech Museum of Innovation, a 
                museum featuring interactive exhibit experiences that 
                engage the visitor with today's technologies, at 145 
                West San Carlos Street, downtown San Jose.
 
Design:         Artist and sculptor George Rhoads of Ithaca, New York,
                designs the ball machines, which he refers to as "art 
                that entertains."
 
Fabrication:    Rock Stream Studios of Ithaca, New York, directed by
                Robert McGuire.
 
Benefactors     Mr. and Mrs. Robert A. Grimm, Los Altos, California.          
  
Other works:    Rhoads' sculptures have been placed in public spaces
                throughout the world, including Boston Museum of
                Science; Port Authority in New York; Ontario Science
                Center in Toronto; Micronesia Mall in Tamuning, Guam; 
                and the Rockingham Center in Freemantle, Australia.
</pre>
<hr>
<h1>About artist and sculptor George Rhoads</h1>
<ul>
<li><a href="/exhibits/rhoads/rhoads-sct_1988.html">Shopping Centers Today, May 1988, "Art in Motion", Metta Winter</a>
<li><a href="/exhibits/rhoads/rhoads-sky_1988.html">Sky Magazine, May 1988, "Mesmerizing Machines", Metta Winter</a>
<li><a href="/exhibits/rhoads/rhoads-smithsonian_1988.html">Smithsonian, October 1988, "Clumper Upper to Wok Dumper to Chute to Helix to Block", Richard Kostelanetz</a>
</ul>
<hr>
<img src="/gifs/logos/tech/techbutton-footer.gif" alt="">
<address>The Imaginative Chip / The Tech /
<a href="/webmaster.html">webmaster@thetech.org</a></address>
</DOC>
