<h2>Calendar Listings
for November-December 1996
at The Tech</h2>

<h3>NOVEMBER</h3>

<b>TECH TALKS</b>

<p>

<b>Xerox PARC: Merging the Worlds of Art and Technology</b><br>
November 8 - 7 p.m. - What happens when professional artists work in
collaboration with research scientists and their technical ideas? The noted
Xerox PARC (Palo Alto Research Center) program opens up new possibilities
for aesthetics in photography, telecommunications and creative documents.
Rich Gold from Xerox PARC will lead the panel of artists and researchers.
Individual Tech Talk lecture tickets are available on a space-available
basis for $6 at the door and $5 for members. For ticket information, call
(408) 279-7158.

<p>

<b>TECH TALKS</b>

<p>

<b>Chico MacMurtrie - A Dance of Robots</b><br>
November 21 - 7 p.m. - The Tech Museum's groundbreaking was stunning,
thanks to the troupe of anthropomorphic robots created by artist Chico
MacMurtrie. Just back from a European tour with his family of robots,
MacMurtrie will discuss his techniques and ideas and demonstrate some of
his creative and frolicsome robots. Individual Tech Talk lecture tickets
are available on a space-available basis for $6 at the door and $5 for
members. For ticket information, call (408) 279-7158.

<h3>ONGOING</h3>

<b>Lasers, Light & Color</b><br>
Through December - In a whirling kaleidoscope of color, light and
scientific discovery, The Tech's new series of hands-on and interactive
exhibits allow visitors to explore and understand rainbows, shadows and
reflections, as well as discover innovative uses of lights in holograms,
communications, medicine and much more.

<p>

<b>WORKSHOPS</b>

<p>

<b>Tech Girls!</b><br>
November 2, 9 - 10 a.m.-1 p.m.  - (eight Saturday mornings, twice a month,
September 1996-May 1997) - A program of hands-on experiences for young
women (ages 10-13), exploring the theme: Technology as a Tool of Science.
Limited to 20 participants.

<p>

<b>Animated Greetings</b><br>
November 2 - 10 a.m.-noon - Make interactive, personalized greetings that
move, talk, sing. Send your greetings on a floppy disk (to take home) or
send over e-mail. $20/non-members, $15/members.

<p>

<b>LEGO Robots (Intro)</b><br>
Nov. 2 - 1:30 p.m.-4:30 p.m. - A popular introduction to constructing LEGO
robotic devices, and basic navigation and computer programming skills,
using Hyperbot software. $25/non-members, $20/members.

<p>

<b>ROBOTIX Construction</b><br>
November 9 - 1:30 p.m.-4:30 p.m. - Construct and control a ROBOTIX lunar
launcher mini-kit (to take home following the workshop). $35/non-members,
$30/members.

<p>

<b>The ABC's of the Internet with Netscape</b><br>
November 9 - 10 a.m.-12:30 p.m. - Get an overview of the Internet. Surf the
Web with a popular Web browser, use search engines, learn to send and
receive e-mail and more. $25/non-members, $20/members.

<p>

<b>Multimedia for Kids</b><br>
November 16 - 10 a.m.-Noon - Create your own multimedia show using
libraries of exciting images, paint tools, text, voice recordings and
dazzling special effects. Grade, 3-4 only. $15/non-members, $10/members.

<p>

<b>Model Rockets</b><br>
November 16-17 - 1-4 p.m. The Tech and DeAnza College - Build, design and
blast off a rocket that is yours to keep (and reusable) after the workshop.
Flies 30 stories high. Requires two afternoons. Launch day (second day) is
at DeAnza College. Safe and fun. $50/non-members, $40/members.

<p>

<b>LEGO Robots (Intro)</b><br>
November 17 - 1 p.m.-4 p.m. - A popular introduction to constructing LEGO
robotic devices, and basic navigating and computer programming skills using
Hyperbot software. $25/non-members, $20/members.

<p>

<b>Multimedia for Kids</b><br>
November 23 - 10 a.m. -Noon - (See Nov. 16 for details.) Grades 5-6 only.
$15/non-members, $10/members.

<p>

<b>Inside a Computer's Insides</b><br>
Nov. 23 - 1 p.m. - 4 p.m. - Take apart and reassemble a working PC, and
learn how this incredible machine functions. Limited to 12 participants,
ages 10 and above. $25/non-members, $20/members.

<p>

<b>Lego Robots Family Workshop</b><br>
Nov. 24 - 1:30-4:30 p.m. - An introduction to computer-controlled LEGO
robots, for family groups (one adult and one child, minimum age 6). Limited
to 6 groups. $35/non- members (per group), $30/members per group.


<h3>DECEMBER</h3>

<b>TECH TALKS</b>

<p>

<b>Hal's Legacy . . . Beyond 2001: A Space Odyssey</b><br>
December 10 - 7 p.m. - Author Dr. David G. Stork discusses his newly
released book "Hal's Legacy," which explores the relationship between
science fiction and technological fact. His book is based on the 1968 movie
"2001: A Space Odyssey." Dr. Stork will be available for book signings.
(The Tech Museum Store will sell copies of the book that night.) Individual
Tech Talk lecture tickets are available on a space-available basis at $6 at
the door and $5 for members. For ticket information, call (408) 279-7158.

<b>Special Hours</b>

<p>

December 23, 30 - 10 a.m.-5 p.m. - The museum will be open on Mondays
during the winter holidays.

<p>

<b>WORKSHOPS</b>

<p>

<b>Tech Girls!</b><br>
December 7, 14 - 10 a.m.-1 p.m. - (See Nov. 2 for details.)

<p>

<b>World Wide Web Page Making (Basics)</b><br>
December 7 - Noon-3 p.m. - A basic introduction to HTML coding and Web page
publishing. Learn how to make your own home page and links.
$25/non-members, $20/members.

<p>

<b>Robots on Mars</b><br>
December 7 - 1:30 p.m.-4:30 p.m. - Construct complex ROBOTIX planetary
rovers to navigate through challenging, simulated Martian surfaces.
Recommended: any other robotics workshop. $25/non-members, $20 /members.

<p>

<b>Flying Machines!</b><br>
December 8 - 1 p.m.-4 p.m. - Build, test and keep  a rubber band-powered,
helicopter-like whirly-gig and a trapezoidal kite. Learn about powered and
unpowered flight. $30/non-members, $25/members.

<p>

<b>World Wide Web Page Making (Intermediate)</b><br>
December 14 - 10 a.m.-1 p.m. - An in-depth look at Web page publishing,
including image alignment, internal links, advanced formatting, and tables.
Prerequisite: An understanding of basic HTML codes. $30/non-members,
$25/members.

<p>

<b>Advanced Robotics Projects</b><br>
December 15 - 1 p.m.-5 p.m. - Using a variety of creative approaches and
all kinds of construction materials (LEGO and ROBOTIX), build more
advanced types of robotic models, and control them with new Hyperbot Plus
software. Recommended: other robotic workshops. $35/non-members,
$30/members.

<p>

<b>TECH TALKS</b>

<p>

<b>Tales From the Final Frontier</b>

<p>

January 29 - 7 p.m. - Ray Bradbury, author of "The Martian Chronicles,"
"The Illustrated Man," "Fahrenheit 451" and "Something Wicked This Way
Comes" will discuss technology's role and shaping societal values. Widely
regarded as the most important figure in the development of science fiction
as a literary genre, his work evokes the themes of racism, censorship,
technology, nuclear war, humanistic values and the importance of
imagination. All Tech Talks will be at Flint Center for the Performing Arts
at De Anza College. Tickets for the four-part series are $100 for
non-museum members and $88 for members. Tickets may be purchased by mail,
at the Flint Center box office and through BASS ticketing.

<p>

March 5 - 7 p.m. - Captain James Lovell Jr., astronaut, is best known for
his fourth and final space flight, the perilous Apollo 13 mission in 1970.
In 1994, Lovell wrote "Lost Moon," the story of the courageous mission of
Apollo 13. In 1995, the film version touched the hearts of millions of
people. Here is a chance to hear firsthand the courage and determination
exhibited as man battled the unknowns of both space and technology. (See
Jan. 29) for further information.

<p>

April 9 - 7 p.m. - Lawrence Krauss, author of the national best-selling
book "The Physics of Star Trek" is an internationally known theoretical
physicist. A widely acclaimed teacher and lecturer, Professor Krauss
reaches out to popular audiences at such places as the Smithsonian Air and
Space Museum, The National Museum of Natural History and frequent PBS radio
and TV appearances. For those technologically challenged, Prof. Krauss has
a knack for turning complex subjects into easily understood concepts. (See
Jan. 29 for further information.)

<p>

May 14 - 7 p.m. - Mae Jemison, pioneer, astronaut and the first woman of
color in space, works on a variety of projects that promote ways to
integrate technology and science into our everyday lives - culture, health,
environment and education. As a teacher and motivator, Dr. Jemison engages
audiences in her passion for putting technology to work to ultimately
create a better world. (See Jan. 29 for further information.) 

<h2>About The Tech</h2>

The Tech Museum of Innovation is a hands-on museum featuring the
emerging technologies of Silicon Valley and beyond. The Tech is as 145 W.
San Carlos St. in downtown San Jose. Admission is $6 for adults; $4 for
youths, seniors and students. Members and children 5 and under are free.
The museum is open Tuesday-Sunday 10 a.m.-5 p.m. For general information,
call 408-279-7150.

<p>

For more information, please contact:

<p>

Gloria Chun Hoo<br>
Marketing Manager, The Tech Museum of Innovation<br>
(408) 279-7157<br>
<a href="mailto:gloria@thetech.org">gloria@thetech.org</a>


