<h2>Calendar Listings for
January-February at
The Tech Museum of Innovation</h2>

<h3>JANUARY</h3>

<b>TECH TALKS</b>
<p>
<b>Tales From the Final Frontier</b><br>
<P>January 29 - 7 p.m. - Ray Bradbury, author of "The Martian Chronicles,"
"The Illustrated Man," "Fahrenheit 451" and "Something Wicked This Way
Comes" will discuss technology's role and shaping societal values. Widely
regarded as the most important figure in the development of science fiction
as a literary genre, his work evokes the themes of racism, censorship,
technology, nuclear war, humanistic values and the importance of
imagination. All Tech Talks will be at Flint Center for the Performing Arts
at De Anza College. Tickets for the four-part spring series are $100 for
non-museum members and $88 for members and are available at The Tech. After
Jan. 8, tickets for an individual Tech Talk may be purchased at the Flint
Center box office and through BASS ticketing for $29.
<p>
<p>
<b>WORKSHOPS</b><br>
<P>
<b>The ABCs of the Internet</b>
<P>January 4 - 10 a.m.-12:30 p.m. - A basic introduction to HTML coding and
Web page publishing. Learn how to make your own home page and links.
$25/non-members, $20/members.
<P>
<b>World Wide Web Page Making (Basics)</b><br>
<P>January 11 - 10 a.m.-1 p.m. - Includes easy to learn HTML coding for Web
page publishing. Make your own home page with links. For PC and Mac
computer users. $25/non-members, $20/members.
<P>
<b>LEGO (tm) Robots (Intro)</b><br>
<P>January 11 - 1:30-4:30 p.m. - The best introduction to constructing LEGO
(tm)
robotic devices, and developing basic navigation and computer programming
skills, with Hyperbot (tm) software. $25/non-members, $20/members.
<P>
<b>World Wide Web Page Making (Interm.)</b><br>
<P>January 18 - 10 a.m.-1p.m. - An in-depth look at Web page publishing,
including image alignment, internal links, advanced formatting, tables.
Prerequisite: An understanding of basic HTML codes (or basics class).
$25/non-members, $20 members.
<P>
<b>Computer Put Together</b><br>
<P>January 19 - 1-4 p.m. - A popular hands-on class to learn about a
computer's insides. Take apart and reassemble a working PC. Limited to 12
participants, ages 10 and above. $25/non-members, $20/members.
<P>
<b>Graphics-Making for the Web</b><br>
<P>January 25 - 10 a.m.-12:30 p.m. - An in-depth look at using and creating
graphics for Web pages. Prerequisite: An understanding of basic HTML codes
(or basics class). $25/non-members, $20/members.
<P>
<b>Robotic Maze Solver</b><br>
<P>January 26 - 1:30-4:30 p.m. - Experiment with a new robotic vehicle, the
Pilot, with built-in sensors, lights and sound system. Use a computer and
Hyperbot software to program the Pilot, either wired or remotely.
Recommended: any other Robotics workshop. Limited to 14 participants.
$25/non-members, $20/members.
<P>

<h3>FEBRUARY</h3>

<P>

<h3>SPECIAL EXHIBIT</h3>
<P>
<b>American Movie Makers: The Dawn of Sound</b>
<P>American Movie Makers: The Dawn of Sound - Opening  Feb. 1 through Labor
Day 1997 - A nostalgic trip into the past, this exhibition blends
technology and cinema artistry to trace the growth of sound movies from
Edison's early experiments to such blockbuster classics as "Gone With the
Wind."
<P>Artifacts from the early days of "talkies" include a Vitaphone Projector,
the first successful movie sound machine, which used separate record disks
to accompany the pictures on film with sound. Other artifacts and
photographs document the evolution of electroacoustics, from Bell
Laboratories' development of effective method of sound amplification of
electrical recording to the Vitaphone's synchronizing of sight and sound.
Photmurals display shots of early movies, and three interactive video
kiosks document 50 years of movie history, including Lindbergh's take-off
for Paris in 1927 and Greta Garbo's first lines on the screen in 1930.
Visitors also can enter a sound booth to sing along with Al Jolson, then
listen to a 1920s-quality recording of their own voices.
<P>

<P><B>Kids Do the Web</b>
<P>February 8 - 1-5 p.m., demos every 30 minutes - Demonstrations of Web tools
for kids and displays of Web sites created by kids. Parents also can
purchase a copy of the newly published book "Kids Do The Web" from Adobe
Press, a colorful look at how young people around the world are creating
Internet sites.
<P>

<P><B>Engineer's Weekend at The Tech</b>
<P>February 22-23 - As part of the celebration of National Engineering Week,
join The Tech for hands-on activities and special exhibits. Underwriters
Laboratories will demonstrate tests on public safety.

<h3>WORKSHOPS</h3>
<P><B>Simpsons Cartoon Studio</b>
February 1 - 10 a.m.-12:30 p.m. - Create and watch your very own cartoons
with your favorite Simpson characters, including authentic voices,
backgrounds, props, special effects, and music. $25/non-members,
$20/members.

<P><B>Lunar Launcher ROBOTIX (tm) Construction</b>
<P>February 1 - 1:30 p.m.-4:30 p.m. - Construct and computer-control a
ROBOTIX (tm) Lunar Launcher take-home mini-kit. Recommended: any other Robotics
workshop. Limited to 15 participants. $35/non-members, $30/members.
<P>

<P><B>Incredible Flying Machines</b>
<P>February 2 - 1 p.m.-4 p.m. - Build, test and take home rubber-band powered
helicopter-like whirly-gig and a trapezoidal kite. Learn about powered and
unpowered flight. Limited to 15 participants. Ages 12-16. $30/non-members,
$25 members.

<P><B>Hollywood Animation Revisited</b>
<P>February 8 - 10 a.m.-12:30 p.m.  - Write your own Hollywood script and
direct your own animations, with new talking teenage characters, titles,
sound effects. $25/non-members, $20/members.

<P><B>LEGO (tm) Robots Family Workshop</b>
<P>February 9 - 1:30-4:30 p.m. - An introduction to computer-controlled
LEGO (tm)
robots, for family groups (one adult and one child, minimum age 6). Limited
to 6 groups. $35/non-members (per group), $30/members (per group).

<P><B>Computer Screen LEGOs (tm)</b>
<P>February 15 - 10 a.m.-12:30 p.m. - With more than 300 LEGO (tm) Brick
styles,
build cars, boats, whatever your imagination desires, on your computer
screen. Ages 6 and above. $20/non-members, $15/members.

<P><B>Quiz Show Designer</b>
<P>February 22 - 10 a.m.-noon - Design your own quiz show, create your own
questions and answers, with animated players and lively sound effects and
music. Ages 6 and above. $20/non-members, $15/members.

<P><B>LEGO (tm) Robotic Construction</b>
<P>February 22 - 1:30-4:30 p.m. - Construct robotic machines from a Simple
Gears LEGO Dacta (tm) mini-kit and computer-control projects which include a
merry-go-round and a hill-climbing tricycle (take home mini-hit following
workshop). Limited to 15 participants. $35/non-members, $30/members.

<h3>FUTURE</h3>
<b>TECH CHALLENGE '97</b>
<ul>
<li>March 1 - Information clinic.
<li>March 2 - Registration deadline.
<li>April 12-13, 19-20 - 1-4 p.m. at The Tech - Test trials.
</ul>
<p>April 23 - Civic Auditorium, San Jose - An exciting team competition for
students in grades 5-12. Land a robotic rover on Mars and escape from an
ancient crater. Call (408) 279-7158 (press 5) for latest information or to
receive registration materials. For details, see the Tech's web site,
<a href="http://www.thetech.org">http://www.thetech.org.</a>

<P>
<b>It's a Comet and It's Blazing</b>
<P>March 1997 - During March, Comet Hale Boop is expected to be a dazzling,
viewable sight in the early evening sky. Special programs are planned with
planetariums and museums in other parts of the world to share the historic
event. The Tech will offer visitors opportunities to learn more about the
comet, first noticed in 1995.

<h2>About The Tech</h2>
<P>
The Tech Museum of Innovation is located at 145 W. San Carlos St. in
downtown San Jose. Admission is $6 for adults; $4 for youths, seniors and
students. Members and children 5 and under are free. The museum is open
Tuesday-Sunday 10 a.m.-5 p.m. For general information, call (408) 279-7150
or visit <a href="http://www.thetech.org">http://www.thetech.org</a>.

<p>

For more information, please contact:<br>
Gloria Chun Hoo- The Tech Museum of Innovation<br>
(408) 279-7157 <a href="mailto:gloria@thetech.org">gloria@thetech.org</a><br>

