<h2>Special Announcement</h2>

<b>WANTED: SOPHOMORES WHO WANT TO MAKE SCIENCE THEIR CAREER</b>

<p>

<b>WANTED: MENTORS FOR OUTSTANDING HIGH SCHOOL MATH AND SCIENCE STUDENTS</b>

<h3>Valley Scholars Program Description</h3>

A Valley Scholar is a student whose primary interest is in the field of
math, science, and/or technology, who has shown evidence of being a
creative problem solver, and who is excited about practical applications of
math, and science. Valley Scholars are articulate, determined, and seen as
good role models by their peers and by adults. Valley Scholars intend to
pursue careers as mathematicians, engineers, practical scientists, and
teachers.

<p>

The Valley Scholars Program was established in 1994 by the Noyce
foundation, the Community Foundation of Santa Clara County, and the
Peninsula Community Foundation for public high school students in Santa
Clara and San Mateo Counties and the Fremont Unified School District
(Alameda County).

<p>

These $20,000 scholarships are offered to make it possible for outstanding
Silicon Valley math and science students to attend highly competitive
colleges and universities that they otherwise could not afford.
Following their selection in the spring of the sophomore year in high
school, Valley Scholars are matched with mentors who are professionals from
industry and education in the Silicon Valley. These mentors are available
to share their experience and knowledge and to give the students confidence
and encouragement. Mentorship activities vary with the individual, but
include visits to the work place, discussion of career and educational
opportunities, and personally designed projects leading to internships.
While in high school, Valley Scholars participate in activities which
support their academic goals. During their junior year, recipients take
part in various workshops which include an overview of different types of
colleges, an introduction to the admissions process, and preparation for
SAT testing. As seniors the Scholars are given individual college
counseling as well as assistance in completing financial aid applications.
Additional activities include tours of Silicon Valley companies and an
overnight on a college campus which allows the students to experience
college life by attending an engineering class and spending time in the
dorm with college students. A tour of the campus focuses on college
selection.

<p>

Upon acceptance into a competitive four-year college, a Valley Scholar
receives up to $5,000 each year for four years. Scholarship renewals are
based upon continued academic success and a major in the fields of math,
practical science, and/or technology.
For further information about the Valley Scholars program, please call
Judith Schweikert, Director, at the Valley Scholars office (415) 324-1390.

<h3>Elegibility for Valley Scholars</h3>

<ul>
<li>Creative interest in an curiosity about science as demonstrated through
problem-solving skills and hands-on application
<li>Committed to a career as
an engineer, mathematician, practical scientist, or teacher.
<li>Agreement to participate actively in th Valley Scholars program during
high school
<li>Credentials for aceptance into competitive post-secondary institutions
<li>Involvement in school and/or community activities - a good role-model for his or her peers.
<li>Sophomore in high school
<li>Financial need, defined as family income of up to $100,000
<li>U.S. citizen or permanent resident
<li>Residency in San Mateo, Santa Clara, or alameda County for five years
<li>Attendance at a public high school in San Mateo County, Santa Clara
County, or Fremont Unified School District.
<li>The Valley Scholars
scholarship grants are limited to one per family.
</ul>

<h3>Valley Scholars Mentor Program</h3>

You are invited to become a mentor to one of these outstanding young
students as he/she prepares for college and explores career options.

<p>

<b>Purpose:</b>

<p>

<ul>
<li>To provide Valley Scholars with experience in and exposure to the adult
world as it relates to career exploration.
<li>To give these students
confidence and encouragement.
<li>To provide an opportunity for Silicon Valley
professionals to share their knowledge and expertise about careers in
science and engineering.
</ul>

<b>Qualifications:</b>

<ul>
<li>Mentors should be graduates of a competitive American college or
university at the graduate or undergraduate level.
<li>Mentors should have a
knowledge of some of the academic programs in his/her field.
<li>Mentors should be willing to arrange meetings with other professionals to
gain broader knowledge of career options.
</ul>

<b>Commitment and Activities:</b>

<ul>
<li>Minimum of a one year commitment by the mentor.
<li>Minimum of 1-2 hours per
month of contact to be set by mentor and student.
<li>Mentors share information about their jobs/work experience, help students
relate school-based learning to the workplace, introduce the Scholars to
other professionals and companies, and are generally "there for the
students."
<li>Activities vary with the individual, but have included social meetings,
phone and email contact, visits to the work place, discussion of career and
educational opportunities and responsibilities, participation in
individually designed projects and hands-on activities, internships, and
summer positions.
</ul>

<p>

<b>Outcomes:</b>

<p>

Student learns:
<ul>
<li>about the actual field that the mentor works in.
<li>about the skills
needed for a particular job, including the type of written and oral
presentations necessary.
<li>how much training is needed for the job (both
in school and on-the-job).
<li>behaviors, attitudes, and interpersonal skills needed for the workplace.
<li>professional networks related to his/her interests.
</ul>

<ul>
<li>Student is encouraged in his pursuit of a scientific career.
<li>Student reinvests his talents in Silicon Valley.
</ul>

For additional information, please contact Judith Schweikert, Director,
Valley Scholars, 415/324-1390 or email <a href="mailto:vscholar@ix.netcom.com">vscholar@ix.netcom.com</a>.


