<h2>Unisys Aquanta PC Division Donates
$1 Million in 'Adoption' of The Tech</h2>

SAN JOSE, CA (Dec. 19, 1996) - The San Jose-headquartered Aquanta
Personal Computer Division of Unisys raises the spirit of corporate
donations to a new level of personal involvement with the announcement
today of its "adoption" of The Tech Museum of Innovation.

<p>

Continuing a long history of involvement with science and
technology institutions by Unisys, the PC Division is donating $1 million
worth of Aquanta-brand personal computers and network servers, along with
installation services and technical support, to be delivered over the next
two and a half years as the new Tech Museum building takes shape. The $59
million, 112,000-square-foot future home for The Tech is scheduled to open
in late 1998.

<p>

The announcement of the adoption was made to employees recently by
Frank Brandenberg, corporate vice president of Unisys Corporation and
general manager of the Unisys Aquanta PC Division. At the meeting, the
company handed out "early adopter" certificates to employees and encouraged
their active participation.

<p>

The first installment of Unisys hardware arrived at The Tech today
just in time for Christmas. The equipment arrived after a symbolic sleigh
ride on the Santa Clara Valley Transportation Authority's historic trolley
from the Aquanta PC Division headquarters on North First Street.

<p>

Aquanta PC Division employees decked out in Santa Claus hats,
unloaded the gift-wrapped computers. A holiday reception followed in the
museum.

<p>

"The adoption provides Aquanta PC Division employees and their
families an opportunity to take advantage of the volunteer recognition
programs available at The Tech," said Peter Giles, president of The Tech.
"There are hundreds of ways that people as a group and as individuals can
help make the dream of a new Tech Museum a reality, from community
outreach, educational programs, memberships and donations to volunteerism
and the creation and development of new exhibits."

<p>

In announcing the adoption of The Tech, Unisys PCD's Brandenberg
said, "We want to be a force in promoting the value of technology in our
community and to foster increased understanding of, and interest in,
science, math and technology. To make this happen, we have encouraged all
of our employees here in San Jose to join in adopting The Tech Museum of
Innovation.

<p>

"Since the world headquarters for the Unisys Aquanta Personal
Computer Division are located just a short Light Rail ride up North First
Street from the museum, our employees will be able to visit the museum
frequently to brainstorm and share their love of technology."

<p>

"In the process they will be making a tangible contribution to the
community and hopefully encourage more young people to consider careers in
technology and sciences. The latter activity is a major focus of Unisys
worldwide."

<p>

The Tech Museum is the premier science and technology museum
serving the Greater San Jose metropolitan area. It is located at 145 W. San
Carlos Street in downtown San Jose. Admission is $6 for adults, $4 for
students, youth and seniors, and free for children under 5 and members. The
Tech is open 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Tuesday through Sunday, and Mondays December
23 and 30 during the holiday season. For information, call (408) 279-7150
or www.thetech.org.

<p>

For more information contact:

<p>

Gloria Chun Hoo, The Tech Museum, (408) 279-7157, <a href="mailto:gloria@thetech.org">gloria@thetech.org</a><br>
John Murphy, Unisys Corporation, (408) 434-4360, <a href="mailto:jmurphy@sj.unisys.com">jmurphy@sj.unisys.com</a><br>
Gina Anderlini, Miller Shandwick Technologies, (415) 962-9550,
<a href="mailto:ganderlini@shandwick.com">ganderlini@shandwick.com</a><br>

	    <!-- end text cell -->
	  </td>
	</tr>
      </table>

