<h2>Department of Commerce Awards Grant To The Tech Museum of Innovation
For Exhibit on National Medal of Technology</h2>

SAN JOSE, CA (Dec. 13, 1996) - The Tech Museum of Innovation today
announced that it is the recipient of a $50,000 exhibit planning grant from
the U.S. Department of Commerce.  The funds received would be used for
developing a National Medal of Technology exhibit celebrating the American
spirit of creativity, commitment to innovation and technological achievement.

<p>

The exhibit, which will be permanently housed at The Tech's future home and
which will serve as a prototype for a national traveling exhibit, will
highlight the recipients of the National Medal of Technology.  The National
Medal of Technology is the highest honor awarded by the President of the
United States of America for technological innovation; an award established
by Congress in 1980 and first awarded in 1985. It is administered by the
U.S. Department of Commerce's Technology Administration.

<p>

"The Tech Museum, located here in the heart of Silicon Valley, is honored
to have been  chosen to develop this exhibit and to annually showcase the
nation's Medal of Technology winners.  Worldwide, Silicon Valley is
recognized as a center of creativity, innovation and technological
achievement," said Peter Giles, president of The Tech Museum.
The Tech, which is constructing a new facility scheduled to open in late
1998 in San Jose, plans to use the grant for the exhibit's conceptual design
promoting the importance of innovation in technology as a force in shaping a
strong economy and improving the quality of life.   This new multimedia and interactive Medal of Technology exhibit
will be integrated into the "Innovations" theme already selected as a major
gallery in the new museum facility.

<p>

"The American spirit of innovation has always been at the heart of our
country's economic strength and prosperity. Technological innovation
continues to reshape America, creating new jobs and markets, and improving
the standard of living for our people," said Mary L. Good, Under Secretary
of Technology, U.S. Department of Commerce.

<p>

"Silicon Valley is a prime example of how American innovation is alive and
well today.  The fact that 20 percent of the National Medal of Technology
winners over the past 12 years have come from Silicon Valley is a clear
reflection of the region's technological leadership.  The Technology
Administration is very excited to partner with The Tech Museum, itself a
powerhouse of creativity, in developing a national prototype exhibit that
celebrates American innovation and inspires future generations of
innovators," added Dr. Good.

<p>

The Tech Museum broke ground in June for its new 112,000 square feet
facility which will include a large-screen OMNIMAX theater, four main
galleries, hands-on laboratory space for student workshops, and a Center for
Learning for teacher education.  The new $59 million facility will open in
November 1998.  The City of San Jose is a major contributor toward
construction of the new museum building, along with private donations from
many Silicon Valley companies.

<p>

The Museum is a private, nonprofit educational resource currently located
at 145 W. San Carlos Street in downtown San Jose.  Over 500,000 people have
visited the museum since it opened in late 1990 in its temporary facility.
Leaders from many of Silicon Valley's high tech companies sit on the
museum's board of directors.   For general information on The Tech Museum
call (408) 279-7150 or www.thetech.org.

<p>

For more information, please contact:

<p>

Gloria Chun Hoo<br>
Marketing Manager, The Tech Museum of Innovation<br>
(408) 279-7157<br>
<a href="mailto:gloria@thetech.org">gloria@thetech.org</a>


