<h2>Tech Talks '97 to Explore
'Tales From the Final Frontier'</H2>

<P>
SAN JOSE, CA (Dec. 3, 1996) - To cover the person on your holiday gift list
who's interested in what's happening next in outer space, The Tech Museum
of Innovation offers an ideal suggestion.
<P>
Tickets for Tech Talks '97 will allow the person to trek imaginatively into
the dark blue cosmos with an all-star lineup of speakers in "Tales From the
Final Frontier." The four-part series will consist of science fiction grand
master Ray Bradbury on Wednesday, Jan. 29; former Apollo 13 commander James
Lovell on Wednesday, March 5; best-selling author Lawrence Krauss on
Wednesday April 9; and pioneer astronaut Mae Jemison on Wednesday, May 14.
<P>
Series tickets cost $88 for museum members and $100 for non-members. All
1997 Tech Talks will be at 7 p.m. at the Flint Center at DeAnza College. To
order series tickets or for more information call the museum at (408)
279-7150. Individual tickets cost $29 and are available through B A S S
Tickets or at the Flint Center.

<h3>Ray Bradbury, Wednesday, January 29, 1997</h3>
<P>
Known for his magical tales of insightful aliens and futuristic worlds,
Bradbury is most at home in the world of science fiction, where
imagination, fantasy and creativity reign. He has written more than 500
published works, which include short stories, novels, plays, screenplays,
television scripts and verse. His work in such classics as "Fahrenheit
451," "Dandelion Wine," "The Illustrated Man" and "The Martian Chronicles"
evokes the themes of racism, censorship, technology, nuclear war,
humanistic values and the importance of imagination. Since 1985, Bradbury
has adapted 42 of his short stories for "The Ray Bradbury Television
Theater" on USA Cable.
<P>
<h3>Jim Lovell, Wednesday, March 5, 1997</h3>
<P>
Lovell traveled into space four times but is best known for the perilous
Apollo 13 flight in 1970. In 1994 Lovell wrote "Lost Moon," which became
the basis of a 1995 film that touched the hearts of millions. He will
recount the courage and determination as man battled the unknowns of both
space and technology. Lovell was chosen in September 1962 for the space
program after extensive experience as a naval aviator and test pilot. He
served as pilot on the history-making Gemini 7 flight which saw the first
rendezvous of two manned spacecraft in 1965.
<P>
<h3>Lawrence Krauss, Wednesday, April 9, 1997</h3>
<P>
Krauss is an internationally known physicist whose book, "The Physics of
Star Trek," is a national best-seller. His research includes such topics as
the interface between elementary particle physics and cosmology, in which
he explores the early universe, the nature of dark matter, general
relativity and neutrino astrophysics. His investigations into questions
ranging from exploding stars to the issues of the origin of mass in the
universe have made him popular with audiences at such places as the
Smithsonian Air and Space Museum, The National Museum of Natural History
and frequent PBS radio and TV appearances. For those technologically
challenged, he has a knack of turning complex subjects into easily
understood concepts.
<P>
<h3>Mae Jemison, Wednesday, May 14, 1997</h3>
<P>
Jemison, the first woman of color to travel into space, works on projects
to integrate technology and science into our every day lives - culture,
health environment and education. As a teacher and motivator, the Stanford
University graduate engages audiences in her passion for putting technology
to work to create a better world. Her company The Jemison Group Inc. is
dedicated to researching, developing and implementing advanced technologies
suited to the social, political, cultural and economic context of the
individual. Company projects include a satellite-based telecommunications
system to improve health care delivery in West Africa; solar energy project
development; and an international science camp to increase science literacy
for students 12 to 16 years of age that uses experimental curricula.
<P>
 The series is underwritten by <a
href="http://www.lockheed.com">Lockheed-Martin Missiles & Space</a>, <a
href="http://www.att.com">AT & T</a> and <a
href="http://www.scitor.com">Scitor Corporation</a>.
<P>
<P>

<h2>About The Tech</h2>
<P>
The Tech Museum of Innovation is located at 145 W. San Carlos St. in
downtown San Jose. Admission is $6 for adults; $4 for youths, seniors and
students. Members and children 5 and under are free. The museum is open
Tuesday-Sunday 10 a.m.-5 p.m. For general information, call (408) 279-7150
or visit <a href="http://www.thetech.org">http://www.thetech.org</a>.

<p>

For more information, please contact:

<p>

Gloria Chun Hoo<br>
Marketing Manager, The Tech Museum of Innovation<br>
(408) 279-7157<br>
<a href="mailto:gloria@thetech.org">gloria@thetech.org</a>


