	  <td valign=top width="75%">
	    <!-- begin text cell -->

<h2>High-Tech Model Railroad
Ticket to Fun at The Tech</H2>

<P>
SAN JOSE, CA. (Nov. 27, 1996) - For most kids perhaps their fondest holiday
memory was finding a model railroad underneath the tree. The only trouble
was wrangling the controls away from Dad.
<P>
In a special holiday exhibit opening Dec. 16, The Tech Museum of Innovation
couples a model railroad with a practical demonstration of programmable
logic for both kids and adults.
<P>
"The Xilinx Express" model railroad runs on 60 feet of track and allows
users to pick up cars on the siding tracks to make up a complete train. A
stream of data, corresponding to the car order selected, is loaded into the
Xilinx XC5204 field programmable gate array (FPGA) device. The FPGA acts as
a microprocessor controlling the action of the engine.
<P>
The same FPGA can be programmed over and over to order the cars differently
behind the engine. The FPGA device also is connected to a display built
into a model of the San Jose <a href="http://www.xilinx.com">Xilinx</a>
factory. It provides information on the
car sequence selected and the car being picked up as the engine proceeds.
Railroad train enthusiast Tom McMahon, director of product development at
Xilinx, spent 400 hours of his own time building the model railroad in his
garage. The model has been used to demonstrate Xilinx products to customer
traning classes, employees and their families.
<P>
"In addition to using the demonstration to educate employees and customers,
I've really enjoyed showing it to the children of employees," he says. "The
children who have seen the train went home with the idea that Mom and Dad
do something interesting at work."
<P>

<h2>About The Tech</h2>
<P>
The Tech Museum of Innovation is located at 145 W. San Carlos St. in
downtown San Jose. Admission is $6 for adults; $4 for youths, seniors and
students. Members and children 5 and under are free. The museum is open
Tuesday-Sunday 10 a.m.-5 p.m. For general information, call (408) 279-7150
or visit <a href="http://www.thetech.org">http://www.thetech.org</a>.

<p>

For more information, please contact:

<p>

Gloria Chun Hoo<br>
Marketing Manager, The Tech Museum of Innovation<br>
(408) 279-7157<br>
<a href="mailto:gloria@thetech.org">gloria@thetech.org</a>


