<h2>Calendar Listings
for December-January
at The Tech Museum of Innovation</h2>

<h3>DECEMBER</h3>

<b>TECH TALKS</b>

<p>

<b>Hal's Legacy . . . Beyond 2001: A Space Odyssey</b><br>
<P>December 10 - 7 p.m. - Author Dr. David G. Stork discusses his newly
released book "Hal's Legacy," which explores the relationship between
science fiction and technological fact. His book is based on the 1968 movie
"2001: A Space Odyssey." Dr. Stork will be available for book signings.
(The Tech Museum Store will sell copies of the book that night.) Individual
Tech Talk lecture tickets for the fall series are available on a
space-available basis for $6 at the door and $5 for members. Call (408)
279-7158.

<p>

<b>Video phone call to Santa</b><br>
<P>Through December - The oldest of family holiday traditions goes high tech
with the latest in PC video phone technology. The Tech invites kids and
family members to call Santa or a mystery holiday character from a kiosk
containing a Quantex home PC equipped with the new Intel Video Phone with
ProShare technology. Using the kiosk with this new PC video phone
technology, kids will see and talk to their favorite holiday charcters live
on the PC screen.
<P>
<p>
<b>Special Hours</b><br>
<P>December 23, 30 - 10 a.m.-5 p.m. - The museum will be open on Mondays
during the winter holidays.
<P>

<b>SPECIAL EXHIBIT</b><br>
<P>
<b>Lasers, Light & Color</b><br>
<P>Through December - In a whirling kaleidoscope of
color, light and scientific discovery, The Tech's new series of hands-on
and interactive exhibits allow visitors to explore and understand rainbows,
shadows and reflections, as well as discover innovative uses of lights in
holograms, communications, medicine and much more.
<P>
<b>Holiday Members Event</b><br>
<P>December 3 - 6 p.m. - In this event for museum members only, Dr. Lillian
Carson, author of "The Essential Grandparent," will will guide the audience
through her experiences and anecdotes, quotes and exercises, dispelling
grandparenting myths and helping to develop grandparenting strategies to
make the most of this rewarding stage of life. Also, Steve Wozniak,
co-founder of Apple Computer, will join his former students from the fifth
grade class of Lexington School to discuss their learning experiences.
Martha Kendall, author of "Steve Wozniak: Inventor of the Apple Computer,"
will be available to sign her book. Wozniak will sign copies of the
biography as well.
<p>
<b>WORKSHOPS </b>
<P>
<b>Tech Girls!</b><br>
<P>December 7, 14 - 10 a.m.-1 p.m.  - (eight Saturday mornings, twice a month,
September 1996-May 1997) - A program of hands-on experiences for young
women (ages 10-13), exploring the theme: Technology as a Tool of Science.
Limited to 20 participants.
<P>
<b>Robots on Mars</b><br>
<P>December 7 - 1:30 p.m.-4:30 p.m. - Construct complex ROBOTIX planetary
rovers to navigate through challenging, simulated Martian surfaces.
Recommended: any other robotics workshop. $25/non-members, $20
/members.

<P>
<b>Lasers, Light & Color</b><br>
<P>Through December - In a whirling kaleidoscope of color, light and
scientific discovery, The Tech's new series of hands-on and interactive
exhibits allow visitors to explore and understand rainbows, shadows and
reflections, as well as discover innovative uses of lights in holograms,
communications, medicine and much more.
<P>
<b>Flying Machines!</b><br>
<P>December 8 - 1 p.m.-4 p.m. - Build, test and keep  a rubber band-powered,
helicopter-like whirly-gig and a trapezoidal kite. Learn about powered and
unpowered flight. $30/non-members, $25/members.
<P>
<b>World Wide Web Page Making (Intermediate)</b><br>
<P>December 14 - 10 a.m.-1 p.m. - An in-depth look at Web page publishing,
including image alignment, internal links, advanced formatting, and tables.
Prerequisite: An understanding of basic HTML codes. $30/non-members,
$25/members.
<P>
<b>Advanced Robotics Projects</b><br>
<P>Using a variety of creative approaches and
all kinds of construction materials (LEGO and ROBOTIX), build more
advanced types of robotic models, and control them with new Hyperbot Plus
software. Recommended: other robotic workshops. $35/non-members,
$30/members.
<P>
<h3>JANUARY</h3>

<b>TECH TALKS</b>

<p>

<b>Tales From the Final Frontier</b><br>
<P>January 29 - 7 p.m. - Ray Bradbury, author of "The Martian Chronicles,"
"The Illustrated Man," "Fahrenheit 451" and "Something Wicked This Way
Comes" will discuss technology's role and shaping societal values. Widely
regarded as the most important figure in the development of science fiction
as a literary genre, his work evokes the themes of racism, censorship,
technology, nuclear war, humanistic values and the importance of
imagination. All Tech Talks will be at Flint Center for the Performing Arts
at De Anza College. Tickets for the four-part spring series are $100 for
non-museum members and $88 for members. Tickets may be purchased by mail,
at the Flint Center box office and through BASS ticketing.

<h3>FUTURE TECH TALKS</h3>

<p>
March 5 - 7 p.m. - Captain James Lovell Jr., astronaut, is best known for
his fourth and final space flight, the perilous Apollo 13 mission in 1970.
In 1994, Lovell wrote "Lost Moon," the story of the courageous mission of
Apollo 13. In 1995, the film version touched the hearts of millions of
people. Here is a chance to hear firsthand the courage and determination
exhibited as man battled the unknowns of both space and technology. (See
Jan. 29) for further information.
<p>
April 9 - 7 p.m. - Lawrence Krauss, author of the national best-selling
book "The Physics of Star Trek" is an internationally known theoretical
physicist. A widely acclaimed teacher and lecturer, Professor Krauss
reaches out to popular audiences at such places as the Smithsonian Air and
Space Museum, The National Museum of Natural History and frequent PBS radio
and TV appearances. For those technologically challenged, Prof. Krauss has
a knack for turning complex subjects into easily understood concepts. (See
Jan. 29 for further information.)
<P>
May 14 - 7 p.m. - Mae Jemison, pioneer, astronaut and the first woman of
color in space, works on a variety of projects that promote ways to
integrate technology and science into our everyday lives - culture, health,
environment and education. As a teacher and motivator, Dr. Jemison engages
audiences in her passion for putting technology to work to ultimately
create a better world. (See Jan. 29 for further information.)
<p>
<h3>SPECIAL EXHIBIT</h3>
<P>
<b>American Movie Makers: The Dawn of Sound</b>
<P>American Movie Makers: The Dawn of Sound - Opening  Feb. 1 through Labor
Day 1997 - A nostalgic trip into the past, this exhibition blends
technology and cinema artistry to trace the growth of sound movies from
Edison's early experiments to such blockbuster classics as "Gone With the
Wind."
<P>Artifacts from the early days of "talkies" include a Vitaphone Projector,
the first successful movie sound machine, which used separate record disks
to accompany the pictures on film with sound. Other artifacts and
photographs document the evolution of electroacoustics, from Bell
Laboratories' development of effective method of sound amplification of
electrical recording to the Vitaphone's synchronizing of sight and sound.
Photmurals display shots of early movies, and three interactive video
kiosks document 50 years of movie history, including Lindbergh's take-off
for Paris in 1927 and Greta Garbo's first lines on the screen in 1930.
Visitors also can enter a sound booth to sing along with Al Jolson, then
listen to a 1920s-quality recording of their own voices.
<P>

<h2>About The Tech</h2>
<P>
The Tech Museum of Innovation is located at 145 W. San Carlos St. in
downtown San Jose. Admission is $6 for adults; $4 for youths, seniors and
students. Members and children 5 and under are free. The museum is open
Tuesday-Sunday 10 a.m.-5 p.m. For general information, call (408) 279-7150
or visit <a href="http://www.thetech.org">http://www.thetech.org</a>.

<p>

For more information, please contact:

<p>

Gloria Chun Hoo<br>
Marketing Manager, The Tech Museum of Innovation<br>
(408) 279-7157<br>
<a href="mailto:gloria@thetech.org">gloria@thetech.org</a>


