<h2>The Tech Names 4
to Board of Directors</h2>
SAN JOSE, CA (Oct. 10, 1996) - The Tech Museum's Board of Directors
recently added four members: John G. Adler, John P. Cromwell III, James C.
Deichen and Donald F. Liddie.

<p>

Adler is chairman of Adaptec Inc. He joined the company as president in
1985 and was appointed chief executive officer in 1986. He also served as
chief operating officer for the company from May 1985 to December 1986. In
May 1990, Adler was appointed chairman of the company's Board of Directors.
Before joining Adaptec, Adler held various senior level positions at Amdahl
Corp. from 1981-1985. His final position was vice president of product
development responsible for the company's mainframe computer products.
Adler began his career in high technology in 1960, when he joined
International Business Machines as an engineer. By 1979, when he left IBM,
he was manager of IBM's Los Gatos high-end disk drive controller
laboratory.

<p>

A native of Budapest, Hungary, Adler has lived in the United States since
1956. He earned a bachelor's degree in electrical engineering from the
University of Mississippi in 1960 and was a Sloan Executive Fellow at
Stanford University in 1971.

<p>

Cromwell has been managing director at Bentley Hall Von Gehr International
since joining the company last April. BHVGI is an investment banking firm
based in Palo Alto focused on providing financial advisory services for
mergers, acquisitions, divestitures, strategic partnering, and private debt
and equity financing for growth or acquisition. The firm is most active in
semiconductors, networking and computer-related products, as well as in
medical devices and telecommunications. He was formerly industry manager of
Bank of America's High Technology Group, which he managed from 1992. Prior
to joining BofA, he was in the leveraged buyout and security business at
Security Pacific Bank. He received his B.S.C. in finance from Santa Clara
University and his MBA from the University of California, Berkeley. He and
his wife, Donna Chiaro, reside in Woodside.

<p>

Deichen is a senior vice president and marketing manager for BofA's High
Technology Group. He is responsible for delivering the bank's products,
such as credit, corporate finance, trade finance, and payments services, to
large and midcap high technology companies nationally.
Before taking the position in 1995, Deichen was senior vice president and
regional manager of credit products in the bank's U.S. Division, first in
Los Angeles from 1991-1993 and then in San Francisco from 1993-1995. In
both positions, he was responsible for delivering the bank's credit loan
services to large corporate clientele.

<p>

Deichen joined BofA in 1978 as an associate in the Fountain Valley Branch
in Southern California. From 1980-1988, he was vice president, relationship
manager and team leader in the bank's corporate office in Chicago,
providing products to the bank's large corporate clients in the Midwest. In
1988, he returned to Los Angeles and started the Structured Finance Group,
aimed at facilitating leveraged financing to middle market companies
throughout California.

<p>

In 1995, Deichen received the CEO's Eagle Award for his efforts in closing
a major refinancing deal for Del Monte Foods. The Eagle Award in the most
prestigious award attainable and is given only to those individuals within
the bank who demonstrate excellence of the highest level.

<p>

Deichen has a BA and MBA in economics from The Colorado College and
Northwestern University, respectively. He and his spouse, Kathleen, reside
in Kentfield with their three children, Kendall, Troy and Jordan.

<p>

Liddie is the retired executive vice president and chairman of the
Management Committee of Philips Semiconductors North America. He was
responsible for the oversight and governance of all Philips Semiconductors
activities in North America.

<p>

Prior to assuming his position at Philips Semiconductors, for nearly 30
years Liddie had been part of Signetics Corp., a subsidiary of U.S. Philips
Corp. While there he served as vice president, Human Resources and C.A.O.;
vice president, Corporate Services; president, Signetics International
Corp.; manager, Corporate Services; and manager, Manufacturing. Liddie also
founded Signetic's facilities in Utah, Korea and Japan.

<p>

In 1956, Liddie joined Corning Glassworks and filled positions as plant
supervisor of administration services; plant industrial engineer; and
senior industrial engineer.
Liddie received his Bachelor of Science Degree in industrial engineering
from Lehigh University in 1952.

<h2>About The Tech</h2>

The Tech Museum of Innovation is a hands-on museum featuring the emerging
technologies of Silicon Valley and beyond. The Tech is located at 145 W.
San Carlos St. in downtown San Jose. Admission is $6 for adults; $4 for
youths, seniors and students. The Tech is open Tuesday through Sunday 10
a.m.- 5 p.m.

<p>

For more information, please contact:

<p>

Gloria Chun Hoo<br>
Marketing Manager, The Tech Museum of Innovation<br>
(408) 279-7157<br>
<a href="mailto:gloria@thetech.org">gloria@thetech.org</a>


