<h2>Sellout Crowd to Attend
 'Reaching for Stars' Oct. 17</h2>

SAN JOSE, Ca. (Oct. 4, 1996) - Retired Gen. Colin Powell, a sellout crowd
and a stellar "who's who" of Silicon Valley will turn out Oct. 17 for
"Reaching for Stars," a salute to business and innovation benefiting The
Tech Museum of Innovation and the San Jose Metropolitan Chamber of
Commerce.

<p>

Before a sellout crowd at the 6 p.m. dinner event at the Fairmont Hotel's
Imperial Ballroom, "Reaching for Stars" will spotlight The Tech's
commitment to teaching about technology and the Chamber's commitment to
maintain San Jose's prominence as the capital of Silicon Valley.
Powell embodies the American Dream as he rose from humble beginnings in
Harlem, N.Y., to become a four-star general, National Security Advisor,
Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff and mastermind of Desert Storm. The
title of his speech is "From Desert Storm to the End of the Cold War and
Beyond."

<p>

The event promises to be star-studded. In addition to Gen. Powell, many
prominent Silicon Valley leaders will be present, including a recipient of
The Tech's Chairman's Award, Dr. Gordon E. Moore, chairman of Intel
Corporation, and a recipient of the Inspiration Award, Sanford R.
Robertson, chairman of Robertson, Stephens & Company.
Leadership Excellence Awards will be presented by the Chamber. The awards
reflect the Chamber's dedication to developing individuals to lead San Jose
into the 21st century through its Community Leadership San Jose program.
Community Leadership San Jose annually selects potential leaders from
business, the professions and government and provides leadership skills
training as well as familiarization sessions covering issues and
institutions of Silicon Valley.

<p>

Nominees for the award in the community category are Gayle Jones, community
volunteer;  Yosh Uchida, Uchida Enterprises; and Fernando Zazueta, Esq.,
Zazueta Law Office. Nominees in the leadership program's alumni category
are Gerald DeYoung, president, Ruth & Going; Sarah Janigian, community
volunteer; Captain Scott Seaman, San Jose Police Department; and Steve
Wincor, senior systems analyst/consultant, Lockheed Martin Missiles &
Space. Recipients will be announced at the dinner. In support of this
stellar event, the following companies will be represented:
A.T.&T.; Adobe Systems Incorporated; American Airlines, Apple Computer Inc;
Applied Materials Inc.; Arthur Anderson LLP; Bank of America; The Business
Journal; California Eastern Laboratories; Cirrus Logic Inc.; Comerica Bank;
Coopers & Lybrand; GTE Corporation; GVO Inc.; Hewlett-Packard Company; IBM
Corporation: Intel Corporation; KPMG Peat Marwick LLP; Lam Research
Corporation; Lockheed Martin Missiles & Space; M.E. Fox & Co; Microsoft
Corporation; The NASDAQ Stock Market; National Semiconductor Corporation;
Novell Inc.; Pacific Bell; Pacific Gas & Electric; Quantum Corporation; San
Jose Mercury News; San Jose Water Company; Santa Clara Land Title Co.,
Scitor Corporation, 36 KICU TV; Silicon Valley Bank, and United Defense LP.
Government leaders who have confirmed their attendance include Hon. Anna
Eshoo, U.S. Congress; Hon. John Vasconcellos, California State Assembly;
Hon. Jim Cunneen, California State Assembly; Hon. Susan Hammer, mayor of
San Jose; Hon. Judy Nadler, mayor of Santa Clara; and Hon. Pat Dando and
Hon. Charlotte Powers, San Jose City Council.

<p>

<h2>About The Tech</h2>

The Tech Museum of Innovation, 145 W. San Carlos, engages people of all
ages and backgrounds in exploring the technologies affecting their lives,
and seeks to inspire young people to become innovators of the future. Hours
are Tuesday-Sunday 10 a.m.-5 p.m.

<h2>About the San Jose Metropolitan Chamber of Commerce</h2>

The San Jose Metropolitan Chamber of Commerce seeks to maintain the
legendary economy of San Jose and the Silicon Valley through advocacy on
issues affecting the business climate, and wide-ranging programs to improve
the success of individual businesses. The chamber operates with the support
and participation of nearly 2,500 member firms - both large and small -
located from Palo Alto through Gilroy.

<p>

<center>###</center>

<p>

For information, contact:<br>
Gloria Chun Hoo, The Tech Museum - (408) 279-7157 - gloria@thetech.org<br>
Jim Tucker, San Jose Chamber of Commerce - (408) 291-5262 - jitucker@aol.com<br>
Katherine Webb Calhoon, San Jose Chamber of Commerce - (408) 291-5264 -
kwcalhoon@aol.com<br>


	  </td>
	</tr>
