<h2>Dana Atchley, Digital Storyteller,
to Open Fall Tech Talks Oct. 25</h2>

SAN JOSE, CA. (Sept. 16, 1996) - Modern-day storyteller Dana Atchley will
spin his electronic yarns around a video campfire as he presents his
acclaimed "Next Exit" performance at the Tech Museum of Innovation Friday,
Oct. 25, at 7 p.m.

<p>

Atchley is the first performer in the Art of Technology of the museum's
fall Tech Talks series, which  features artists whose work stands as a
testament to creative versatility. The series is underwritten by <a href="http://www.lockheed.com">Lockheed
Martin Missiles & Space</a> and <a href="http://www.microsoft.com">Microsoft Corporation</a> and is co-hosted by the
San Jose Museum of Art.

<p>

Tickets for the four-part series are available at The Tech for $20 and
include admission to the museum. Individual Tech Talk lectures are
available for $6 at the door and $5 for museum members. For ticket
information, call (408) 279-7150 or contact the museum at
http://www.thetech.org.

<p>

Atchley's autobiographical one-man show "Next Exit" has been in the making
for more than eight years and harnesses new digital technologies to span
more than 150 years of Atchley's personal and family archives.
Atchley has kept every image he has taken since he got his first camera at
age 7. He spent the 60s exploring the frontiers of art and technology, the
70s traveling America with his one-man multimedia performance road show,
and the 80s producing more than 500 segments for broadcast and cable TV.
The 90s have been devoted to the creation of "Next Exit," a multimedia
theatrical performance, and to the development of the electronic family
album.

<p>

"Atchley was inspiring...a high-tech shaman," said reviewer Michael Wiese
of Videography magazine. "The most innovative and free stuff I've seen
yet."

<p>

Atchley is the director of D3TV, a partner in the Digital Treehouse, and a
founding partner of the San Francisco  Digital Media Center.
"By any standard I am a techno junkie - which is no surprise since I grew
up with a father whose passion was electronics and ham radio
communication," he said. "He was into antennas; I like entertainment. ...
But while devouring the new technologies, I also want the freedom of an
old-time campfire storyteller who could conjure up any vision from the
flames. My flames are the cool flickering of a digital campfire."

<p>

The remaining lineup for the fall Tech Talks is as follows:

<p>

<b>Xerox PARC: Merging the Worlds of Art and Technology</b><br>
<b>Friday, Nov. 8, 7 p.m.</b>

<p>

Find out what happens when professional artists work in collaboration with
research scientists and their technical ideas. The noted <a href="http://www.parc.xerox.com">Xerox PARC (Palo
Alto Research Center)</a> program opens up new possibilities for aesthetics in
photography, telecommunications and creative documents. Rich Gold from
Xerox PARC will lead the panel of artists and researchers.

<p>

<b>Chico MacMurtrie - A Dance of Robots</b><br>
<b>Thursday, Nov. 21, 7 p.m.</b>

<p>

The Tech Museum's groundbreaking was stunning, thanks to the troupe of
anthropomorphic robots created by Chico MacMurtrie. Just back from a
European tour with his family of robots, MacMurtrie will discuss his
techniques, ideas and demonstrate some of his creative and frolicsome
robots.

<p>

<b>"Hal's Legacy ... Beyond 2001: A Space Odyssey"</b><br>
<b>Tuesday, Dec. 10, 7 p.m.</b>

<p>

Author Dr. David G. Stork will discuss his newly released book "Hal's
Legacy," which explores the relationship between science fiction and
technological fact. His book is based on the 1968 movie "2001: A Space
Odyssey." Dr. Stork will be available for book signings. (The Tech Museum
Store will sell copies of the book that night.)

<h3>About The Tech</h3>

The Tech Museum of Innovation, 145 W. San Carlos, engages people of all
ages and backgrounds in exploring and experiencing the technologies
affecting their lives, and inspires young people to become innovators in
developing the technologies of the future. The museum is open
Tuesday-Sunday 10 a.m.-5 p.m. Admission to The Tech is $6 for adults and $4
for youths, students and seniors. For more information, call 279-7150 or
visit The Tech on the World Wide Web at http://www.thetech.org.

<p>

For more information, please contact:

<p>

Gloria Chun Hoo<br>
Marketing Manager, The Tech Museum of Innovation<br>
(408) 279-7157<br>
<a href="mailto:gloria@thetech.org">gloria@thetech.org</a>


