FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE

<p>

<h2>The Tech Offers Visitors a Taste of Award-Winning Multimedia and Web sites
during September and October</h2>

SAN JOSE, CA (Sept. 9, 1996) - Beginning Tuesday, September 17, The Tech
Museum of Innovation in San Jose, CA, will offer visitors a chance to truly
explore and experience 20 of the top new media applications and Web sites.
The featured applications and Web sites are all 1996 NewMedia INVISION award
winners.

<p>

On Saturday, September 21 from 1 to 3 p.m. NewMedia Magazine and The
Tech will conduct a program featuring some of the creative designers
of several of the award-winning titles featured at The Tech.
Designers will demonstrate their work, talk about the creative process
and examine issues affecting the design and development of new works
using cutting edge technology tools in multimedia.  The program, led
by NewMedia Magazine's senior editor, Gillian Newson, will allow the
public to meet some of the top creative people from the area.

<p>

Gold, bronze and silver winners in select categories will be featured
at the museum through the end of October and will include a wide-range
of titles in several categories from educational to edutainment to
training productions. Visitors to the museum, with paid admission,
will have access to all of the featured programs.

<p>

This is the first year that The Tech is teaming up with NewMedia
Magazine to present to the public a sample of innovative multimedia
products that demonstrate the most creative and innovative new media
applications of the year.  This year's NewMedia INVISION Awards
program included 900 entries in 71 categories.  The awards were
presented in June during the COMDEX/Spring computer trade show in
Chicago.

<p>

"The Tech Museum is delighted with this new partnership with NewMedia
Magazine, a publication which looks at cutting-edge hardware, software
and on-line tools for new media development and the Internet," said
Peter Giles, president of The Tech Museum of Innovation. "This
Festival of NewMedia INVISION award winners gives our visitors a
chance to sample the best and the most innovative new media programs
and Web sites being developed."

<p>

Some of the featured winning titles include: "Crime Scouts" a
multimedia educational CD-ROM which explores the challenges and
temptations of young people who are growing up with drugs, gangs,
lying and stealing.  "Critical Mass: America's Race to Build the
Atomic Bomb" is a story of the people and events behind the
U.S. effort to build the first atomic bomb, while "The Cypher" is an
interactive series taking a reader through ten centuries and four
worlds to solve a mystery.

<p>

In keeping with the election year, three titles are presented
including "Oval Office: Challenge of the Presidency" which engages
high school students to experience first-hand the roles and
responsibilities of being the president of the U.S., while Web sites
"Rock the Vote" and "Candidate 96" will engage surfers to keep up with
the presidential elections.

<p>

"On the Road with BB King" is an interactive autobiography of the King
of Blues complete with song clips, while a Gold Medal winner "Inventor
Labs" allows users to explore the laboratories and inventions of
Thomas Edison, Alexander Graham Bell and James Watt.

<p>

"NewMedia INVISION Award winners represent the best work that creative
minds are producing in the field of digital media," said Richard
Landry, president and CEO of NewMedia Magazine.  "By identifying the
top applications of new media technology, whether they are World Wide
Web sites or CD-ROM titles, we believe that the INVISION Awards
program is setting standards of quality for an explosive new
industry."

<p>

The Tech Museum is open Tuesday through Sunday, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. and is
located at 145 W. San Carlos Street, in downtown San Jose, across from the
Convention Center.  Admission is $6 adults, $4 youth, students and seniors.
Children ages five and younger are free. For more information call (408)
279-7150 or see The Tech's Website: www.thetech.org.

<p>

<center>###</center>

<p>

For more information contact:<br>
Gloria Chun Hoo, The Tech, (408) 279-7157 or <a href="mailto:gloria@thetech.org">gloria@thetech.org</a><br>
Gillian Newson, NewMedia Magazine (415) 573-5170 X224, or <a href="mailto:gnewson@newmedia.com">GNEWSON@newmedia.com</a><br>


