<b>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE</b>
<p>

<h2>The Tech Museum to Peak Behind Curtain 
of Nanotechnology, Futuristic Theater,  Sept. 11</h2>

<b>Free Admission to New Media Colloquia, Museum</b>
<p>

SAN JOSE, Ca. (Sept. 3, 1996) - The Tech Museum of Innovation will present
an engrossing look at some of the latest work from the Bay Area computer
art communities with a pair of virtual artists and thinkers as part of the
1996 New Media Colloquia at 6:30 p.m. Wednesday, Sept. 11.

<p>

Computer art evangelists Phillip Esparza and Charles Ostman will explore
the state of computer art as it approaches the millennium. Their talks are
free and open to the public.

<p>

At  6:30 p.m., Ostman will track the role of nanotechnology from today's
"decision rendering" efforts to the future reality of synthetic brains
playing at virtual theater. At  8 p.m., Esparza of El Teatro Campesino will
describe a transition from the traditional theater to an inevitably
electronic future. An open session will follow the two talks at 9 p.m.

<p>

The Berkeley Contemporary Opera and Seybold San Francisco at the San
Francisco Museum of Modern Art, the Exploratorium and The Tech are
presenting the lively series of talks throughout the week on computers and
art past 2020. Each talk presents computer artists and new media experts
using the artistic dimensions of current new media work as a touchstone for
exploring art activity throughout the world today.

<p>

Before you enter Ostman's world, you must imagine that it is possible to
create tiny machines no more than a billionth of an inch across. If you
blew up a baseball to the size of the earth, these machines would become
visible, about the size of grapes.

<p>

Imagine you could build those machines atom by atom, molecule by molecule
and manipulate atoms individually to fabricate novel devices with
extraordinary products. You could cure cancer by drinking a medicine
stirred into your favorite fruit juice or develop a supercomputer no bigger
than a human cell. A four-person, surface-to-orbit spacecraft would be no
larger and cost no more than the family car.

<p>

Finally, imagine that these organic systems can be used to manufacture
sentience, not consumer products. These nanotechnological machines are
actually living, growing systems and can adopt themselves to new tasks or
situations.

<p>

You've now entered the world of Ostman, a nanotech visionary who finds
compelling parallels between the shifting architecture of nanotechnology
systems and the human mind. The anticipated payoff for mastering this
technology is beyond any human accomplishment thus far.
Join Ostman as he plots the fascinating course of his own work. A Ph.D. in
physics is not required!

<p>

To many, El Teatro Campesino is one of the very best performance groups in
America. Over a long history the company's generous artistry and humanity
have been one of California's crown jewels.

<p>

Esparza, a member of the Teledramatics faculty at California State
University, Monterey Bay, has been with El Teatro since its early days when
the company would perform guerrilla theater for farm workers from the back
of a truck.

<p>

Today, however, his revolutionary spirit has brought him to consider the
Internet, CD-ROM and other emerging tools of new media. Esparza's interest
in computers is no lark - he believes that learning how to tap the power of
technology will be crucial to the survival and success of arts
organizations in the coming years.

<p>

At The Tech, he will discuss the high-tech course he is on. His talk will
hold insight for others eager to see a vibrant arts community in the next
century tap the power of technology.

<p>

<h3>About The Tech</h3>

The Tech Museum of Innovation, 145 W. San Carlos St. in downtown San Jose,
engages people of all ages and backgrounds in exploring and experiencing
the technologies affecting their lives and to inspire young people to
become innovators in developing the technologies of the future.
The museum's hours are Tuesday-Sunday 10 a.m.-5 p.m.  The museum is closed
Mondays.

<p>

For more information, please contact:

<p>

Gloria Chun Hoo<br>
Marketing Manager, The Tech Museum of Innovation<br>
(408) 279-7157<br>
<a href="mailto:gloria@thetech.org">gloria@thetech.org</a>

	
