<h2>National Science Foundation Awards Major Grant
To Tech Museum To Produce Explorations Exhibit</h2>

SAN JOSE, Cal. (Aug. 26, 1996) - The Tech Museum of Innovation today
announced it was awarded a grant of $644,700 by the National Science
Foundation (NSF) to support production of Explorations, one of four theme
galleries that will open in The Tech's new museum building in fall 1998.
This exhibition will demonstrate how science and technology are extending
our ability to explore the Earth, its oceans and the universe.
Visitors to the new exhibit will maneuver a submersible robot in an ocean
aquarium, learn the likely places for Bay Area earthquakes, see a research
station on the moon and discover how to use the Hubble Space Telescope.
"Awards by the National Science Foundation are granted through a very
competitive process of peer review," Tech President Peter Giles said. "We
appreciate this national recognition of our ability to produce world-class
educational exhibitions."

<p>

This is the fourth NSF grant received by The Tech. Previous grants
supported exhibit planning and prototyping for Innovation, another
exhibition that will open in 1998; development of The Tech Teacher
Institute training program; and implementation of Tech educational programs
in collaboration with industry partners.

<p>

In addition to the NSF, major contributors to Explorations  are
Lockheed-Martin Corp., the David and Lucile Packard Foundation and the S.D.
Bechtel, Jr. Foundation.

<p>

The Tech Museum of Innovation's mission is to engage people of all ages and
backgrounds in exploring and experiencing the technologies affecting their
lives, and to inspire young people to become innovators in developing the
technologies of the future.

<p>

The National Science Foundation is an independent federal agency charged
with promoting and advancing scientific and engineering progress and
understanding throughout the nation. The NSF annually awards $3 billion in
grants competitively to educational and other institutions for research and
education in the sciences, mathematics and engineering.

<p>

For more information, please contact:

<p>

Gloria Chun Hoo<br>
Marketing Manager, The Tech Museum of Innovation<br>
(408) 279-7157<br>
<a href="mailto:gloria@thetech.org">gloria@thetech.org</a>


