<h2>Former Moonwalker Buzz Aldrin
Tech Museum Guest Sept. 19</h2>

SAN JOSE, Ca. (Aug. 21, 1996) - As a space futurist, former moonwalker Buzz
Aldrin has a vision to share about the future of man's exploration outward
to the planets and stars.

<p>

Visitors to The Tech Museum of Innovation can question the ex-astronaut
about his vision - and buy his latest book for signing - when Aldrin is
interviewed Sept. 19 at 7 p.m. by radio host Moira Gunn for her weekly
National Public Radio show TechNation, sponsored in part by The Tech.
Admission to the event will be $15 for the public and $10 for Tech members.
The audience members will have the opportunity to ask live, on-the-air
questions.

<p>

Aldrin will share his vision, answering such questions as "Will we ever
take vacations in space - book seats aboard a space craft and stay in a
hotel  orbiting the earth? Or perhaps on the moon?"

<p>

The museum gift shop will be selling Aldrin's new book,  "Encounter with
Tiber,"  which was released in July and has sold out in its first printing.
Visitors to The Tech can join Aldrin for a signing session after the radio
show.

<p>

The exhilarating novel chronicles a new generation of space heroes in the
21st century. Aldrin, as someone who has been there, writes about a new
space race sparked by a bitter feud between scientist-astronaut Chris
Terence and visionary entrepreneur Sig Jarlsbourg.

<p>

The two enemies are determined to claim the frontier blazed by the Apollo
pioneers. But a radio beacon from deep space, from a world called Tiber,
will bring both men together - and lead one of them to his doom.
Tech Nation is heard locally on KQED-FM (88.5) on Sundays at 9 p.m. and
KALW-FM (91.7) at 10 a.m. Tuesdays.

<p>

Radio host Gunn, the first female to earn a Ph.D. in mechanical engineering
from Purdue University, has a background in the space program herself as a
former NASA engineer and scientist. She serves as an adjunct professor at
the University of San Francisco and also as a consulting robotics expert.
The focus of her show is that whatever technology is, people make and use
it and it's people who need to understand it. Her focus always is on how
technology affects people.

<p>

This slant and her extremely engaging, high-energy style brings an
understanding of technology right into your life.

<h3>About The Tech</h3>

The Tech Museum of Innovation's mission is to engage people of all ages and
backgrounds in exploring and experiencing the technologies affecting their
lives, and to inspire young people to become innovators in developing the
technologies of the future.

<p>

Through Labor Day, the museum is open Monday-Saturday 10 .m. to 6 p.m. and
Sundays noon to 6 p.m.. After Labor Day, the museum's hours will be
Tuesday-Saturday 10 a.m.-5 p.m. and Sundays noon to 5 p.m.

<p>

For more information, please contact:

<p>

Gloria Chun Hoo<br>
Marketing Manager, The Tech Museum of Innovation<br>
(408) 279-7157<br>
<a href="mailto:gloria@thetech.org">gloria@thetech.org</a>


