<td valign=top width=75%>


<h2>Calendar Listings for September-October 1996
at The Tech</h2>

FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
CONTACT:    <a href="mailto:gloria@thetech.org">Gloria Chun Hoo</a><br>
Aug. 14, 1996   (408) 279-7105
<p>

SEPTEMBER
<hr>

Free Days<br>
<b>Labor Day Weekend</b> - Saturday and Sunday, 10 a.m.-6 p.m.; Monday, 10 a.m.-6
p.m. - The Tech opens its doors free to the community to celebrate the 21st
Festival of the Arts as a Tapestry In Talent partner. Visitors to the
festival's Family Expo area can engage in different stages of aviation with
kite, hot air balloon and paper plane construction. Saturday, visitors will
experience "The Safe Moves City," a bicycle rodeo that educates children to
the traffic controls that they encounter every day. Sunday and Monday, they
can check out big high-tech building equipment from Barnes Construction.
Also, visitors will have the opportunity to try unlimited tricks and
maneuvers on AstroJax,  a Bay Area physicist's new toy invention that has
been described as the future of the yo-yo.
<p>
<b>1996 New Media Colloquia - Free Talks</b><br>
September 11 - 6:30 p.m.-9 p.m. -  Futurist and writer for Mondo 2000,
Charles Ostman will speak  at 6:30 p.m. on "Nanotechnology and the
Invocation Rapture."  If you are familiar with biocomputing only for its
potential to revolutionize computer technology, join this nanotechnology
futurist  as he tracks today's "decision rendering" efforts to the future
reality of synthetic brains playing at a virtual theater. At 8 p.m.,
Phillip Esparza of El Teatro Campesino will discuss the "Theater of the
Future." His talk will cover the Internet, CD-ROM and other emerging tools
of new media and will hold insight for others eager to see a vibrant arts
community in the next century. The free event is sponsored by Seybold, San
Francisco, in conjunction with the Berkeley Contemporary Opera.
<p>

<b>Buzz Aldrin Visit</b><br>
September 19 - 7 p.m. - Former astronaut and second to walk on the moon,
Buzz Aldrin, will be interviewed at The Tech by radio host Moira Gunn for
her weekly National Public Radio show, TechNation, sponsored by The Tech.
The public is invited. Fee: $15 for the public, $10 for Tech members.
Aldrin will sign copies of his new book, the fictional "Encounter with
Tiber," which will be sold at the museum.

<p>

<b>Multimedia Developers Fest</b><br>
September 21 - 1 p.m. to 3 p.m. - Meet and get answers from award winners
and developers in the Festival of NewMedia invision as they explain the
development of their projects and answer questions for the public. Free
with paid admission museum.

<p>

<b>Home School Day '96</b><br>
September 25 - 10 a.m.-5 p.m. - A special day for home schoolers. Students
can scavenge the World Wide Web for answers to selected questions in
science and mathematics,  become "Science Sleuths" to solve a mystery in an
interactive exhibit on CD-ROM and re-create experiments done aboard the
space shuttle.  Special admission rates are $3 for home-school students and
$5 for adults. Labs requiring preregistration are $6 per student and
includes admission to the exhibit hall. Please call (408) 279-7173 to
preregister for labs.

<p>

OCTOBER
<hr>

<b>"Reaching for the Stars"</b><br>
October 17 - Fairmont Hotel, 6 p.m.-10 p.m. - Retired Gen. Colin Powell
will underscore The Tech's commitment to teaching about technology and San
Jose's prominence as the capital of Silicon Valley. Benefiting both The
Tech and the San Jose Metropolitan Chamber of Commerce, this dinner event
will feature the annual presentation of The Tech's Chairman's and
Inspiration awards. Gen. Powell, mastermind of Desert Storm, will present
the keynote address. The Chairman's Award will be presented to the
cofounders of Intel Corp., Gordon E. Moore and the late Robert N. Noyce.
The Inspiration Award will be given to Apple Computer and Sanford Robertson
of Robertson, Stephens and Co. To purchase tickets, contact Dick King at
279-7153.

<p>

ONGOING
<hr>

<b>Festival of NewMedia Invision Winners</b><br>
September and October  - The Tech and NewMedia Magazine will present 17
winners  in the NewMedia Invision Awards featuring the most innovative new
media applications. There's "Oval Office: Challenge of the Presidency,"
showing the challenges that confront the president, and "Managing Across
Difference," presenting diversity as an opportunity for greater personal
and organizational effectiveness. Visitors will explore  "Surf this Disc,"
a CD-ROM music catalog with samples from 500 albums;  and view "Public
Shelter,"  exploring the social, environmental and political issues of
America in the Atomic Age. Also featured will be "Inventor Labs," the first
in a series of CD-ROMs developed by Red Hill Studios of Sausalito, that
jumps into the worlds of three great inventors - Thomas Edison, Alexander
Graham Bell and James Watt.
<p>

<b>Lasers, Light & Color</b><br>
Through December - In a whirling kaleidoscope of color, light and
scientific discovery, The Tech's new series of hands-on and interactive
exhibits allow visitors to explore and understand rainbows, shadows and
reflections, as well as discover innovative uses of lights in holograms,
communications, medicine and much more.

<p>

<b>Workshops</b><br>
The ABC's of the Internet with Netscape
September 7 - 10 a.m.-12:30 p.m. - Get an overview of the Internet. Surf
the Web with a popular Web browser, use search engines, learn to send and
receive e-mail and more. $25/non-members, $20/members.

<p>

<b>World Wide Web Page Making (Basics)</b><br>
September 14 - 10 a.m.-1 p.m. - A basic introduction to HTML coding and Web
page publishing. Learn how to make your own home page and links.
$25/non-members, $20/members.

<p>
<b>LEGO(R) Robots (Intro)</b><br>
September 15 - 1:30 p.m.-4:30 p.m. - A popular introduction to constructing
LEGO(R) robotic devices, and basic navigation and computer programming
skills, with Hyperbot(R) software. $25/non-members, $20/members.

<p>

<b>World Wide Web Page Making (Intermediate)</b><br>
September 21 - 10 a.m.-1 p.m. - An in-depth look at Web page publishing,
including image alignment, internal links, advanced formatting, tables.
Prerequisite: An understanding of basic HTML codes. $30/non-members,
$25/members.

<p>

<b>How to Draw: Cartooning</b><br>
September 28 - 10 a.m.-12:30 p.m. - Learn the basics of cartooning, the
secrets of character design, choosing colors, creating speed, sound and
expression as well as how to create original cartoons. $25/non-members,
$20/members.

<p>

<b>Model Rockets</b><br>
September 28-29 - 1-4 p.m. The Tech and DeAnza College - Build, design and
blast off a rocket that is yours to keep (and reusable) after the workshop.
Flies 30 stories high. Requires two afternoons. Launch day (second day) is
at DeAnza College. Safe and fun. $50/non-members, $40/members.

<p>

<b>LEGO(R) Robots Family Workshop</b><br>
September 29 - 1:30 p.m.-4:30 p.m. - An introduction to
computer-controlled LEGO(R) robots, for family groups (one adult and one
child, minimum age 6). Limited to 6 groups. $35/non-members (per group),
$30/members (per group).

<p>

<b>Hollywood Scriptwriting and Animation</b><br>
October 5 - 10 a.m.-12:30 p.m. - Write your own script and direct your own
animations, with talking characters, titles, sound effects.
$25/non-members, $20/members.

<p>
<b>Inside a Computer's Inside</b><br>
October 5 - 1 p.m.-4 p.m. - Take apart and reassemble a working PC and
learn how this incredible machine functions. Limited to 12 participants,
ages 10 and above. $25/non-members, $20 members.

<p>

<b>Eureka: I Can Draw!</b><br>
October 12 - 10 a.m-12:30 p.m . - Interactively learn the basics of
drawing, shadows and shading, portions and more. $25/non-members,
$20/members.

<p>

<b>Simpsons Cartoon Studio</b><br>
October 19 - 10 a.m.-12:30 p.m. - Create and watch your very own Simpsons
cartoons, one scene or entire episode, with authentic voices, backgrounds,
props, special effects and music. $25/non-members, $20 members.

<p>

<b>LEGO(R) Robotic Construction</b><br>
October 19 - 1:30 p.m.-4:30 p.m. - Construct robotic machines from LEGO
Dacta's Simple Gears minikit. Projects include a merry-go-round and a
hill-climbing tricycle (to take home following the workshop).
$35/non-members, $30/members.

<p>

<b>Computerized  Electronics</b><br>
October 26 - 10 a.m.-1 p.m. - Virtual and hands-on electronic projects,
including radio, siren, burglar alarm, and more. Learn the basics of
electricity. $30/non-members, $25/members.

<p>

<b>Robots on Mars</b><br>
October 27 - 1:30 p.m.-4:30 p.m. - Construct complex ROBOTIX planetary
rovers to navigate through challenging, simulated Martian surfaces.
Recommended: any other robotics workshop. $25/non-members, $20/members.

<p>

TECH TALKS
<hr>

<b>Dana Atchley - "Next Exit" Performance</b><br>
October 25 - 7 p.m. - Dana Atchley, a digital storyteller, presents "Next
Exit," a multimedia road trip spinning electronic yarns around a video
campfire. Called a "high tech shaman," Atchley is a techno junkie who uses
sophisticated multimedia to create state-of-the-art art.

<p>

<b>Artist in Residence Program</b><br>
November 8 - 7 p.m. - Xerox PARC: Merging the Worlds of Art and Technology:
What happens when professional artists work in collaboration with research
scientists and their technical ideas? The noted Xerox PARC (Palo Alto
Research Center) program opens up new possibilities for aesthetics in
photography, telecommunications and creative documents. Rich Gold from
Xerox PARC will lead the panel of artists and researchers.

<p>

<b>Amorphic Robot Works</b><br>
November 21 - 7 p.m. - The Tech Museum's groundbreaking was stunning,
thanks to the troupe of anthropomorphic robots created by artist Chico
MacMurtrie. Just back from a European tour with his family of robots,
MacMurtrie will discuss his techniques, ideas and demonstrate some of his
creative and frolicsome robots.

<p>
<b>Hal's Legacy . . . Beyond 2001: A Space Odyssey</b><br>
December 10 - 7 p.m. - Author Dr. David G. Stork discusses his newly
released book "Hal's Legacy," which explores the relationship between
science fiction and technological fact. His book is based on the 1968 movie
"2001: A Space Odyssey." Dr. Stork will be available for book signings.
(The Tech Museum Store will sell copies of the book that night.)

<p>

        Series tickets are available at The Tech for $20 and include
admission to the museum. Individual Tech Talk lecture tickets are available
at $6 at the door and $5 for members. Special prices for members of The
Tech and for the San Jose Museum of Art, co-sponsor of the series, are $15
for the series. For ticket information, call (408) 279-7158.

<p>
<center>###</center>
<p>

        The Tech Museum of Innovation is a hands-on museum featuring the
emerging technologies of Silicon Valley and beyond. The Tech is as 145 W.
San Carlos St. in downtown San Jose. Admission is $6 for adults; $4 for
youths, seniors and students. Members and children 5 and under are free.
For general information, call 408-279-7150.

</td>

