<p>
<h3>Mysteries of Science Explored at The Tech Museum</h3>
<b>SAN JOSE, CA, June 18, 1996</b> - How do you turn a penny into gold? How can you catch a kidnapper of pets 
using science? How can you explore the World Wide Web  using your TV set?

<p>

These and other exciting discoveries await visitors in demonstrations
the weekend of June 22-23 at The Tech Museum of Innovation, 145 W. San
Carlos St., San Jose. Hours will be 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.

<p>

As part of <a href="/events/ibm.html">IBM Month at The Tech</a>, a demonstration of a new technology
under development at IBMs Almaden Lab will show how your
television set can be turned into a World Wide Web terminal. There
also will be a computer terminal with a browser so visitors can
explore the graphical portion of the Internet.

<p>

IBM scientists also will show children of all ages  and even some
adult investors  how to turn pennies into gold.
The secret: Coat the copper surface with zinc and heat. The zinc
alloys with the copper to form brass. (Well, we didnt say it was
real gold.).

<p>

Visitors will use a scientific technique called chromatography to
catch a pet- napper. By analyzing the type of ink used in
ransom notes, participants will be able to bring the villains
to justice.

<p>

Another demonstration will show how novel materials change with
heating or cooling and snap back into their original form through
shape memory. Visitors will see how superconductive materials
can make magnets literally float in space.

<p>

In addition, there will be a demonstration of technology called
Query By Image Content (QBIC), which enables users to store
and retrieve images based on color, shape and texture. The technology
has numerous applications in the retail industry, as well as for
medicine and geologic exploration.

<p>

Also on display is an exhibit chronicling how some key technologies
have evolved over time, along with the 305 RAMAC, the worlds first
commercial disk drive, created in San Jose and announced by IBM in
1956. All displays will continue at The Tech through June 30.

<p>

<a href="/">The Tech Museum</a> is the premier science and technology museum in the
greater San Jose metropolitan area with a mission to engage people of
all ages and backgrounds in exploring and experiencing the
technologies changing their lives, and to inspire young people to
become innovators in developing the technologies of the future.

<p>

Admission to The Tech is $6 for adults, $4 for students, children and
seniors and free for children under 5.

<p>

The Tech is open 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Tuesday through Sunday between
September and June. From July 1 through Labor Day, The Tech will be
open Monday through Saturday, 10 a.m. to 6 p.m., Sunday noon to 6 p.m.

<p>
<center>
