<h3>
The Tech Museum of Innovation Unveils HyperTech:
An Interactive Museum on the World Wide Web
at http://www.thetech.org
</h3>

<b>SAN JOSE, CA. (June 11, 1996)</b> --

At the ground breaking ceremony for its new $59 million museum, The
Tech Museum of Innovation today unveiled <a http://www.thetech.org/hyper">HyperTech</a>, an interactive
technology museum on the World Wide Web at <a href="http://www.thetech.org/">http://www.thetech.org</a>
featuring on-line exhibits created by The Tech and its technology
partners including educational institutions, renowned scientists and
technologists, local community groups, and corporations.

<p>

Each online exhibit fits within one of the four theme areas
that will be a part of the new Tech Museum: Innovation, Explorations,
Life Tech and Communications and Information.  HyperTech exhibits will
continue to grow as additional corporate and educational partners are
recruited.

<p>

The Tech Museum's first HyperTech exhibit is "<a href="http://www.thetech.org/hyper/robots/teaser">Get A Grip On
Robotics</a>," which explores robotics and the effects robots have on
people's lives.  The Tech's first web development partner is <a href="http://www.adobe.com/">Adobe
Systems</a>, which has worked with The Tech to develop "The Technology and
Science of Color."  Another partner, <a href="http://www.ucsc.edu/">University of California at Santa
Cruz</a>, has partnered with The Tech to create four virtual exhibits on
Earthquakes, the DNA/Human Genome Project, Lasers, and Privacy and
Security on the Internet.

<p>

Peter Giles, Tech Museum president and CEO, said, "HyperTech
reflects our commitment to link together institutions and
organizations interested in helping us provide educational,
non-commercial information to a global community."

<p>

"HyperTech will enable Web visitors to interact with museum
guests and exhibits, whether it be controlling a robot or listening to
a live lecture," Giles continued.

<p>

The Tech's web site and HyperTech are under the
direction of Mike Rose, WWW publisher at The Tech. Craig Rosa is
responsible for exhibit development, and Eric Schwartz manages
engineering and technical aspects as the site's webmaster.

<p>

HyperTech is funded by a $250,000 grant from an anonymous
donor. Advertising sales will be handled by Rose and the San Jose ad
agency, Pagliaro/Kuhlman.  The Tech's web site will be audited by
I/PRO (Internet Profiles Corporation) to provide site demographics.

<p>

<h3>About The Tech</h3>

<p>
         
The Tech Museum of Innovation, a private non-profit
educational resource, is the premier science and technology museum
serving Northern California area with a specific focus on the advanced
technologies emerging from Silicon Valley and beyond.  By providing
hands-on, engaging experiences and informal learning, as well as
school field trips and labs, The Tech is a leader in the region in
promoting scientific literacy and understanding about the technologies
changing our lives.
         
<p>

The museum is currently located at 145 W. San Carlos Street
in downtown San Jose and is open Tuesday through Saturday, 10 a.m. to
5 p.m. and Sundays, noon to 5 p.m.  From July through Labor Day
weekend, the museum will be open Mondays and hours will be extended
until 6 p.m. daily.  For more information about ongoing programs,
special exhibits or admission, call (408) 279-7150, or visit The Tech
on the World Wide Web at <a href="http://www.thetech.org/">http://www.thetech.org</a>.

<p>
