<p>
<h3>
The Tech Museum of Innovation Breaks Ground for New $59 Million Museum
<p>
Silicon Valley Luminaries Break Ground with Help of Robots
</h3>
<b>SAN JOSE, CA (June 11, 1996)</b> --

Surrounded by children and youth -- the technology innovators of the
future -- San Jose Mayor Susan Hammer, Tech Museum of Innovation
President Peter Giles, and Silicon Valley legend William Hewlett,
co-founder of Hewlett-Packard Company, today ceremoniously broke
ground to start construction of a new $59 million, 112,000 square
ft. home for The Tech Museum of Innovation in downtown San Jose.

<p>

The local luminaries were joined by community, industry, and education
leaders, and internationally-renown architect Ricardo Legorreta, who
designed the three-story facility, which will be a focal point for the
city's downtown, and one of the West Coast's largest
science/technology educational centers. The new facility is scheduled
to open on November 1, 1998.

<p>

"This is a historic moment, dedicated to the innovative spirit and
commitment of the men and women of Silicon Valley," said Peter Giles,
president and CEO of The Tech Museum of Innovation.  "With today's
ground breaking, we begin building a center for experimentation and
discovery.  Here at The Tech we will kindle the flame of curiosity and
the desire to learn."

<p>

Mayor Susan Hammer said that the City of San Jose, known as the
"capital of Silicon Valley," will now have a world-class museum that
will not only inspire today's young people to continue the innovative
spirit born in the region, but will greatly contribute to making San
Jose a cultural center.

<p>

Flocked by youngsters and high school students, William Hewlett, one
of Silicon Valley's earliest pioneers and co-founder of
Hewlett-Packard Company, was given the honor of shoveling the first
spade of dirt.  A long-time supporter of The Tech Museum, Hewlett and
his wife Rosemary have contributed $2.5 million to the museum's
capital campaign.

The ceremony, held at the corner of Park and Market Streets in
downtown San Jose, was concluded with a dramatic performance by four
robots created by San Francisco artist Chico MacMurtrie.  His
anthropomorphic, kinetic sculptures for the ground breaking included a
slow, dramatic advance from a 30 feet long, 10 feet tall robot called
"Too Big Dog Monkey" and drumming by a smaller robot.  Two other
smaller robots, in quick bursts of movement, scattered or lifted dirt
in a symbolic ground breaking action.

<p>
     
The City of San Jose, through its Redevelopment Agency, is
contributing $39 million toward the construction of the building.  The
museum is raising $20 million in cash from private sources plus
another $15-$20 million in donated services and equipment for the
interior of the museum and its exhibits.  To date, The Tech is ahead
of its own capital campaign schedule and has raised $17.7 million from
44 companies, foundations and individuals with gifts of $100,000 and
more.

<p>

The new building will include a domed, 1,200 square feet large-screen
OMNIMAX theater with seating capacity for 300, plus four main
galleries totaling 32,000 sq. ft. of exhibit space, and 3,500 square
feet for a hands-on laboratory space for student workshops.  Projected
attendance is 650,000 visitors a year including 130,000 students and
teachers.

The Tech Museum of Innovation is a private, nonprofit educational
resource.  Now operating out of a 19,000 square feet temporary
facility which opened in November 1990, the new museum will be more
than six times larger.

<p>
<center>
###
</center>

