<p>

<h3>Ground Breaking for New $59 Million Tech Museum<br>
Scheduled for June 11 at Noon</h3>
                                
<h3>Business and Community Leaders to Break Ground With Help of Robots</h3>

On Tuesday, June 11 at noon, The Tech Museum of Innovation, the Mayor
of the City of San Jose, Susan Hammer, and William Hewlett, co-founder
of Hewlett-Packard Company will break ground for the new $59 million
home for The Tech.

<p>

Ricardo Legorreta, the renown Mexico City architect and designer of
the building, will be among the speakers.  To celebrate, San Jose
Taiko will open the ceremonies at the site.  Four anthropomorphic,
kinetic robots, including a 30-foot robot called "Too Big Dog Money"
created by artist Chico MacMurtrie will join the local luminaries in
breaking ground.

<p>

The ceremonies will continue at The Tech Museum's current facility
with a FREE public open house, 12:30 to 5 p.m. There, The Tech will
launch HyperTech, the museum's on-line virtual museum.  Also, museum
exhibit developers and designers will introduce the new exhibits
planned for the future Tech.

<p>

<table>
<tr>

<td>WHO:</td> <td valign=top>Mayor Susan Hammer, Tech President Peter Giles,
                    William Hewlett, Architect Ricardo Legorreta</td></tr><p>

<td>WHAT:</td> <td valign=top>Break Ground for New $59 Million Tech Museum</td></tr><p>

<td>WHEN:</td> <td valign=top>Tuesday, June 11, 1996 at Noon</td></tr><p>
                    
<td>WHERE:</td> <td valign=top>Corner of Park and Market Street, Across from Plaza de Cesar Chavez in downtown San Jose</td></tr><p>

<td>NOTE to EDITORS:</td> <td valign=top>Advance background materials and briefings, as well as color slides/photos of new building available upon request.</td></tr><p>
  
