<p>
<h3>TV Special on  Tech Challenge' Event Focuses on Kids' Ingenuity, Drive and Competitiveness</h3>

<h3>Tech Museum's Annual Contest Featured
on KPIX-TV June 15 at 6:30 p.m.</h3>

<b>SAN JOSE, CA, June 7, 1996</b> --

It's an inside look capturing the drama and excitement of Bay Area
students racing against the clock to compete in the annual Tech
Challenge student design and engineering contest sponsored by The Tech
Museum of Innovation--and it's captured in a special 30-minute TV
program hosted by Kate Kelly airing Saturday, June 15 at 6:30 p.m. on
Channel 5, KPIX-TV.
<p>

The program, produced by KPIX with underwriting from Advanced
Micro Devices and National Semiconductor Corporation, captures the
anxieties, competitive spirit and motivations of various student teams
from throughout the Bay Area (grades 5 through high school).
<p>

"I am delighted and amused at the imaginative, and often elegant
solutions that the students offer to some difficult challenges," said
Robert Grimm, retired engineer from Hewlett-Packard and a member of
the Board of The Tech Museum of Innovation, who is interviewed in the
TV special.  Grimm's backyard and garage are often the construction
site for the creation of many of the platforms or staging used in the
annual Tech Challenge.

<p>

The Tech Challenge in past years have required students to "power up"
a moving, simulated space satellite, rescue a potentially leaking
nuclear canister from destroying an Antarctica ice field, and retrieve
samples from the tree top canopy of the Amazon's Rain Forest.
Volunteers annually help The Tech Museum create not only the problems
to be solved in the Tech Challenge, but also build the platforms for
each of the challenges.  Many of the Tech Challenge platforms have
gone on to be used at school science fairs or for classroom projects.
<p>

"We hope that this TV special will introduce The Tech Challenge to a
wider audience of teachers and students in Northern California who
will not only participate, but discover new ways to make science and
technology literacy fun and engaging," said Peter B. Giles, president
and CEO of The Tech Museum. "We are grateful for the support from
Silicon Valley companies like National Semiconductor and Advanced
Micro Devices which support us in our Mission."
<p>

The Tech Museum is the premier science and technology museum in the
greater San Jose metropolitan area with a mission to engage people of
all ages and backgrounds in exploring and experiencing the
technologies changing their lives, and to inspire young people to
become the innovators in developing the technologies of the future.

<p>
The Tech is located at 145 W. San Carlos Street in downtown San Jose. For
more information call (408) 279-7150 or visit the museum's WWW site at:
http://www.thetech.org.  


<p>

For more information, contact:<br>
Gloria Chun Hoo, The Tech Museum (408) 279-7157 - gloria@thetech.org<br>
Peter Ross, Miller/Shandwick Technologies (415) 962-9550 - pross@millerwest.com<br>

