<p>
<h3>Silicon Valley Donors Contribute $4 Million in Seven Weeks to Tech Museum
</h3>
<b>SAN JOSE, CA, May 28, 1996</b> -- Reaching a milestone in its expansion campaign, The Tech Museum of
Innovation today announced that it had raised $4 million in seven
weeks--bringing the total amount of money raised for the Future Tech
to $56.7 million, including $17.7 million in private funds.  The
pace-setting gifts were stimulated by a $1 million challenge grant
from the Noyce Foundation, which attracted $2.008 million in new gifts
during the last three weeks in March.  In April, the David and Lucile
Packard Foundation awarded a $1 million grant towards the campaign for
The Tech.

<p>

"Never before have I seen such a rapid and enthusiastic
response to a challenge," said Peter B. Giles, President and CEO of
The Tech, in announcing the results of the Noyce Challenge.  According
to Ann Bowers, wife of the late Dr. Robert N.  Noyce, the Foundation
trustees awarded the challenge grant because, "We want more people to
come forward for The Tech so that teachers, students and families will
be better prepared for life in the 21st century."

<p>

A total of 28 corporations and community leaders responded to the
Noyce Challenge during a brief three week period in March.  Applied
Materials, Incorporated increased its contribution to the $1 million
Distinguished Founders level. Gifts of $250,000 at the Honored
Founders level were made by: Adobe Systems Incorporated and Silicon
Graphics, Incorporated. Gifts at the $100,000 Founders level were made
by: David and Cecilia Lee, Altera Corporation, Mr. and Mrs. Bernard
Vonderschmitt, and Xilinx Corporation.
                                
<p>

"The response to the Noyce Challenge exceeded all of our
expectations," said Mike Hackworth, chair of The Tech Capital
Campaign. "Achieving the high standard in quality and scope of The
Tech has taken countless volunteer hours and a dedicated
staff. Generous corporate leaders, engineers, scientists, educators,
community leaders and private citizens have contributed their time and
expertise as advisors in addition to supporting the campaign."

<p>

Exemplifying this spirit of community philanthropy was the late David
Packard.  As senior advisor to The Tech Capital Campaign, Packard
provided inspiration and guidance with the goal of developing The Tech
as a major education center for science and technology learning. With
the $1 million grant, the Packard Foundation has contributed a total
of $1.5 million to the Campaign. A previous grant of $500,000 is
funding development of the Explorations gallery in The Tech's new
facility, including a live ATM (Asynchronous Transfer Mode) link to
the Monterey Bay Aquarium and the Monterey Bay Aquarium Research
Institute's remotely-operated submarine.

<p>

Ray AbuZayyad, major gifts chair for the Campaign, attributes the
fundraising success in the last two months to "the powerful
educational model of The Tech." He says, "Our momentum was born of the
potential we saw for making a real difference in people's lives. We
have made good progress in the Campaign, but we are not done yet."

<h3>Plans for The Tech Expansion</h3>

The Tech Museum of Innovation will open the doors to its new facility
in November, 1998.  The future Tech will increase the museum's exhibit
space by eight times its current size.  Totaling approximately 130,000
square feet, The Tech's new facility will be organized into four major
galleries, with 32,000 square feet of exhibit space, a 12,000 square
feet OMNIMAX Theater, 3,500 square feet of hands-on laboratory space
and 4,000 square feet of training facilities. Projected attendance is
650,000 visitors annually, including more than 130,000 students and
teachers.  The architect is Ricardo Legorreta, who designed the
Cathedral in Nicaragua and the San Antonio Central Library.

<p>
                                
The $79 million project is being launched with a $39 million
commitment from the City of San Jose, directed primarily to the design
and construction of the new facility.  The Tech's Board of Directors
and its Campaign leaders have pledged to raise $20 million in cash
contributions for educational programs and exhibit development.  In
addition, companies and individuals are providing $15-$20 million of
in-kind support: software, equipment and services.

<p>
     
<h3>About The Tech</h3>

The Tech Museum of Innovation's mission is to engage people of all
ages and backgrounds in exploring and experiencing the technologies
affecting their lives, and to inspire young people to become
innovators in developing the technologies of the future.

<p>

The museum's current facility is located at 145 W. San Carlos Street
in downtown San Jose. The museum is open Tuesday through Saturday, 10
a.m. to 5 p.m. and Sundays, noon to 5 p.m.  From July through Labor
Day weekend, the museum will also be open on Mondays and hours will be
extended to 6 p.m. daily.  For more information about the museum call
(408) 279-7150, or visit The Tech on the World Wide Web at
http://www.thetech.org.

<p>
