<p>
<h3>Free Evening at The Tech May 2 Celebrates Olympic Torch in San Jose</h3>
<b>SAN JOSE, CA, April 22, 1996</b> --  The Tech Museum of Innovation will open
its doors to visitors on Thursday, May 2, 1996 from 5 to 9 p.m. for a free evening of exploration and education to mark the arrival of the 1996 Olympic Torch Flame in San
Jose.
<p>
The museum's numerous Internet computer stations will have direct access
to the <a href="http://WWW.BonViv.com/home/olympictorch/1996">Olympic WEB site</a> and other Olympics-oriented sites.  All of the
museum's other exhibits, including "Bits & Pieces: Inside the Computer" will be
available to visitors, as well as special hands-on activities and floor demonstrations.  The evening is being sponsored by National Semiconductor Corporation.
<p>
The Olympic Torch Flame relay is an 84-day, 15,000 mile national trek to
celebrate the  opening the summer Olympics in Atlanta.  Former Olympians plus
local community heros will carry the torch throughout San Jose before finishing at the Guadalupe River Park for a city welcome and ceremony on May 2 at approximately 8:30 p.m.   In addition to The Tech, the San Jose Museum of Art and the Children's Discovery Museum will be open to visitors that evening.
<p>
The Tech Museum of Innovation is located at 145 W. San Carlos Street in
downtown San Jose across from the McEnery Convention Center.  Regular hours are
Tues-Sun 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. and admission is: $6 adults, $4 youth, students and
senior citizens.  Free to members and children five and under.  For general information about the museum, call (408) 279-7150.
<p>

