<tr>
  <td width=450><font size="+1">Explore new worlds, new ideas, new technologies with The Tech Museum of Innovation during its Spring 1996 Evening Tech Talk Series
  </font>
  </td>
</tr>
</table>
<img src="/images/ui/redbar.gif" alt="" border=0>
<blockquote>
<p><b>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE</b><p>
Contact:<p>
Gloria Chun Hoo<br>
408-279-7157<br>
gloria@thetech.org<br>
<p>
</blockquote>
<!--a href="pdf/.template.pdf"><img src="/images/ptrs/PDFIcon.gif" alt="" border=0></a-->
 <!--a href="pdf/.template.pdf">PDF available (12 Kb)</a-->
<p>

<h3>X-plorations:  A Look at New Ideas, New Technologies<br>
Sponsored by Lockheed Martin Missiles & Space Co.</h3>
The Tech Museum of Innovation introduces a five-part evening lecture series week nights
beginning in January 1996. Museum doors will open at 6 p.m. for exploration of The
Tech's ongoing exhibits, as well as its special Spring exhibit "Bits and Pieces Inside the
Computer" sponsored by Intel Corporation. Program will begin at 7 p.m.  A subscription
to all five talks may be purchased in advance (see below). 
<p>

<b>Tuesday, January 23, 1996</b><br>
<b>Exploring The Role of Culture in Crossing the Great `Digital Divide'</b><br>
<b>Judith Mayer, Creative Computer Media Specialist</b><br>
<p>
Creator of the Electronic Mural, artist and explorer in the digital world, Ms. Mayer
recently served as technology consultant to the NGO Forum on Women, Beijing '95.  She
examines the role that culture - different languages, customs, religions and social
systems -  plays in the rapid technological growth of computers and telecommunications. 
Ms. Mayer will also discuss how efforts to digitally link events at the Forum in Beijing to
the outside world resulted in unanticipated, new experiences and opportunities for
participants at the World Conference on Women.
<p>

<b>Thursday, February 1, 1996<br>
Exploring the Medium of Virtual Reality<br>
Mark Bolas, President and Founder of Fakespace, Inc.</b>
<p>
Virtual Reality as entertainment, as new play space, as "fake space" has captured the
public imagination.  But what is the medium of VR?  How are practitioners and creators
manipulating VR and how limited is the medium of Virtual Reality? Will the promises
and the hype about VR disappoint us?  In conjunction with the International Society for
Optical Engineering Photonics West conference in San Jose (Jan. 27 - Feb 2, 1996), Mr.
Bolas and invited conference speakers will offer new insights into the medium of Virtual
Reality.
<p>

<b>Friday, March 1, 1996<br>
Exploring the Galaxy in Search of Extraterrestrials<br>
Seth Shostak, SETI Institute</b>
<p>
Is there intelligent life elsewhere in the cosmos?  Most scientists believe that somewhere,
among the myriad starfields of the Milky Way, other advanced societies exist. Project 
Phoenix is an ambitious plan to find extraterrestrials using giant radio telescopes and
sophisticated, digital receivers.  Will this project succeed?  And what if it does?
Astronomer, author and film producer Seth Shostak will talk about the daring exploration
of our galactic neighborhood in search of intelligent company. 

<p>

<b>Wednesday, April 3, 1996<br>
Exploring the Universe with Hubble<br>
Ray Villard, Space Telescope Science Institute, Johns Hopkins University</b>
<p>

Six years since its launch from Earth in April, 1990, NASA's Hubble Space Telescope has
delighted and fascinated the public with exciting photographs of distant galaxies and
Earth's neighboring planets.  Explore the scientific highlights of Hubble since its
December 1993 repair mission. See some of the spectacular images taken by the Hubble
Space Telescope, such as observations of black holes, the fiery birth of new stars,
observations of remote galaxies and more.
<p>

<b>Friday, May 17, 1996<br>
Exploring The Past - Investigating DNA from Egyptian Mummies & Dead Sea Scrolls<br>
Scott Woodward, Brigham Young University</b>
<p>

Using today's high-tech tools, microbiologist Scott Woodward is uncovering new secrets
about mankind's past by extracting DNA from the remnant pieces of parchment of the
Dead Sea Scrolls, preserved for 2,000 years in arid caves, and by studying the DNA from
Egyptian mummies.  A pioneer in ancient DNA research, Dr. Woodward returns to San
Jose to discuss results of his work in the field and findings about mummies at the
Egyptian Museum in Rosicrucian Park in San Jose.  This talk is held in conjunction with
the Santa Clara County Crime Laboratory.
<p>

Individual tickets may be purchased at the door for $6 ($4 for members).  A series
subscription to all five talks is available in advance for $20 ($10 for members).  Seating is
limited.
<p>

<h2>Advance Purchase of Series Tickets</h2>
To purchase in advance a reduced-price series subscription to all five talks, fill out the
form below and return with full payment to The Tech Museum of Innovation, 145 W. San
Carlos Street, San Jose, CA 95113.  You may also Fax this form back with credit card
information.



