<p>
<h3>New Exhibit at The Tech Museum
Examines "Bits and Pieces: Inside the Computer"
</h3>
<b>SAN JOSE, CA, December 26, 1995</b> -
The Tech Museum of Innovation
opens a major new exhibit, "Bits and Pieces: Inside the Computer" on
Monday, January 15, 1996 that explores the complex inner workings of
today's computers.  It's an appropriate exhibit for The Tech, which is
located in the technological hot-bed of Silicon Valley and birthplace of
the  microprocessor.
<p>
Visitors will be able to test their knowledge and learn more about
computers and terms like RAM, ROM, CPU, I/O, peripherals and more. The new
exhibit lays out the fundamental components and operations of computers
with 15 intriguing hands-on stations, such as using  pegs to "process" a
variety of simple tunes.  The experience is recommended for all ages,
although it will be of particular appeal to grade-school youngsters,
parents and teachers.
<p>
Using simple explanations, the exhibit  illustrates the structure
and function of computers and highlights five elements all computers have
in common: an input device, memory, central processing unit, software and
an output device; and answers commonly asked questions such as what data
is, how software works and how a central processing unit functions.
<p>
"'Bits and Pieces: Inside the Computer' will be a strong complement
to The Tech's current exhibit on microelectronics, and makes the marvelous
technology that is inside the computer easy to understand," said Peter
Giles, president of The Tech Museum.
<p>
"Bits and Pieces: Inside the Computer," which will be on permanent
display, was designed and developed by the Oregon Museum of Science and
Industry in collaboration with four other museums including The Tech.  The
exhibit was funded by the Intel Foundation and Intel Corporation.
<p>
"Intel is pleased to support The Tech Museum's efforts to put
technology into the hands of children, parents, teachers and other
visitors.  We hope 'Bits and Pieces' simplifies the terminology and makes
it fun to learn," said Albert Yu, senior vice president of microprocessor
products at Intel Corporation, and a member of The Tech Museum's technical
advisory board.
<p>
Intel is also donating a large display, "Voyage to the Center of a
Chip," that takes a visitor inside the structure of a microprocessing chip
and explores the more sophisticated technology used to test chips.  Over
the past year, Intel has also donated over $50,000 of Pentium processor
based systems to The Tech for a spectrum of exhibits.
<p>
To complement the exhibit, The Tech will offer adults and kids a
chance to "take apart" old computers on designated weekends to get a close
look at the elements inside computers. The Tech also offers a hands-on
workshop on assembling computers.  In addition, the "Bits and Pieces"
exhibit is being enhanced with large, over-sized computer display
components donated by Adaptec, Inc.
<p>
The Tech Museum of Innovation engages people of all ages and
backgrounds in exploring and experiencing the technologies affecting their
lives and inspires today's young people to become innovators in developing
technologies of the future.  The Tech is the premier science and technology
museum in the greater San Jose area. Located at 145 W. San Carlos Street in
downtown San Jose, the museum is open Tuesday through Sunday from 10 a.m.
to 5 p.m.  Admission is $6 for adults, $4 for youth, students with ID and
seniors.  Members, and children five and under are free.  For more
information, call (408) 279-7150.  The Tech's World-Wide Web address is
http://www.thetech.org.

<p>
