<p>
<h3>First Live ATM Exhibit Link Will Bring Monterey Bay to San Jose</h3>
<b>SAN JOSE, CA, July 6, 1995</b> --
Offering visitors access to new vistas
through use of multimedia and the Information Super Highway, The Tech
Museum of Innovation today formally introduced its exhibit VIRTUAL
WORLD: Multimedia and the Internet.  The exhibit will continue through
December 31, 1995.
<p>
This exhibit, which was made possible with donated and loaned
equipment and software from numerous Silcon Valley companies, puts the
latest communications technology into the hands of visitors to The
Tech.
<h3>Live Link to Monterey Bay</h3>
At the press event, The Tech Museum and Monterey Bay Aquarium also
jointly announced a new, upcoming exhibit, Live Link to Monterey Bay,
which will be the first-ever exhibit taking visitors in San Jose into
the depths of the Monterey Canyon by using Asynchronous Transfer Mode
(ATM) technology.  Live undersea video images from deep in the
Monterey submarine canyon, along with audio and video interpretation
from the Monterey Bay Aquarium, will soon offer Tech Museum visitors a
chance to participate in one of the aquarium's most popular programs.
<p>
"This collaborative exhibit applies advances in communications
technology to enhance information sharing and science education," said
Peter Giles, president of The Tech Museum.  "Much of the technology in
VIRTUAL WORLD: Multimedia and the Internet represents communications
breakthroughs that are not readily available to the general public."
<p>
The new exhibit will include live video broadcasts of unusual animals
and environs deep in Monterey Bay.  The images will be sent from a
remotely-operated vehicle (ROV) used by scientists at Monterey Bay
Aquarium Research Institute (MBARI), an independent research
institution.
<p>
Joining Giles at the preview was Julie Packard, executive director of
the Monterey Bay Aquarium, who said, "This is a great way to use
technology to carry marine science education beyond our walls."  The
exhibit will open to the public on July 15.
<p>
Live Link to Monterey Bay, funded by grants from Pacific Bell's
California Research and Education Network (CalREN) Program and the
David and Lucile Packard Foundation, is the first exhibit using
high-speed, high-bandwidth ATM technology to forge scientific and
educational links between two museums.  When the MBARI submersible is
not in use, the aquarium will use video images from recent dives for
presentations they share with the Tech Museum. During the summer, Live
Link to Monterey Bay will be available to Tech visitors Tuesday
through Sunday from noon to 1:30 p.m.  After the Labor Day weekend,
the program will be available at The Tech Tuesday, Thursday and Friday
from 12:15 to 3:00 pm.  The collaborative exhibit with Monterey Bay
Aquarium will be a permanent addition to The Tech.
<h3>Live ISDN Demonstration</h3>
A demonstration at the opening featured an interactive link between
The Tech and San Diego State University, showing the use of Integrated
Services Digital Network (ISDN).  This technology allows users to
access two separate channels on the same digital line to
simultaneously share video and Internet computer screen images with
another destination using like equipment.  This exhibit demonstrates
the value ISDN will hold in enabling schools in the future to directly
communicate with the museum.
<h3>Interactive Multimedia Exhibit</h3>
At another exhibit, a workstation will offer visitors a chance to
interact with the work of California artist Stewart McSherry, a
self-described abstract expressionist or neo-realist, who creates
dynamic and elastic 3-dimensional computer animations.  Part of his
exhibit, "Airplay," allows the visitor to interact with his artwork,
by triggering events based on hand movements, a "device-free"
interface.
<p>
Three separate stations will offer interactive laser disc viewing,
including a special 3-D station with stereographic goggles that allow
visitors to experience virtual reality sensations with theatre-quality
sound. The Tech will also have a CUSeeMe exhibit showing the
application of digital video compression and network transmission
using a Pentium processor-based computer.
<h3>Exhibit Sponsors</h3>
Major sponsors of Virtual World: Multimedia and the Internet are
Apple Computer, Cirrus Logic, Inc., FORE Systems, IBM Corporation,
Pacific Bell, and Silicon Graphics, Inc.
<p>
Other companies providing sponsorships of donated or loaned equipment
and/or services include BBN Planet, Broadcast Production Group, Cisco
Systems, Helen Weiss Productions, Hewlett-Packard Company, Intel
Corporation, LaserLand, Lexicus, Mercury Center, Microsoft, Netcom,
Netscape, David and Lucile Packard Foundation, Philips Electronics,
Pioneer Electronics, Quantum Corporation, and Smart Valley, Inc.  As
part of the exhibit, The Tech is adding new, donated workstations that
offer visitors opportunities to explore the latest technology in
multimedia and access to "Cyberspace" - the electronic world of the
Internet and World Wide Web. These stations will be joining two Public
Access Network workstations installed by Smart Valley, Inc., last
month to increase the museum's ability to offer visitors Internet
access.
<p>     
The Tech Museum of Innovation, a private non-profit educational
resource, is the premier science and technology museum serving the
greater San Jose metropolitan area with a specific focus on the
advanced technology emerging from Silicon Valley and beyond.  By
providing hands-on, engaging experiences and informal learning, as
well as school field trips and labs, The Tech is a leader in the
region in promoting scientific literacy and understanding about the
technologies changing our lives.
<p>
The Tech is located at 145 W. San Carlos Street in downtown San Jose
across from the Convention Center.  Hours are 10 a.m. to 5
p.m. Tuesday through Sunday.  Admisison is $6 adults, $4 youth,
students and seniors. Children and museum members are free.  For
general information, call (408) 279-7150.
<p>
<center>
