 <a href="pdf/pr1-25-95.pdf">PDF available</a>
<p>
<hr>
<h3><i>The Tech Museum of Innovation Announces $10 Million in Donations
</i></h3>
<b>SAN JOSE, CA, January 25, 1995</b> --
The Tech Museum of Innovation 
announced today at a press conference attended by Silicon Valley luminaries
that it has received over $10 million in contributions from corporate and
community leaders. In addition, the museum unveiled an exterior model and
interior rendering of the new science and technology facility it plans to
open in downtown San Jose by 1998.
<p>
The donations exceed the halfway point of the $20 million goal set by
the museum for its Capital Campaign, a fundraising effort established to fund
exhibits in the new building. The accomplishment puts The Tech ahead of
schedule in meeting the City of San Jose's $7.7 million milestone challenge.
Under a 1994 agreement with 
<a href="/board_of_directors.html">The Tech's board of directors</a>, the
City will provide $39 million to construct the new facility.
<p>
Major donations announced include $1 million from Lockheed Corporation
and Lockheed Missiles &amp; Space Company, Inc., whose gift raised The Tech's
Capital Campaign to its $10 million point. Emphasizing the important role that
The Tech plays in improving science education, Gus Guastaferro, vice president
of <a href="http://www.nasa.gov/">NASA</a> and Federal Systems at 
Lockheed Missiles &amp; Space Company, said that
in the company's 70-year history, it was only the third time Lockheed had ever
made a $1 million donation.
<p>
"Lockheed has always been a future-oriented company. Our contribution to The
Tech is an investment in the education of our future workforce," said
Guastaferro.
<p>
David Packard, director emeritus of 
<a href="http://www.hp.com/">Hewlett-Packard Company</a>, also announced a
$500,000 gift from the David and Lucile Packard Foundation. "The changes in
technology in the future will be far more dramatic than anything we have seen
to date. The Tech is playing an important role in preparing people to take
advantage of these new resources," said Packard, a senior advisor for The
Tech's campaign efforts.
<p>
Other large new gifts include $100,000 from National Semiconductor Corporation
and Pacific Gas and Electric Company. Additionally, a computer equipment grant
of $1 million from 
<a href="http://www.hp.com/">Hewlett-Packard Company</a> was also announced. 
A total of 25 corporations, individuals and foundations are "founders" in the
museum's Capital Campaign and have each pledged $100,000 or more.
<p>
Other donations announced earlier include: Honorary Campaign Chair William
Hewlett, $2.5 million; the Hewlett-Packard Company Foundation, $1 million;
Mike Hackworth, president and CEO of Cirrus Logic Corp. and campaign cabinet
chair, $1 million. "We are greatly honored by the generosity of our donors,"
said Peter Giles, president of The Tech Museum. "Not only do these 
contributions exceed the challenge by the City of San Jose to raise $7.7
million by this point in the year, but they fuel the potential for future
exhibits and services to fully capture the technological vitality of
Silicon Valley."
<p>
"Our campaign sets a new standard for a single institution of this type in
our community. The lead donors are setting a record for philanthropy in
San Jose," said Giles.
<p>
A model and sketches of the planned three-story building were presented by
The Steinberg Group of San Jose. The Steinberg Group is the executive architect
working in conjunction with world-renowned designer Ricardo Legorreta.
The museum's 12-member Exhibit Design and Development Team, responsible for
the new museum's interior and exhibit design was also on hand ot answer 
questions. Highlighting the design is a two story dome housing an IMAX
special-effects theater. The museum will be in downtown San Jose facing the
Plaza de Cesar Chevaz.
<p>
In addition to Packard and Guastaferro, also attending the ceremonies was
computer pioneer William Hewlett, San Jose Mayor Susan Hammer, John Warnock,
CEO of Adobe Systems Inc., Yvette del Prado, vice president of 
<a href="http://www.tandem.com/">Tandem Computers, Inc.</a>,
former San Jose mayor Tom McEnery, and Frank Taylor,
executive director of San Jose's Redevelopment Agency.
<p>
The Tech Museum of Innovation is the premier science and technology museum
serving the greater San Jose metropolitan area with a 
<a href="/mission.html">specific focus</a> on the
advanced technology emerging from Silicon Valley and beyond. By providing
hands-on, engaging experiences and informal learning, as well as 
<a href="/edu/field-trips.html">school field trips and labs</a>, 
The Tech is a leader in the region in promoting scientific
literacy and understanding about the technologies changing our lives.
<p>
