<head>
<title>IBM Provides Educational Systems to The Tech (August 18, 1994)
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#15085a" text="#ffffff" link="#ffffff" vlink="#a8a8a8" alink="#a8a8a8">
<center>
<img src="/images/icons/Press.gif" alt="">
<h2>
<font size="+3">P</font>RESS
<font size="+3">R</font>ELEASE
</h2>
</center>
<hr size=4>
<blockquote>
<p><b>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE</b><p>
CONTACT:<p>
Gloria Chun Hoo<br>
The Tech Museum of Innovation<br>
408-279-7157<br>
gloria@thetech.org<br>
<p>
Walt Keeshen<br>
IBM<br>
408-257-2974<br>
<p>
</blockquote>
<a href="pdf/pr8-18-94.pdf"><img src="/images/ptrs/PDFIcon.gif" alt="" border=0></a>
 <a href="pdf/pr8-18-94.pdf">PDF available</a>
<p>
<hr>
<h3><i>
Tech Opens $350,000 Back-To-School Learning Center Showcase<br>
IBM Provides Latest in Educational Systems; Technical Know-How
</i></h3>
<b>SAN JOSE, CA, Aug. 18, 1994</b> --
The tough job of learning got a 
whole lot easier and much more fun today at The Tech Museum of Innovation
where a back-to-school boost from International Business Machines
Corporation now invites students and teachers alike to take hands-on 
control of more than $350,000 of the company's latest workstations and
award-winning educational courseware which jumps to life at the click of
a mouse.
<p>
The IBM distributed network that ties together 14 IBM Personal
System/2 486 workstations in The Tech's infomation lounge is SchoolView.
It also will link five additional PS/2 terminals that will be installed 
in the Workbench science laboratory to join the one workstation that is
already up and running.
<p>
This network management system brings the world into the classroom
through the "windows" of more than 50 individual programs ranging from
multimedia encounters with Columbus as he sails in 1492 to 1994 scientific 
wet lab work.  The lab experiences involve real time probe-based 
temperature, light and motion experiments.
<p>
The new learning center was unveiled today in ceremonies that 
involved summer camp students who joined a few hermit crabs to help 
demonstrate, with the help of The Tech and other San Jose teachers, the
latest in state-of-the-art educational courseware stored on hard drives, 
CD-ROM and laser disk.
<p>
Judith Fritz, The Tech's director of education, joined Ed Zschau,
general manager of the company's San Jose-based Storage Systems Division, 
and Dindo Rivera, the education executive (western states) for IBM's
Education Business Unit - EduQuest, to formally open the learning center
as members of The Tech's board, civic and community leaders watched.
<p>
"The computer technology for the classroom has been here awhile,
but it has not been fully used as a teaching tool.  IBM is helping us 
make this happen by providing important interactive and engaging tools
that allow children to actually participate in their learning through 
the powerful world of multimedia sight and sound," Fritz said.
<p>
"This is a special day for IBM and for me personally. I have 
worked with The Tech since its beginning to fulfill its educational
promise to the community.  IBM has also been a long-time Tech supporter,"
Zschau said.  "IBM's support of The Tech began with The Tech's first
community educational program for the San Jose Unified School District
in the mid-Eighties.  I'm pleased to be working with IBM in our 
partnership with The Tech to enhance science and technology teaching 
and learning here.  It is a reflection of IBM's corporate commitment to
help K-12 education nationwide to achieve systemic reform," Zschau added.
<p>
Two of the new multimedia educational programs in use - Math and
More, and the Nature of Science - were developed by IBM in response to
the poor performance of U.S. students in math and science.  The second
International Mathematics Study found U.S. 13 year-olds and 17 year-olds
near the bottom in all aspects of achievement.  The Educational Testing
Service 1991 international assessment of educational progress in math
and science found that 9 and 13 year old American students scored
significantly lower than the international average.
<p>
The hardware and software were installed by EduQuest technical
representatives over the summer.  They are now in the process of 
instructing teachers to get them ready for the school year.
<p>
The first class at The Tech using the new equipment later this 
fall will be the Personal Science Laboratory (PSL).  One terminal is 
installed and the other five will be readied over the next few weeks
and loaded with courseware.
<p>
Through discovery learning, PSL allows students to mirror what
scientists do in their work.  For example, the motion and mechanics 
module with its distance probe allows students to learn a scientific
principle by observation -- such as seeing that the effect of gravity on 
a falling object is constant regardless of the object's weight.  The 
probes are laboratory grade scientific measurement tools. For example, 
the photometric response of the PSL light probe is as fast as the human 
eye.  The pH probe can analyze a single drop of liquid to 0.01 pH.
<p>
The PSL base unit is the heart of the system.  It collects data
from modules attached up to four probes and routes it to the host PS/2 
server through standard RS232 communications links.  Different probes
can be plugged into the modules to combine several measurements in a 
single experiment.  The base unit's internal systems clock operates
with a one-microsecond cycle, a high-level of performance not common
in the classroom environment.
<p>
The PSL allows students to set up an experiment, record it, 
tabulate it, calculate it and illustrate it in graph on the computer 
in real time.  Without the technology, the same events done manually
could take many more class sessions to accomplish the same objectives.
<p>
The equipment and software configuration was put together as a 
joint effort between IBM's Storage Systems Division and Eduquest's
Sacramento office.  The IBM computers, peripheral equipment and software
are on loan to The Tech Museum of Innovation so that IBM can upgrade
hardware and software as well as handle any necessary maintenance.
<p>
<center>
###
<p>
