<title>Theme for August Tech Talks: Women in Science and Technology</title>
<pre>
The Tech Museum of Innovation                   Contact:   Gloria Chun Hoo
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE                                      (408) 279-7157
July 28, 1994 
</pre>
<h1>Women Scientists in Space Exploration<br>
Theme for August Series of<br>
Tech Talks at The Tech Museum of Innovation</h1>
 
SAN JOSE, CA (July 28, 1994) -- Women leaders in space exploration and physics
will be highlighted in a series of Tech Talks at The Tech Museum of Innovation 
during the month of August.
<p>
This special series is co-sponsored by Women of Vision, a volunteer group at 
The Tech which is dedicated to providing role models for girls and to 
encourage young women to enter the science and technology fields.  
<p>
"Girls still get societal signals that science and math are boys' fields.  We 
want to change that, and we want boys and girls to recognize the important 
contributions women are now making in Silicon Valley, and in exciting arenas, 
like space exploration," said Joan Hackworth, chair of Women of Vision.
<p>
All talks are free with museum admission and are held in the Info Lounge of 
The Tech Museum, located at 145 W. San Carlos Street in downtown San Jose.
<p>
The series begins with Jill Tarter, project scientist and manager of the 
Phoenix Project, NASA Ames Research, whose talk on Friday, August 5 at 
10 a.m. will coincide with a planned visit by 100 Girl Scouts.  Dr. Tarter 
will discuss: "SETI: Science Fact, NOT Fiction, and One Women's Daily 
Routine!" a look at how she uses her engineering skills and knowledge of the 
observable universe to plan for the thorough observations of the universe.  
The SETI project, terminated by Congress in October 1993 and revived with 
private funding (now called the Phoenix Project), searches for other forms 
of life in space through a set of narrowband and pulse sensitive filters 
never before systematically used by astronomers.
<p>
On Sunday, August 7 at 2 p.m. Susan Ermer, polymer chemistry group leader
from Lockheed Research and Development, discusses "Electro-Optic Materials 
in the Electronic Communications Age."  Her talk will focus on her work in 
the development of polymer-based materials used in photonics, communications 
using light, an emerging field in communications networking and 
telecommunications data exchange.
<p>
Rebecca Welling, scientist and program manager, Lockheed Research Center,
will speak on "Space Shuttle Flight Readiness" and the critical work she 
does in developing laser measuring tools for precision fit of Space Shuttle 
tiles and other space-related projects.  Her unit at Lockheed developed the 
automated, portable optical systems supporting Space Shuttle flight 
readiness and other space-flight and aircraft manufacturing programs. 
Dr. Welling will speak on Saturday, August 13 at 2 p.m.
<p>
Jean Mirra, division manager, Test Engineering of Missile Systems, Lockheed
Missiles and Space Co., will discuss "Careers in Engineering for Math 
Enthusiasts," in a talk geared to young people, especially young women who 
enjoy mathematics and are not sure about pursuing a career in it.  She will 
show some projects in the Missile Division which utilize mathematical minds, 
and discuss career transition in an engineering organization.  Ms. Mirra 
will be the Tech Talk speaker on Saturday, August 27 at 2 p.m.
<p>
Theoretical physicist Joanne Hewett from Stanford Linear Accelerator Center is
the Tech Talk speaker on Sunday, August 28 at 2 p.m.  "SLAC and High Energy 
Physics Predictions," is the topic for Dr. Hewett who will describe what the 
Stanford Linear Accelerator's research results have been and how these compare 
to high energy physics predictions.
<p>
These informal talks by scientists, while about highly technical fields, are 
designed to be informative for a general audience and to youth, as well.  
This particular series will provide insights into career preparation for 
these highly-technical fields and will be of interest to youth in their 
teens who are beginning to explore career options.
<p>
The Tech Museum of Innovation provides interactive exhibits and programming
designed to inspire young people to become the innovators of tomorrow's 
technologies. The museum is located across from the San Jose Convention 
Center and is open Tuesday through Sunday, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Admission is 
FREE for members, $6 for adults, $4 for youth, students 18+ with ID, and 
seniors.  Children ages 5 and under are free.  For general information, 
call (408) 279-7150.
