<title>Special Programs on Jupiter-Comet Collision</title>
<pre> 
The Tech Museum of Innovation                CONTACT:  Gloria Chun Hoo     
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE                                  (408) 279-7157
July 1994
</pre>
<h1>Special Programs Scheduled<br>
at The Tech Museum of Innovation<br>
On Jupiter-Comet Collision</h1>
 
     SAN JOSE, CA. -- To help the public better understand the
Jupiter-Comet Collision phenomenon happening in mid-July, The Tech
Museum of Innovation in San Jose, California, will feature a series
of special programs, speakers and an interactive kiosk that will
highlight simulations of the anticipated collision and offer
explanations of the event.
<h2>
`Comet Fragments Headed for Jupiter' Exhibit 
</h2>
     This new exhibit, produced by Sandia National Laboratories,
includes a multimedia station, with a touch screen, that will allow
visitors a chance to find out what scientists have predicted for
the July, 1994 collision of Comet Shoemaker-Levy 9 on Jupiter. The
exhibit offers answers to some fundamental question about the
event, why scientists are so interested it, how scientists are
studying the collision on Jupiter, and how the information will be
gathered and processed.  Exciting images, including animation,
movies, and simulations and statements from experts are featured. 
     Three different teams of scientists have been studying the
potential impacts of the upcoming collision and aspects of their
work are in the exhibit. The exhibit, produced by Sandia
Laboratories for The Tech Museum, was developed in cooperation with
Sandia Laboratories - Experimental Impact Physics Department,
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, the National Aeronautics and
Space Administration, and Jet Propulsion Laboratory. 
     The kiosk, which will be at The Tech until the end of August,
will be updated by Sandia to include new information and
photographs taken of the actual comet collision. 
<h2>
Tech Talk:  "The Impact of Comet Shoemaker-Levy 9 on Jupiter"<br>
Sunday, July 24 at 2:00 p.m. 
</h2>
Two physicists, David A. Crawford and Mark Boslough from Sandia
National Laboratories who will have just returned from Hawaii where
will observe the Comet Shoemaker-Levy 9 collision, are the Tech
Talk speakers who will discuss their new discoveries. At The Tech,
they will show slides of their experience, discuss their
observations, and answer audience questions.
<h2>
"Hubble and Beyond" Space Exhibit
</h2>
This space exhibit from Lockheed Missiles and Space Company
features images taken by the Hubble Telescope and the repair
mission to correct Hubble's original faulty vision.
Now through the end of August.
<h2>
One Giant Step for Mankind - FREE publication
</h2>
During July, while supplies last, visitors will receive a FREE copy
of "A Tribute to America's Moonwalkers - Apollo at 25"
commemorating the 25th anniversary of the landing of mankind on the
Moon.  In observation of the event, The Tech will have a free, 24-
page color publication featuring interviews with living astronauts
and a summary of each moon landing mission.  
     The Tech Museum of Innovation is a three-year old science-
technology museum which offers interactive exhibits designed to
engage people of all ages and backgrounds to explore and experience
the technologies affecting lives and to inspire young people to
become tomorrow's innovators.  The Museum recently announced plans
and architectural renderings of its new building, a 115,000 square
feet facility that will increase exhibit space and include a large
screen threatre. The Tech's new building will open in 1998.
     The Tech is located in downtown San Jose, across from the San
Jose McEnery Convention Center and is open Tuesdays through Sunday
10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Admission is $6 for  adults, $4 for seniors and
youth, and free to museum members and children aged 5 and younger.
<pre>
                            # # #
</pre>
