<title>First Look at The Future Tech</title>
<em>The images on this page were captured with a Logitech FotoMan(TM) digital
camera, on loan for exhibit development from Logitech, Inc. of Fremont.</em>
<hr>
<pre>
The Tech Museum of Innovation                   CONTACT: Gloria Chun Hoo
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE                                    (408) 279-7157
                                                         Kevin Pursglove
June 27, 1994                                            (408) 277-5800
</pre>
<h1>First Look at The Future Tech</h1>
<img src="/gifs/fotoman/press/peter_behind_camera-2.gif">  
SAN JOSE, CA (June 27, 1994) -- Today San Jose Mayor Susan Hammer joined with Ed 
Zschau, IBM Vice President and General Manager, Storage Systems Division and 
board member of The Tech Museum of Innovation to unveil an architectural drawing 
and model of the new building concept for The Tech and to announce pledges from 
the private sector totaling $8,090,000.
<p>
Major Hammer and Zschau were assisted by Tech board members, City Council 
members, Tech volunteers and student participants as they present the 
architectural rendering and a model of the proposed new facility concept. The 
design was developed by internationally-known architect Ricardo Legorreta of 
Mexico City. Executive Architect is to be the Steinberg Group of San Jose.
<p>
In unveiling the model and rendering, Major Hammer stated that, "The Tech 
is an educational endeavor that brings Silicon Valley industry and entrepreneurs 
together with the City of San Jose in a world-class investment in the future 
through education. San Jose is proud of the important role that both technology 
and innovation play in providing jobs and other economic benefits to the region, 
state and nation."
<p>
Mayor Hammer went on to say that, "The location of The Tech in downtown San 
Jose is consistent with San Jose's emerging role as the capital of Silicon 
Valley. In this new facility, The Tech can achieve its potential as the 
'Smithsonian of the West' and draw visitors to San Jose and the Bay Area from 
around the world as well as serve as an unparalleled learning resource for local 
families, schools and companies."
<p>
The new facility will be located on a premier downtown San Jose site, facing 
Plaza de Caesar Chavez, looking across to the Fairmont Hotel and the San Jose 
Museum of Art. The new facility will be 115,000 square feet and will include 
exhibits, coupled with areas for hands on experimentation with science and 
technology, a large screen domed theater, plus room for expansion. The location 
of The Tech's current facility, McCabe Hall, will be converted to house 
administrative and engineering support functions.
<p>
In describing the sources for the leadership fund phase, Mr. Zschau announced 
three major pledges to The Tech's capital campaign that have spearheaded this 
first stage of the campaign: $2,500,000 from Mr. William R. Hewlett, co-founder 
and director emeritus, Hewlett-Packard Company, and who serves as honorary chair 
of the capital campaign; $1,000,000 from Mr. and Mrs. Michael Hackworth -- Mr. 
Hackworth serves as chair of The Tech's capital campaign cabinet and is 
president and CEO of Cirrus Logic, Inc.; and $1,000,000 from the Hewlett-Packard 
Company Foundation.
<p>
Mr. Zschau noted that these significant commitments lead a growing number of 
Silicon Valley corporations and individuals lining up in support of The Tech's 
educational mission, including the following individuals, companies and 
foundations who have made early commitments to the campaign:<br>
Stephen and Betty Bechtel, Jr., Robert and Marion Grimm, David and Cecilia Lee, 
Roger and Gail McCarthy, Marilyn and David Pratt, the John and Marva Warnock 
Family, Jack and Mary Lois Wheatley, Mr. and Mrs. Hans Wolf, Altera Corporation, 
Cirrus Logic Inc., Failure Analysis Associates, Inc., FMC, Ford Land Company, 
IBM, Intel, Lockheed Missiles and Space Company, ROLM, Silicon Graphics, Inc., 
Tandem Computers, Inc., Knight Foundation and the Valley Foundation.
<p>
Mr. Zschau also reported that at a Tech Museum board meeting, a challenge pledge 
from an anonymous donor of $700,000 was announced. The purpose of this was to 
help The Tech campaign reach the halfway point of $10 million by the end of 
1994.
<p>
"It is clear," according to Zschau, "that the leadership of 
Silicon Valley is coming together around The Tech as a major avenue to stimulate 
excitement in young minds about science and technology through school, family 
visits, weekend programs, outreach and teacher development."
<p>
Funds raised equal more than one third of the $20 million total the museum's 
board of directors plan to raise by 1998. An additional estimated $20 million in 
equipment and services will be raised from corporate supporters by the time the 
facility is opened, scheduled for early 1999. The Redevelopment Agency of the 
City of San Jose is prepared to commit a total budget of $39 million toward the 
project, primarily for design and construction of the new facility at its board 
meeting later today.
<pre>
                                   # # #
</pre>
