<title>Shopping Centers Today, May 1998</title>
<h1>"Art in Motion"</h1>
<h2>By Metta Winter<br>
Shopping Centers Today, May 1988</h2>
 
The reason The Pyramid Cos., Syracuse, N.Y., commissioned two of
George Rhoads' audiokinetic sculptures is simple: People love them.
<p>
"It's an amenity that really works," said Pyramid partner Gary
Dower.  "People get a giggle out of such an upbeat thing.  It enhances
the shopper's comfort level, and this pleases our tenants as much as it
does us."
<p>
The waving arms atop 26-feet-high <i>Watchamaballit</i> first
catch the eyes of shoppers at Pyramid's Salmon Run Mall in Watertown, N.Y.
Perched as they are, these green wands beckon the viewer to take a
closer look at the gigantic metal contraption below.  The nearer one
comes, the more there is to see and to hear.  Inside the steel
supporting frame is a frenzy of activity, all triggered by billiard
balls rolling simultaneously down nine different mazes of track.  As the
balls move through spirals, loop-the-loops and free-falls, each sets off
dozens of mechanical devices and percussion instruments.
<p>
Sections of track tilt, disks sway, plates spin, rods wiggle, levers
flip.  Here and there bells ring, gongs sound, xylophone bars play,
wooden boxes resonate.  It's a noisy whimsical affair that people are
irresistibly drawn to and find hard to walk away from.  But when they
do, there's invariably a smile on their faces, a lilt to their walk that
hadn't been there before.
<p>
"When we start to think about working with a piece of sculpture, we
look for what would be most appreciated by shoppers." said the mall's
designer, Alfred H. DalPos, principal architect for DalPos Associates
Architects, Syracuse.  "We considered a lot of different approaches and
eventually came up with the idea of something that could be enjoyed from
a distance, something where the closer you got the more you saw
happening.  It's a fun type of piece that is constantly changing."
<p>
Mr. Rhoads' work fit the bill precisely.  Animation, vitality and
humor are among the words used to describe his imaginative machines that
turn work into play.
<p>
"While beautiful to look at, it's not decorative art applied in the
usual way," said Peter Chermayeff, founding principal architect with
Cambridge Seven Associates, Cambridge, Mass.  "Most artwork is
fundamentally static or limiting.  What Rhoads does is more fully public
art.  He creates a living thing that draws people into its ever-changing
behaviors."
<p>
Viewers, architects and developers alike cite the carefully
orchestrated random activity, constantly offering something new to look
at as central to the success of Mr. Rhoads "ball machines."  This
unpredictability piques viewers curiosity and is almost hypnotic.  As
one woman said after checking her watch, "It totally blocks out the rest
of the world while you're watching it."
<p>
The effect is caused by distributors located at key points near the
top of the machine.  Often a spinning mechanism or a lever, the
distributor can send any ball down two or more tracks.  You cannot
predict which direction the ball will go; you just have to watch, and
people do.
<p>
The timing is so intricate that, while all manner of engaging
activity goes on in the meantime, it can take up to an hour before an
exact sequence of motion and sound repeats itself.  Serious Rhoads fans
have been known to wait it out.
<p>
A particular type of distributor called a dumper and the motorized
hoist that ferries the balls up for another roller coasterlike descent
also control pace, another source of variety that keeps viewers
guessing.  "It's all planned out with the dumpers, portions of track on
a pivot," said Mr. Rhoads. "When a certain number of balls collect in
it, the dumper tilts and they all roll out rapidly, causing an
unexpected crescendo of sound and action.  When this tapers off nothing
happens for a little while, then a small crescendo, a pause, a bigger
one, and so on."
<p>
The oldest Rhoads mall sculpture, <i>Electric Ball Circus,</i> has
been in continuous operation since 1971 in the Long Ridge Mall in Rochester,
N.Y., which is owned by National Shopping Centers Inc., Harrison, N.Y.
For a working machine, that type of durability is hard to beat.
<p>
In fact, it was National Shopping Centers president David Bermant
who influenced the introduction of Mr. Rhoads' audiokinetic pieces into
public spaces, first in the lobby of the Port Authority of New York and
New Jersey Bus Terminal in New York, then in four of his centers.  Now
there are 17 pieces on display in 10 malls and strip centers across the
United States and Canada.
<p>
The grandest of them all is <i>Ball City,</i> a colossal
10-foot-square-by-24-feet-high piece in Triple Five Corp.'s, West
Edmonton Mall in Alberta, Canada.  The most unusually placed is
<i>Having a Ball</i> in National Shopping Centers' Allendale Shopping
Center in Pittsfield, Mass.  Eight foot square by 1 foot deep, the piece sits
up against a glass-enclosed elevator, which allows passengers to view
it while they are riding up and down.
<p>
"There is no question in my mind that George Rhoads' is the most
appropriate work for public spaces being done by an American artist
today," said Mr. Bermant.  "I put them in shopping centers because it
makes a better day for people no matter who they are -- rich or poor,
educated or not.  They get enjoyment out of it, talk about it, and then
others come out to see it, too."
<p>
It's not only shoppers who are talking about these quirky machines.
"Rhoads is becoming well known," said Jack Beyer, partner with Beyer,
Blinder, Belle Architects, Planners, New York, designers of Strawberry
Square in downtown Harrisburg, Pa., now under construction by Harristown
Developments.
<p>
"Rhoads' approach animates public spaces in a more dynamic way than
conventional art forms.  It's not only a piece of sculpture but a
curiosity, automatically drawing attention to itself.  We felt it had
overall civic interest," Mr. Beyer said.
<p>
Those who have worked with Mr. Rhoads say not only is he a
professional who sticks to the agreed upon budget and produces a
reliable product on time, but also he is congenial to deal with as well.
"He's a pleasure for someone like myself to work with because he
responds to your thoughts and inputs, collaborates with you," said Mr.
Chermayeff of Cambridge Seven.
<p>
Size, shape and complexity are all negotiable among the architect,
Mr. Rhoads himself and Robert McGuire, owner of Rock Stream Studios,
Ithaca, N.Y., where the pieces are fabricated.
<p>
"Rhoads is a man with a childlike inquisitiveness, a freshness,
approaching each problem not in the tradition of what he's done before
but as an entirely new exploration," said Mr. Chermayeff.  The company
collaborated with Mr. Rhoads on two pieces at the renovated terminal C
at Boston's Logan Airport.  Discussions are now under way for two more
Rhoads' pieces for malls in the northeast.
<p>
Commissions from shopping centers currently in production by Mr.
Rhoads include large ball machines for Strawberry Square, Goodwin
Developments' Micronesia Shopping Center on Guam, Hooker USA's Forest
Fair Mall, Cincinnati, and the Ontario Science Center in Toronto.
Prices start at $125,000.  An operation and maintenance manual
accompanies the piece.  Total time from initial discussion to on-site
installation averages a year.
<p>
In addition to these large sculptures Mr. Rhoads also designs
smaller wall and freestanding versions suitable for corporate
headquarters and private collections.  Prices range from $6,000 to
$20,000.
 
<hr>
