<title>Sky Magazine, May 1988</title>
<h1>"Mesmerizing Machines"</h1>
<h2>By Metta Winter<br>
Sky, May 1988</h2>
 
There's a trap waiting to snare the unsuspecting passenger who
expects to breeze directly from the ticket counter to the gate at
Terminal C at Boston's Logan Airport.  Don't worry: it won't sneak up on
you.  In fact, you can't miss it.  George Rhoads' audiokinetic
sculpture, <i>Exercise in Fugality</i>, is a huge metal contraption nine
feet square by seven and one-half feet high.  No doubt there will be captives
already standing there, caught up in the fun of watching Rhoads'
fanciful "machine" that turns work into play.  But be careful.  Once
you stop to look, there's no telling how long you might want to stay.
<p>
"I know we're late, but take it easy, Sam," one man was heard
saying to another.  "It'll only take a minute or two until the big ball
gets to the top.  Then watch out!" They did.  For a full eight minutes
they stood, mesmerized by the antics of a black bowling ball as it
gracefully spiraled up an eight-foot auger, before making its
roller-coaster-like descent.
<p>
The big moment comes when the ball, having meandered down a maze
of metal track, free-falls three feet, hits a jogger's trampoline,
bounces two feet into the air, and lands safely in a basket.  At first,
surprise and delight mix with a satisfying sense of completion.  Not
long after comes another feeling: the intense desire to see it happened
all over again.
<p>
Rhoads' so-called "ball machines" are indeed difficult to walk
away from.  For one thing, so much is happening all at once.  In addition to
the bowling ball, 30 lacrosse balls set off a frenzy of activity as they
roll along three other sets of track.
<p>
As the balls move through spirals, loop-the-loops, and free falls,
each bumps against dozens of mechanical devices and percussion
instruments.  Sections of track tilt, disks sway, plates spin, rods
shimmy, levers flip.  Chimes and bells ring, gongs resound, xylophone
bars play, wooden blocks resonate.  From this welter of sound and motion
emerges a sequence of notes that form a discernible melody.  Just as in
a formal musical fugue, a second sequence starts before the first has
finished.
<p>
What's different in Rhoads' <i>Exercise in Fugality</i> is that you
can't tell when the second sequence is going to start or how many
sequences may occur at once.  When there is only one ball on each track,
the effect is like a triple fugue with three melody lines.  But when
three, four, or even five balls roll down each track in rapid
succession, it's like three separate fugues all going at once, forming a
grand combination.
<p>
Although each sequence is recognizable and easy to pick out, the
total effect seems random, unless it's studied over a period of time.
"This is what I'm after," says Rhoads, "constant variety that
doesn't drive the viewer crazy with a repeated melody."  Carefully
orchestrated random activity that is always offering something new to hear (and
to see, as well) is the hallmark of Rhoads' audiokinetic art.
<p>
Serious Rhoads fans have been known to wait it out.
<p>
Pace is controlled by a particular type of distributor called a
"dumper," as well as by the motorized hoist that ferries the lacrosse
balls up for another run.  "It's all planned out with the dumpers,"
says Rhoads.  "When a certain number of balls collect in it, the dumper
tilts, and all the balls roll out rapidly, causing an unexpected
crescendo of sound and action.  When this tapers off, nothing happens
for awhile.  Then a small crescendo, a pause, a bigger one, and so on."
<p>
Rhoads' choice of the word "crescendo" is no accident, for at one
time he thought of becoming a composer.  "My interest in listening to
music is intense," he says.  "I learned the basic rules of
composition, but figured I couldn't carry it any further and still become a
visual artist."  And that was the goal.
<p>
During his career of more than 40 years, Rhoads has been variously
successful as a painter of expressionistic urban landscapes, an
authority on the Japanese art of paper-folding called origami, an
accomplished medical illustrator, muralist, printmaker, and ceramist -
as well as house painter and furniture mover.
<p>
In the 1950s, Rhoads taught himself to weld, a skill that would
eventually bring an end to periods of living hand to mouth.  "I started
with fountains," he says.  "These led to a lot of ideas with
mechanical things, because you're using the same principles and a lot of the
same techniques."
<p>
The first moving sculpture was a kind of "music machine with
ratchets."  Later, Rhoads added rolling balls to trigger, or impel, the
action.  The early ball machines were single-track, hand-powered
devices, small enough to sit on a coffee table in someone's living room.
<i>Exercise in Fugality</i> and its companion piece at Logan,
<i>Goldberg Variation #1,</i> are elaborations on these simple devices.
They unite a mind fascinated by, and capable of comprehending, complex
mechanisms - with a childlike creativity that takes joy in designing truly
fantastic "toys."
<p>
Rhoads describes his sculptures as "little dramas" that surprise
and entrance the viewer with workings that are fully comprehensible - if
you stick around long enough.  "I think one of the appeals is that they
demystify technology," he says.
<p>
Another is the kind of musical sounds they create.  Although
<i>Goldberg Variation #1</i> is more mechanically intricate and has a
structural motif (a tree with branches coming out of a central trunk
that holds up the various sound - and motion-making elements), viewers
strongly prefer <i>Exercise in Fugality</i>, the more musical of the two.
<p>
Says Rhoads: "I wanted to make sounds that I think are interesting,
that give the listener something that is life enhancing, that makes them
feel better."  <i>Exercise in Fugality</i> seems to do just that.
People watch and watch and when they finally pull themselves away there is a
lilt to their walk, a smile on their faces that wasn't there before.
<p>
One has to wonder where Rhoads gets the compelling and fanciful
ideas needed to create an art that appeals to people of all ages and
backgrounds.  He says he's really been at it since childhood.  An
exhibit of clock escapements at the Museum of Science and Industry in
Chicago first inspired him to take watches apart.  By the age of ten, he
was making calendar clocks of his own out of wood, pennies, and soldered
bits of metal sheeting.  He made barometers and a Ferris wheel.  "I
really never stopped.  After I learned welding, I was able to bring some
of this stuff I'd done as a kid into the artworks."
<p>
Acknowledging the influence of French-born kineticist Jean
Tinguely, Rhoads says some of his ideas are variations on previous
designs.  Others come into his head "full blown."  Still others evolve
from a collaboration between him and his team of seven fabricators at
Rock Stream Studios in Ithaca, New York, where the sculptures are
actually built.
<p>
"Rhoads is often compared to Rube Goldberg, the cartoonist, who
drew cause-and-effect scenes," comments Rock Stream's owner, Robert
McGuire.  "The difference," says McGuire, "is that nobody ever
built a Goldberg, whereas all of Rhoads' pieces work."  That they do work
sometimes depends on McGuire and his welders devising what Rhoads calls
"elegant solutions" to problems in his designs.
<p>
Each year, Rock Stream Studios produces three large sculptures,
twice the size of those at Logan.  Prices start at $125,000.  Seventeen
of them are on display at ten shopping centers in the United States and
Canada.  Two are at New York's LaGuardia Airport and the Port Authority
of New York and New Jersey bus terminal in Manhattan, and another in
Boston, at the Museum of Science.  Of the four pieces currently under
construction, three are bound for shopping centers, two in the U.S. and
one in Guam.  The third will be installed at the Ontario Science Center
in Toronto early next year.
<p>
In addition, the studio builds 16 or so smaller pieces that sell to
private collectors and corporate buyers through galleries in New York
City, Las Vegas, and Lexington, Massachusetts.  Prices range from $6,000
to $20,000.
<p>
The supporting structures are welded pieces of steel tubing, the
track of steel rods.  Most of the noise- and motion-making devices are
familiar objects bought in hardware stores or from music and restaurant
suppliers.  The joggers' trampoline in <i>Exercise in Fugality</i> was
purchased at the local Montgomery Wards.
<p>
Each finished sculpture is tested for 1,000 hours of trouble-free
performance before being installed on-site.  The two Logan pieces are on
wheels so they can be trundled out for a semiannual oiling and cleaning.
This procedure is detailed in a maintenance manual that accompanies each
of Rhoads' pieces.
<p>
"All urban places need animation, character, vitality, humor -
combinations of these - that enrich people's experience in being there,"
says Peter Chermayeff of Cambridge Seven Associates of Cambridge,
Massachusetts, coordinating design architect for the remodeling of
Terminal C.
<p>
"George Rhoads is an artist who understands this," Chermayeff
says. "Not only does he create an object that people find attractive, but 
he is someone who can create a `living' thing that draws people into its
own ever-changing behaviors."
<p>
So, be forewarned.  When next you pass through Logan, allow a little extra time.  
You may be there longer than you expect!
 
<hr>
<img src="/gifs/logos/tech/techbutton-footer.gif" alt="">
