<title>Smithsonian, October 1988</title>
<h1>"Clumper Upper to Wok Dumper to Chute to Helix to Block"</h1>
<h2>By Richard Kostelanetz<br>
Smithsonian, October 1988</h2>
 
     The paths taken by George Rhoads' flashing little sound-making
balls are varied and magical, making art of hypnotic movement.  They've
been showing up all over North America these past few years -- these
intriguing machines with acrobatic balls that move around metal tracks
and make noises as they go.  There's a highly conspicuous, popular one
called <i>42nd Street Ballroom</i> in the Port Authority Bus Terminal in New 
York City.  There are two in Terminal C at Boston's Logan International
Airport and two more in the mammoth West Edmonton Mall in Alberta.  You
can also encounter them in shopping centers in New Haven, Connecticut;
Pittsfield, Massachusetts; Rochester and Watertown, New York; and
Kamloops, British Columbia, among other places in North America.  There
is a big one in the Boston Museum of Science, and there was in the
recent past a gallery full of them at the Queens Museum in Flushing
Meadow on Long Island.  To the man who made them, artist George Rhoads,
they are "audiokinetic sculptures" that generate sounds as they move.
<p>
Gathered around them, tracing the trajectories, are children of all
ages.  "The rest of the world is blocked out while you are watching 
it" is a common response; for though individual moves in these machines are
simple and clear, from the multiplicity and interconnections comes a
complexity that requires concentration to be understood; these
sculptures do not exhaust attention quickly.  Another element of the
Rhoads experience is watching the expression on the faces of others,
especially of real children, because, as the artist puts it, in pieces
for public spaces "the best stuff takes place at a kid level."
<p>
It is hard to imagine what kind of person created these.  My first
thoughts were that George Rhoads must be a young man who had barely
outgrown a fascination with erector sets and that he lived in a
stainless-steel, high-tech environment.  The surprises are that he is
62, was born in Chicago, is the son of a prominent internist, and now
lives rustically in Ithaca, in central New York.  Tall, trimly built, he
is a modest man who favors loose shirts, sweatpants and thong sandals.
He looks like a high school physical education teacher nearing
retirement.  Three years ago he moved into a little farmhouse on the
edge of the college town.  "I'm glad I came to this area," he says.
"It's the right distance from New York City.  It's a five-hour drive;
when you have to go, it's not bad."
<p>
Rhoads remembers growing up in suburban Evanston, where he took
private art lessons and wanted to be a painter; but he also learned from
looking at the clocks at the famed Museum of Science and Industry.
"What I particularly enjoyed was an exhibit of clock escapements.  They
were enlarged so that you could see how each one worked."  Escapements,
he explains, are mechanisms that drive the clock's pendulum and
determine the position of its hands.
<p>
In 1943, Rhoads studied painting at the Art Institute of Chicago
(SMITHSONIAN, August 1988) and then in Paris.  In New York City, he
worked sporadically at the kinds of free-lance jobs favored by some
struggling artists -- medical illustration, house painting and furniture
moving.  Through a gallery and on his own, he sold paintings into the
'60s, most of them expressionistic urban landscapes and trompe l'oeil.
Some of these, according to his own records, were purchased by Laurence
Tisch and Leonard Bernstein.
<p>
<i>This George of all trades</i>
<p>
The painter Herby Katzman remembers Rhoads 30 years ago as "a damn good
painter who also knew how to take apart and put together watches.  He
could do building construction."  Around this time Rhoads also met Hans
Van de Bovenkamp, a Dutch-born artist then living in the West Village,
who was involved in sculpting fountains.  Teaching himself metal
welding, Rhoads began to make his own kinetic fountains, which recycled
water through gravity-based systems similar to those he has since used
with rolling balls.  Between two and six feet high, these sold for a few
thousand dollars apiece.  "George is an absolutely wonderful genius,"
Van de Bovenkamp says; "he's a practical visionary in the sense that he
can have an idea and think it through."  Rhoads plans to return to
kinetic water fountains, perhaps with a limited edition of an
exquisitely simple sculpture with a pump, four moving parts and a
stationary network of descending trays.  The example in his own living
room can also function as a humidifier.
<p>
In the late '60s, David Bermant, a shopping mall magnate, began
commissioning the first of more than two dozen Rhoads pieces for his own
collection of kinetic art and for installation in his malls, where they
had secondary, "baby-sitting" functions.
<p>
Through the 1970s and into his own 50s, Rhoads worked on creating
new devices for his kinetic sculptures.  During this period he met Bob
McGuire, a local reading teacher now in his early 40s, who had briefly
studied engineering as an undergraduate.  McGuire became Rhoads'
principal "fabricator" and today is his business associate.
<p>
For a visual artist currently so prominent, Rhoads has had a
remarkably slight gallery career.  "He was always an introvert," Van 
de Bovenkamp remembers, "low-key, shy about selling."  He has had only 
a half-dozen one-man shows in New York City, the most recent nearly a
decade ago (where no sculptures were sold); and there have been only
three museum shows devoted exclusively to his work, two in upstate New
York and the other in Queens.  There is no catalog devoted to his art
and no critical literature more significant than short newspaper and
magazine articles.  He has never received any grants for his art; he has
never won any competitions for public art, although from time to time he
submits slides of his work for adjudication.  A painter I know who has
been affiliated with the Cornell University art department for nearly
two decades told me that she'd "never heard of him" until recently, 
and the only artists long-familiar with his name seem to be those likewise
involved in technological art.  Instead of showing his art in galleries,
he went public, so to speak, and out of a ne'er-do-well career came
sudden success.
<p>
Some Rhoads audiokinetic sculptures are more complicated than
others, but they all share several elements.  Near the top of a typical
Rhoads machine is a ball distributor -- sometimes it's a pendulum
switch, sometimes a rotating disk, sometimes a pin board that feeds the
initial supply of balls onto several tracks.  Depending upon how a ball
hits its distributor, it can be sent down one or more skeletal ramps 
into helixes or loop-the-loops.  As it goes it strikes noisemaking 
devices such as bells or a xylophone or pieces of metal.  With more than 
one path running from top to bottom, several balls can be moving at 
once, and while the sequence of sounds down each path is more or less 
fixed, the combinations of noises are various.  "You might call it 
semirandom," he explains.
<p>
As the rate at which the balls are released can vary, the sculpture
is sometimes considerably busier than other times.  When the balls hit
bottom, they are gathered into a chute where a motorized chain hoist
carries them to the top for another trip.  Because the hooks on the
chain are unevenly space, with clusters of them followed by empty
spaces.  Rhoads ensures that the flow of balls downward will be variable
-- now with many, now with only a few.  As with a roller coaster,
external power is applied to assist the process only in getting the
balls back to the top; otherwise, all the action depends strictly upon
old Mother Gravity, the principal co-conspirator in his art.
<p>
Rhoads' works, however, vary in structure and in complexity.  Some
he calls "wall pieces" because they have a front and a back, and are
thus meant to be placed against a wall.  But most, by contrast, are
meant to be viewed from several sides, as is the grandest of them all,
<i>Ball City</i>.  10 feet square, 24 feet high, his first installation in
Alberta's West Edmonton Mall.
<p>
Two qualities they all share are that, in contrast to other
artistic machines, their action is infinitely various and entirely
visible.  Because the decisions of the distributors can be so random,
there are no cycles of comprehensibly repeated activity, as in some
other artistic machines, but instead, endless variation.  On the
visibility issue.  Rhoads refuses to use electronics because the energy
would thus be hidden.  "Machines are interesting to everybody," he 
says, "but people usually don't understand them because, as in a gasoline
engine, the fun part goes on inside the cylinder.  So I've restricted
myself to mechanisms that you can see and understand quickly."  In this
emphasis on preelectronic machines (and in, say, his reluctance to use
acoustic amplifiers), Rhoads remains an old-fashioned technological
artist; from the strictly technical point of view, his sculptural
machines could have been constructed a century ago.
<p>
<i>"Nobody vandalizes what everybody loves"</i>
<p>
What Rhoads has realized is a popular, public art, sculptures that are
capable of holding the attention of nearly everyone without sacrificing
the complexity that marks their esthetic integrity.  At Logan Airport,
where there are two in sight of each other, one more complex than the
other, the more complex one always draws a larger audience.  When <i>42nd
Street Ballroom</i> was first installed, there was fear that it might be
vandalized, or its plastic case defaced; but even in the Port Authority
Bus Terminal, notorious as it is for both crowds and "loony tunes," 
that has not happened.  "Nobody vandalizes what everybody loves," one 
artist explained.
<p>
These sculptures seem to reflect the mobiles of Alexander Calder on
the one hand, and the fantastic contraptions of cartoonist Rube Goldberg
on the other.  In the first respect, they are kinetic, with plenty of
moving parts; in the second, they are elaborate machines with an
abundance of comic moves, producing nothing other than the pleasure that
comes from observing their operation.  Among the esthetic influences on
his own art Rhoads acknowledges Calder, "whom I'd always known about,"
and Jean Tinguely, the Swiss-born kinetic sculptor.
<p>
"I've known about Rube Goldberg for a long time," Rhoads says while
rolling his cigarette from pipe tobacco.  "I related to the goofiness of
his work, the unexpected event, the unlikely combination of elements.
His drawings are real wacky, true nonsense -- which is never as big in
America as in Britain.  But you can't actually make the things that
Goldberg drew; that's a severe limitation."  Rhoads also acknowledges
the influences of such "folk art" as roller coasters (especially the
large, scary one called "The Bobs" that used to be at River View Park 
in Chicago) and carousels (a current favorite being "the big one in Balboa
Park in San Diego").
<p>
The real innovation of his mature art was to be his use of the
little ball, which, like water, would not only respond to gravity but
would also be more controllable (and, as Bob McGuire puts it, "less
messy").  Rhoads designed a series of devices for handling rolling
balls, from metal tracking to several kinds of distributors, and then
the objects through which the balls could pass in resounding ways.
Certain elements reappeared in different guises: the helix, or vertical
spiral, and the loop-the-loop, which usually propels the balls at great
speed into a sound producer mounted above a catch basket.  There is also
a basket in the "bounce-and-catch" routine, where the ball is allowed 
to fall onto a plate from which it bounces up into the basket.
<p>
The "stairway of chimes" appears, too, in various forms, including
a succession of cowbells in <i>Magic Clock II</i>, which stood for a couple
of years in the main terminal of La Guardia, and the xylophone in <i>42nd
Street Ballroom</i> that rings out "East Side, West Side."  Then there 
are "dumpers" that customarily won't move until they collect several 
balls, and the "rock back" that catches a single ball and tilts back 
with it before returning it to one of the tracks.  And a "wraparound with
tinkle," as Rhoads calls it.  There is even a curious device, the
"clumper upper," for feeding balls into the loop-the-loops.  As the
balls roll down their tracks, they usually trip switches that in turn
strike noisemakers or make something else move, such as a miniature
windmill.  Near the bottom is often a wok, into which the balls fall,
making resonant sounds not only when they land but as they circle about.
The sound and motion in this simple vessel are instantly pleasing.
<p>
James Seawright, director of the Visual Arts Program at Princeton
University, compares Rhoads' sculptures to textile mills.  "There's a
level of mechanical genius behind the inventing of complex mechanisms;
that's what George has.  His kinetic sculptures act in an amazing
variety of ways, the balls going from one part of the track to another,
suddenly turning corners.  A group of balls will collect in a dumper,
and all but one will go off in one direction, while that extra ball goes
off on its own and does something else.  These machines embody almost
every basic element of machinery, but the elements are combined in a
bewildering variety of ways.  You look at one of his pieces and get a
sense of overall design, but then you must trace out the details for
yourself.  The enjoyment comes from seeing your expectations fulfilled."
<p>
Rhoads discounts the myth of himself as a technological genius:  "I
know zilch about electronics.  I can't fix my car anymore; I wouldn't
even try.  I really wanted to be a composer, but I couldn't do it.  I
didn't have enough training.  I didn't have the ability."  What's his
favorite music?  "Mozart's Tenth Serenade for Woodwinds; it used to be
the Clarinet Quintet."  His favorite films?  "Monty Python's Life of
Brian is my favorite movie at the moment, but all the Monty Python films
are good.  Certain Buster Keaton pictures.  Steve Martin's a supreme
comedian."  His favorite theater?  "Musicals with dancing and 
singing." This love of musicals reminds me that <i>42nd Street 
Ballroom</i>, for example, is extremely choreographic, able in its theatricality 
to compete with the nearby shows on Broadway.  (And, thanks to the Port
Authority, the Rhoads show is free.)
<p>
To Rhoads, the content of his work is indeed theatrical: "Balls
having fun doing different things.  Later you perceive the organization
and the cycles and the sequences. People keep saying, `Wouldn't it be
great if you could have seats inside the ball and travel down the track
yourself!'"
<p>
Abstract though these works essentially are, they are always on the
verge of representing something.  A woman beside me watching <i>42nd Street
Ballroom</i> compared it to her 4-year-old daughter, "full of activity and
out of control."  When I mentioned this interpretation to Rhoads, he
replied, "But they're not out of control.  They are allowed latitude,
but not too much.  Otherwise, the balls would fall on the floor."  He
continued, "Nothing is represented, but you could think of different
interpretations.  The main one I thought of earlier was that the balls
are the soul going through incarnations.  Start with birth at the top
and death at the bottom.  So each time the ball goes through, it goes a
different way; it does different things.  It's a model of human
existence -- a model of collective existence, the picture of many souls
in the Universe, or one soul in a succession of incarnations."
<p>
He reached for a book he had recently borrowed from the local
library, Isaac Bashevis Singer's Shosha, and directed me to a page
where Singer's narrator is attributing certain ideas to the Scottish
philosopher David Hume: "Since we are sure of nothing and there is even
no evidence that the sun will rise tomorrow, play is the very essence of
human endeavor, perhaps even the thing-in-itself.  God is player, the
cosmos a playground.  For years I have searched for a basis of ethics
and gave up hope.  Suddenly it became clear to me.  The basis of ethics
is man's right to play the games of his choice.  I will not trample on
your toys and you will not trample on mime; I won't spit on your idol
and you will not spit on mine."
<p>
One charm of Rhoads' audiokinetic sculptures is that they don't
announce themselves as Art; their informality makes them more
appropriate for public spaces than for art museums.  People gathered
around them are likely to ask one another.  "What is this, a game or
something?"  I remember once telling an editor about a great work of art
within two blocks of his office (on Manhattan's West 43rd Street).
"There's no great work of art around here," he replied gruffly.  
"Sure there is," was my retort.  "Where?" he challenged me.  
"In the Port Authority Bus Terminal," I replied, "the thing with 
the balls."  Without a pause he fired back, "Oh that! That's a 
masterpiece."
<p>
It is in the public spaces that Rhoads has since installed his very
best works.  <i>Tower of Babel</i> in Kamloops is the tallest and in many
ways the most ambitious, including new elements such as a large counting 
mechanism.  In common with another new piece for a Plattsburgh, New 
York, shopping center, <i>Tower of Babel</i> has three distinct levels of
activity.  The piece at the Allendale Shopping Center (pp.134-35) seems 
the richest to me, with lots of devices so far unique to it.  Golf balls
go up a clear tube into a stainless-steel catching basket before
spiraling down a helix into a complex of switches and dumpers that, as
they move, release the stops on organ pipes, whose sustained sounds thus
become a counterpoint to the traditional clinking of Rhoads' pieces.
Descriptions are scarcely adequate in portraying such activities, which
are best seen to be believed.
<p>
<i>Global Circus</i>, initially made in 1985, was recently refurbished
for installation at World Expo '88 in Brisbane, Australia.  It was
tested for a thousand hours of flawless functioning before being sent
out.  (The principal problem was balls jumping their tracks, so a
slow-speed video camera was trained on the machine, and the floor below
it was covered with sand so that McGuire and his assistants could see
exactly where the delinquent balls fell.)
<p>
<i>The other colossuses of Rhoads</i>
<p>
These sculptures hardly exhaust the record of Rhoads' inventiveness.  
Outside McGuire's house is a "pendulum swing," which has not only a
chair suspended below but two pendulums extending up into the air.  The 
movement of the lower pendulum (the swing) causes the top ones to rock 
in ways that can be felt by the person in the seat.  "It's like 
resonance in music," the artist explains.  In Rhoads' own backyard 
recently lay a "hula pole," back from a Chicago shopping center to be 
repaired.  It has switches that spectators can use to control the 
motions, either rotary or rocking, of each of four different parts, in 
sum producing gyrations comparable to those of a hula dancer.  Also
supine in Rhoads' backyard was a 30-foot-high helix with soccer balls.
In his guest room was a ball clock that strikes the hours; a foot or so
high, a few feet wide, it could become the prototype for an edition.  In
David Bermant's bedroom in Rye, New York, is <i>Blue Shamrock</i> (1986) with
five spinning circular structures, two of them moving around the others.
Bermant, who graduated from Yale in 1940, commissioned <i>Boola Boola</i>, an
audiokinetic sculpture in which a ball, inserted at the top, strikes
xylophone keys that ring out the Eli refrain before hitting bottom.
<p>
In the Queens Museum show was <i>Splendule</i> (1980), which had a
little ball suspended from the end of a string, itself attached to a
pole that is cleverly turned in eccentric ways by motors moving at three
different speeds.  As the ball spins around, it hits one of several
chimes at random, resulting in an aleatory music considerably less noisy
than is usual in Rhoads' work.  Outside the Wadsworth Atheneum in
Hartford is a motorless "windamajig," a pure mobile of wind-driven 
cones that rotate on several axes, tripping hammers to sound chimes.  A
"rotomabob," recently installed on a Manhattan penthouse porch, has a
circular pattern of cones suspended from an axis pole that holds a plate
at the top.  As the wind hits the plate, the whole thing tilts on a
single universal joint.
<p>
"What I want to do now is introduce mechanical elements other than
rolling balls.  I want to do things with gears, levers and cams.  I just
invented a mechanical arm that moves a ball in a quarter-circle and then
places it on a higher track.  The arm is operated by cams attached to a
motor.  It's fun to see because you can watch how the arm is directed by
a cam.  I got this idea from an old doughnut machine, where the arm
takes a doughnut out of the oil and then flips it over before it moves
it back in.  Now all this kind of motion is done by electronics," Rhoads
says.
<p>
He and McGuire have created a business structure that is rather
unusual in the history of contemporary art.  Essentially, McGuire owns
Rock Stream Studios, while Rhoads is a "designer working on 
commission." Rock Stream Studios is responsible for everything -- for 
making the sculptures, for installing them, for maintaining them.  It reminded 
me of Buckminster Fuller's admonition that whenever he founded a company he
always included a device for getting out of it in case it became too
successful and consumed too much of his attention and energies.  "I
wasn't thinking in terms of a company," Rhoads told me, when I mentioned
Fuller to him.  "We were thinking how best to arrange business matters,
so I'd be more free."  What Rhoads ultimately wants for himself is a
daily-work situation that allows him to paint or write or draw, while
those machines bearing his unique creative stamp continue to appear
across the land.
<p>
<hr>
