<HEAD>
<TITLE>Visions of Exploration</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY
BACKGROUND="backgrnd/vbar2.gif" BGCOLOR="#C0C0C0" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#0000FF" LEFTMARGIN="0" TOPMARGIN="0">
<P><A HREF="index.html"><IMG
SRC="images/torcher2.gif" ALT="Return to AEF Home Page" ALIGN="TOP" BORDER="0" VSPACE="0" HSPACE="12" WIDTH="46" HEIGHT="59"></A>
<IMG
SRC="images/afa_sup2.gif" ALIGN="TOP" BORDER="0" VSPACE="10" HSPACE="22" WIDTH="270" HEIGHT="54">
</P>
<P><IMG
SRC="backgrnd/spacer.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" VSPACE="1000" HSPACE="26" WIDTH="35" HEIGHT="4"></P><HR><H2 ALIGN=center>Visions of Exploration</H2>
 <P>
The Visions of Exploration is a cooperative program between <A HREF="http://www.usatoday.com">USA Today Newspaper</A>, AFA state
organizations and chapters, and AEF to encourage the skills necessary for success in math and
science among the nation's elementary school children. In the AY 1995-96, the program reached
75,000 students.  
<P>
To give participants a memento of the Visions course, handsome Certificates of Accomplishment
are sent to each Visions student who completes the program.  The certificates are distributed to
participating AFA chapters for signature and presentation.
<P>
Starting in the Fall on 1996, the Visions program was expanded from 10 weeks to an 18-week
program to better match the 9-week quarter schedule at most schools.  Schools can even break
the course into two 9-week increments for two separate classrooms.  Beside the curriculum
material furnished by USA Today, each participating class receives a copy of the annual Air
Force Magazine Space Almanac.  
<P>
The 18-week Visions program costs $178.75 per class.  AFA chapters can register to support as
few as five classrooms, down from the ten required in 1995-96.  AEF will pay half of the
registration costs for the five classrooms so a chapter can now make an initial investment of $445
and participate in the Visions program.  Registration for chapter participation occurs each Spring.
<P>
The joint USA Today/AEF goal is to reach 1,170 classrooms in 1996-97, 1,220 classrooms in
1997-98 and 1,270 classrooms by 1998-99.
<P>
To honor special contributions to the program, Visions Chapter of the Year Awards are
presented to two AFA chapters.  One is awarded to the chapter with the strongest Visions
program and one goes to the chapter with the most growth in its Vision effort. 
<P>
While AFA support for Visions nationwide remains strong, some areas have achieved remarkable
results -- sponsoring at least 50 classrooms.   During the past few years in New Jersey, the
Passaic Bergen and John Currie Memorial Chapters joined past State Presidents Enrico Camicelli
and Dolores Vailone to sponsor fifty Visions classrooms. And, for the first time in AEF's history,
four AFA chapters are sponsoring more than 50 classrooms each: the David D. Terry Chapter in
Jacksonville, Arkansas; the General E.W. Rawlings Chapter in St. Paul, Minnesota; the Wright
Memorial Chapter at Wright Patterson AFB, Ohio; and the Langley Chapter in Hampton,
Virginia. 
<P>
In the Northwest, an innovative partnership between the "Ninety-nines," a female pilots
organization, and AFA, pioneered by the Klamath Basin (Oregon) Chapter and AFA Regional
Vice President John Lee, has produced striking growth. In fact, they set a goal for every fifth
grade student in Klamath County to have the chance to participate in Visions. Other chapters in
the region have also signed up and initial reports from Alaska to Oregon indicate a banner year
for the Northwest. 
<P>
The success of Visions is directly attributable to the dedication of AFA chapters and the
demonstrated quality of the program. Teacher evaluations of the Visions program are consistent
with more than eighty percent rating the program as good or excellent in encouraging math and
science among their students. Teachers give the program high marks for enhancing students'
decision making, critical, imaginative and strategic thinking skills as well.
<P>
In the past, David Hill of Akron, Ohio, noted, "My students gained a great deal in the areas of
math and science, as well as current events. This was a valuable teaching tool for me .... " Anita
Barngrover, a teacher at Colleyville Elementary School, Colleyville, Texas, said "The science
interest is really sparked due to Visions," and Jim Harrison from Balboa School in Spokane,
Washington, noted, "As all budgets tighten, it is extremely beneficial to have the AFA support
this program."  
<P>
Some AFA chapters are using Visions to build closer ties with local schools.  In Enid, Oklahoma,
Visions students participated in an AFA sponsored essay contest with the winners treated to
simulator flights at Vance AFB. New Jersey Visions teachers report frequent visits from, and
broad appreciation for, their AFA sponsors. 
<P>
For AFA chapters who haven't yet joined the the Visions of Exploration program, please consider
becoming a part of this exceptional effort reaching thousands of school children across America.
<HR><P>
<B>Visit <A HREF="http://www.usatoday.com/classlin/clfront.htm">USA Today's Classline</A> designed to help teachers integrate today's top news into the classroom.</B><P><HR>
Send e-mail to <A HREF="mailto: AEFStaff@aef.org">AEFStaff@aef.org</A>
<HR>
