<HEAD>
<TITLE>Wright Flight Program</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY
BACKGROUND="backgrnd/vbar2.gif" BGCOLOR="#C0C0C0" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#0000FF" LEFTMARGIN="0" TOPMARGIN="0">
<P><A HREF="index.html"><IMG
SRC="images/torcher2.gif" ALT="Return to AEF Home Page" ALIGN="TOP" BORDER="0" VSPACE="0" HSPACE="12" WIDTH="46" HEIGHT="59"></A>
<IMG
SRC="images/afa_sup2.gif" ALIGN="TOP" BORDER="0" VSPACE="10" HSPACE="22" WIDTH="270" HEIGHT="54">
</P>
<P><IMG
SRC="backgrnd/spacer.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" VSPACE="1000" HSPACE="26" WIDTH="35" HEIGHT="4"></P>
<HR>
<H2 ALIGN=center>Wright Flight Program</H2>
     

<I>Wright Flight</I> is a non-profit corporation named after Orville and Wilbur Wright
for their first powered flight in an aircraft.  Using the universal appeal of flying to
motivate kids, the program teaches discipline and an interest in mathematics and
science.  The curriculum has two levels:
<P>
<B>Minuteman Program</B> for 4-5th grades.  Students who complete a contract
specifying the school areas they desire to improve and must sign a pledge to remain
drug, alcohol and smoke free during the six week program.  Successful student are
provided a with a half-day series of hands-on activities at the local military facility,
a certificate, bumper sticker, T-shirt and commemorative photo.  The lessons
cover:
<UL><LI>The Air National Guard, from the ground up
<LI>The Wright Brothers and how experiments and hard work lead to success
<LI>How Pilots plan a flight
<LI>Milestones of flight
<LI>The world of weightlessness
<LI>Women in aviation</UL>
<P>
<B>Basic Flight Program</B> for 6-12th grades is an eight lesson program which includes
a student setting goals and identifying steps to achieve them.  Those students
meeting the goals and passing the final exam with a score of 85% or better are
provided a half-hour hands-on flight in a light aircraft with a volunteer pilot.  The
course curriculum covers such topics as:
<UL><LI>The Wright Brothers
<LI>The Jimmy Doolittle story
<LI>The Schweinfurt Air Battle
<LI>The Battle of Midway
<LI>African Americans in aviation
<LI>NASA: From the dawn of the space age to the Shuttle</UL>
<P>
A number of AFA chapters have elected to participate in the Wright Flight Program
to encourage interest an aviation with local students.  To provide the course
material, workbooks and incentives, Wright Flight's cost per student is in excess of
$115, and they ask local sponsors to provide donations to defray part of these costs.  
<P>
Chapters interested in further information about the Wright Flight Program should
contact:
     <BLOCKQUOTE>Wright Flight, Inc.<BR>
     1300 East Valencia Road, #300<BR>
     Tucson, Arizona 85706<BR>
     (602) 294-0404</BLOCKQUOTE>


