<TITLE>Christa McAuliffe Memorial Award</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY
BACKGROUND="backgrnd/vbar2.gif" BGCOLOR="#C0C0C0" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#0000FF" LEFTMARGIN="0" TOPMARGIN="0">
<P><A HREF="index.html"><IMG
SRC="images/torcher2.gif" ALT="Return to AEF Home Page" ALIGN="TOP" BORDER="0" VSPACE="0" HSPACE="12" WIDTH="46" HEIGHT="59"></A>
<IMG
SRC="images/afa_sup2.gif" ALIGN="TOP" BORDER="0" VSPACE="10" HSPACE="22" WIDTH="270" HEIGHT="54">
</P>
<P><IMG
SRC="backgrnd/spacer.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" VSPACE="1000" HSPACE="26" WIDTH="35" HEIGHT="4"></P><HR>
<H2 ALIGN=center>Christa McAuliffe Memorial Award <BR>
Teacher of the Year</H2>


Christa McAuliffe's untimely death on the Space Shuttle Challenger gave us
thought about the valuable role teachers and educators fulfill in stimulating our
youth to "reach for the stars" in their dreams and aspirations to make the world of
tomorrow a better place for all mankind. 
<P>
The Aerospace Education Foundation, the educational affiliate of the Air Force Association has established
a recognition program to honor educators who have gone "the extra mile" to instill a
basic awareness of aerospace technologies in their students.
<P>
Local educators who hear of the honor may contact your local AFA chapter asking for
assistance with the nomination packet for the Christa McAuliffe National Award. 
Nominations from educatiors not submitted from an AFA chapter, State or Regional
organization will be disqualified. 
<P>
AFA chapters are encouraged to select a local teacher for the McAuliffe National Teacher of the
Year Award to honor an outstanding teacher who inspires an understanding of
science and mathematics and instills an awareness of aerospace technologies in
their students.
<P>
<B>Selection Criteria:</B>
<P>
The Christa McAuliffe Memorial Award honors an outstanding elementary or
secondary school teacher who has made great strides in instilling a greater interest
in the math/science education fields (Science: biology, physics, chemistry,
computer science, etc., Mathematics: algebra, trigonometry, geometry, etc.). More
specifically, we are looking for an educator who emphasizes the connection
between these technical subjects and America's need for qualified individuals in
aerospace careers. 
<P>
The winner will be honored at the Aerospace Education Foundation luncheon on
Monday, September 15, 1997. (The winning applicant will be flown to Washington,
DC on Saturday, September 13 and can anticipate departing sometime after 3 p.m.
on Monday, September 15. AEF will cover the costs for one coach class, round-trip
airline ticket and two nights lodging at the Sheraton Washington Hotel.) 
<P>
<B>Award Nomination:</B>

<UL><LI>Name
<LI>Address
<LI>School
<LI>Description of programs and activities that inspire a greater interest in the
math/science education fields.  The material can include news clippings,
photos or other materials describing the activities.
<LI>Teacher background/qualifications/honors
<UL><LI>Professional development, teaching philosophy, research,
honors/awards, civic service accomplishments, hobbies.</UL> 
<LI>Recommendations from students, parents, PTA, and fellow teachers.</UL>
<P>
The local AFA chapter will work with community educators to develop the
nomination packet.  The nomination should be a loose-leaf notebook, no larger than
2 inches thick. Videos will not be accepted.  For the contact point or location of an
AFA chapter in your area, please contact the national AEF office.
<P>
<B>Deadline for 1997 McAuliffe Award Nomination: June 6, 1997</B>
<HR>
Send e-mail to <A HREF="mailto: AEFStaff@aef.org">AEFStaff@aef.org</A>
<HR>
