<HEAD>
<TITLE>JROTC Video Contest</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY
BACKGROUND="backgrnd/vbar2.gif" BGCOLOR="#C0C0C0" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#0000FF" LEFTMARGIN="0" TOPMARGIN="0">
<P><A HREF="index.html"><IMG
SRC="images/torcher2.gif" ALT="Return to AEF Home Page" ALIGN="TOP" BORDER="0" VSPACE="0" HSPACE="12" WIDTH="46" HEIGHT="59"></A>
<IMG
SRC="images/resource.gif" ALIGN="TOP" BORDER="0" VSPACE="10" HSPACE="22" WIDTH="270" HEIGHT="54">
</P>
<P><IMG
SRC="backgrnd/spacer.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" VSPACE="1000" HSPACE="26" WIDTH="35" HEIGHT="4"></P><HR>
<H2 ALIGN=center>JROTC Video Contest</H2>                      

<P.
Each year, AEF sponsors an Video Contest for Air Force JROTC units.  
<P>
Since 1973, AEF in cooperation with the U.S. Air Force has sponsored a video contest for all
AFJROTC units.  The contest supplements and reinforces the cadet aerospace and leadership
education courses by encouraging cooperation and teamwork to accomplish a specific goal--produce a videotape documenting how the unit meets its mission.
<P>
<B>CRITERIA:</B>
<P>
<UL><LI>Videos must be limited to five minutes.
<LI>The video production must be created, shot, dubbed, mixed and produced by the cadets.
<LI>The video must include the school name, address and JROTC unit number.
<LI>The video must be on VHS format
<LI>Entries are due by March 7, 1997
</UL>
<P>
<B>AWARDS:</B>
<P>
<UL><LI><I>1st Place</I> Receives a cash award of $1,000 and a plaque for permanent display at the unit.  The ASI,
          High School principal and three representative from the unit will be invited to the
          Aerospace Education Foundation luncheon held during the AFA national
          Convention in Washington, DC September 15, 1997.

<LI><I>2nd Place </I>Receives a cash award of $750 and a plaque for permanent display

<LI><I>3rd Place</I> Receives a cash award of $500 and a plaque for permanent display</UL>
<P>

The mission of the AFJROTC program is to educate and train high school cadets in citizenship;
promote community service; instill responsibility, character, and self-discipline; and provide
instruction in air and space fundamentals.
<P>
The theme for this year's JROTC video contest was "Meeting the AFJROTC Mission." AEF
received over 150 tapes from units all over the world.  The judges evaluated each video based on
the unit's ability to fulfill the following objectives:
<OL><LI>Educate and train high school cadets in citizenship (15%)
<LI>Promote community service (15%)
<LI>Instill responsibility, character and self-discipline (15%)
<LI>Provide instruction in air and space fundamentals (15%)
<LI>Creative and original production (15%)
<LI>Technical merit (15%)
<LI>Time limit (10%)</OL>
<P>
<H3 ALIGN=center>Below are the winners and honorable mentions from the 1996 contest.</H3>
<P> 
Del Campo High School in Fair Oaks, Calif. won the JROTC video contest for the third year in a
row. This year the cadets at CA-863 demonstrated how they fulfill the JROTC mission by
participating in a youth leadership council on drugs and alcohol, working with the needy during
the holidays, making improvements in the teachers' lounge and working with new JROTC units
to teach leadership and drill and ceremony.  The unit also participated in leadership training, drill
meets and encampments with other JROTC units.  During the year, the cadets went on military
flights, attended ground school and hosted an academic challenge with 12 schools involved. 
<P>
Second place went to Bellevue West High School in Nebraska. The NE-771st worked with
Mothers Against Drunk Driving to raise awareness of the problem in their community.  The
cadets also participated in summer leadership school, placed second in a state quiz bowl and built
a display in the school cafeteria depicting military heritage from WWII through the Gulf War.
The unit color guard participated in many community activities and during the holidays the
cadets "adopted" 30 needy children in the K-mart Adopt-A-Child program.
<P>
The cadets of Forest High School in Ocala, Fla., captured third place.  Their unit recently built a
house with Habitat for Humanity and the color and honor guards participated in community
activities and football games throughout the year. The cadets took field trips to local air force
bases and helped teachers move in to new school facilities. During Veterans' Day, the unit held a
flag vigil. 
<P>
<U><B>Honorable Mention</B></U>
<P>
<table><tr><td><B>Squadron</B></td><td>  <B>School</B></td></tr>
<tr><td>CA-011 </td><td>   Novato H.S.</td></tr>      
