<HEAD>
<TITLE>von Karman Scholarships</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY
BACKGROUND="backgrnd/vbar2.gif" BGCOLOR="#C0C0C0" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#0000FF" LEFTMARGIN="0" TOPMARGIN="0">
<P><A HREF="index.html"><IMG
SRC="images/torcher2.gif" ALT="Return to AEF Home Page" ALIGN="TOP" BORDER="0" VSPACE="0" HSPACE="12" WIDTH="46" HEIGHT="59"></A>
<IMG
SRC="images/scholar.gif" ALIGN="TOP" VSPACE="16" HSPACE="18" WIDTH="373" HEIGHT="31">
</P>
<P><IMG
SRC="backgrnd/spacer.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" VSPACE="1000" HSPACE="26" WIDTH="35" HEIGHT="4"></P>
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER">AEF Scholarships and Grants</H2><HR>

<CENTER><H3>von Karman Scholarships</H3></CENTER>
<p>

AEF's Dr. Theodore von Karman Graduate Scholarships of $5,000 are awarded each year to five of 
the most outstanding AFROTC graduates for advanced degrees in mathematics, engineering or the 
sciences. Selections are based on the students' academic records, recommendations from professors
 and others, as well as written materials.
<P>
The two-step selection process begins with a board at ROTC headquarters at Maxwell AFB, Ala., 
with final selections being confirmed by the Foundation. 
<P>
The von Karman Class of 1997 is the eighth group of scholarship recipients.  Selection announcements 
will be made by the end of May 1997.  
<P>
<B>ELIGIBILITY</B>
<P>
<UL<LI>Air Force ROTC seniors who will graduate and be commissioned in fiscal year 1995.       
   <LI>Prior to the actual grant of the scholarship, the applicant must provide evidence of 
       acceptance for admission to an accredited masters program at a U.S. college or technical 
       institution in a full-time course of study leading to a graduate degree, and must remain 
       a student in good standing for the duration of the scholarship. </UL>
<P>
<B>SELECTION CRITERIA</B>
<P>
<UL<LI>Students who are otherwise qualified are selected on the basis of scholastic ability or 
       potential leadership skills and apparent qualties of personal excellence. 
   <LI>The applicant's file will be reviewed to determine if eligibility requirements have been 
       met. The Scholarship Committee must be satisfied that progress is being made toward the 
       completion of the undergraduate degree. </UL>
<P>
<B>APPLICATION:</B>
<P>
Eligible students may request an application form from their Professor of Aerospace Studies 
(PAS). Applications must be postmarked by February 1, 1997 to the Aerospace Education Foundation
 through the AFROTC. 
<P>
<UL><LI>Official grade transcript from Freshman, Sophomore, Junior and Senior years, through the last semester completed at the time the application is submitted. 
    <LI>Letter of reference from a school official, employer or civic leader.       
    <LI>Applicant's autobiography including Air Force career plans and reasons for pursuing an advanced degree. (Please limit to two pages) 
    <LI>Submit a "Technical Reference" from a faculty member in your academic department, which includes an estimate of your chances for success in the proposed area of study. This could be in the form of a letter included in the package or a letter sent separately to AEF (Must be postmarked by February 15, 1997).       
    <LI>Application(s) for delayed entry on to active duty. 
    <LI>Letter of recommendation from PAS. 
    <LI>Resume </UL>
<P><B><A HREF="mailto: AEFStaff@aef.org">AEFStaff@aef.org</A></B>
<HR>
<CENTER><H3>1996-97 von Karman Scholarship Recipients</H3></CENTER>
<P>
<I>Five Air Force ROTC graduating seniors have been named winners of the von Karman $5,000 for 
graduate-level academic work in engineering, mathematics or science.</I>
<P>
Todd Graham<BR>
Clemson University -- Environmental Systems Engineering/Process Engineering
<P>
Kristofer Labowski<BR>
Pennsylvania State University -- Nuclear Engineering
<P>
Kelly Mirone<BR>
University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill -- Operations Research
<P>
Christopher Snyder<BR>
University of Dayton and the Air Force Institute of Technology -- Aerospace Engineering/Aerodynamics
<P>
Jesse Zydallis<BR>
New Jersey Institute of Technology -- Computer Engineering
<P>
