<HEAD>
<TITLE>Colorado Springs-Dorfman</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY
BACKGROUND="backgrnd/vbar2.gif" BGCOLOR="#C0C0C0" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#0000FF" LEFTMARGIN="0" TOPMARGIN="0">
<P><A HREF="index.html"><IMG
SRC="images/torcher2.gif" ALT="Return to AEF Home Page" ALIGN="TOP" BORDER="0" VSPACE="0" HSPACE="12" WIDTH="46" HEIGHT="59"></A>

<IMG
SRC="images/library.gif" ALIGN="TOP" VSPACE="16" HSPACE="18" WIDTH="345" HEIGHT="34">
</P>
<P><IMG SRC="backgrnd/spacer.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" VSPACE="2500" HSPACE="26" WIDTH="35" HEIGHT="4"><HR><H2 align="CENTER">Foundation Forums</H2><HR>
Air Force Association Symposium<BR>
Colorado Springs<BR>
May 24, 1996<BR>
Mr. Steven D. Dorfman<BR>
<P>
  I am honored to be here to represent the industry view in a conference on Air Force
acquisition, a subject that is vital to national security.  As the nation's space assets are used more
and more to gather and disseminate information and intelligence for the warfighter, there is no
question that they have become critical to the warfighting process   and a major differentiating
strength for our military.
<P>  The importance of situational awareness was proven definitively during Desert Storm.  But
Desert Storm also showed that further improvements are necessary, and many studies for new
systems are underway.  I personally applaud DoD's focus on improving the acquisition process,
and I see plenty of evidence that this is happening.  I'd like to talk about three significant forces
that make such improvement mandatory.
<P>  The first is the most obvious one; namely, that increasing budget pressures make it more
important than ever to forge a more efficient acquisition system.  In fact, in both the defense and
commercial environments, all customers are demanding more performance for less money.  In
the case of DoD, the customers are U.S. taxpayers.  We have to listen to our customers.  They
want more for less, and that is what we must give them.
 <P> The second force mandating acquisition change is the increasing pace of technology
advancement, which compels us to reduce cycle time from acquisition to deployment.  Most of
us are familiar with "Moore's Law," which was advanced by Gordon Moore, currently chairman
of Intel.  Several decades ago, Moore predicted that the number of circuits on each
semiconductor chip would double every two years.  Over a long period of time, this has proven
true.  In fact, in recent years, the number of circuits has actually doubled every 18 months.  This
enhanced capability can have a significant impact on the performance of our systems, if we are
able to harness it.
 <P> For example, MILSTAR took approximately 12 years to deploy from initial procurement. 
During this time period, the computing power of chips increased by a factor of 250.  Think about
the implications of this for the MILSTAR program.  In fact, as many of you know, by the time
we launched MILSTAR, some of the payload was obsolete.  This happened not only because of
technological advances, but also because the threat model had changed over this long time
period.  With technology turnover so swift and the world political environment changing so
rapidly, it is clear that we must reduce acquisition cycle time.  Similarly, we must have sufficient
flexibility in the procurement process to incorporate technology improvements and respond to
changes in the political environment.
 <P> The third significant force arguing for change in the acquisition process is the rapid growth of
commercial space, including launch vehicles, satellites, and ground systems.  For example, there
are now more commercial communications satellites launched each year than DoD satellites.  In
1996 alone, 34 commercial satellites are scheduled for launch, and an estimated 350 are to be
launched through the end of the decade.
 <P> I believe that, through acquisition reform, government and industry can work together to
greatly improve the capabilities, delivery time, and cost-effectiveness of our nation's space-based
defense systems.  In fact, we are already realizing significant progress, plus mutual benefits, in
the areas of launch vehicles and communications satellites.
<P>
Launch Vehicles
<P>  As we know, the Air Force recreated the expendable launch vehicle [ELV] industry with
MLV II and MLV III, the Delta II and the Atlas.  Now the commercial sector is making good use
of these assets, plus Ariane, Proton, Long March, and others.  However, despite all these systems,
there is still an excess of demand over supply for launches.  I predict that demand will continue
to exceed supply through the year 2000, and maybe beyond.
<P>  Many of us in this room have advocated a new generation of ELV that would simultaneously
provide more assured and affordable access to space for the government sector, and a more
internationally competitive launch vehicle capability for the commercial sector.  In the last few
years, the European-built Ariane launch vehicle has dominated in market share.
 <P> However, we have found that a new U.S. ELV has been a tough sell in Washington, given all
the competing demands on today's decreasing DoD budget.  The fundamental problem is that
today's stable of launch vehicles meets today's government mission requirements.  The purpose
of a new launch vehicle is to save money.  But, in Washington, it is hard to justify spending
money now to save money later.  Out of this situation, the EELV [Evolved Expendable Launch
Vehicle] has emerged.  But, unfortunately, the first operational launch isn't going to occur until
the next century.  I believe that in the area of launch services, government has an opportunity to
achieve significant cost-efficiencies provided by the commercial sector.
<P>  Hughes has a direct interest in launch services because we acquire them both for our own
fleet of satellites and for many of our customers that want their satellites delivered on orbit.  By
the end of this decade, we will have purchased more than 60 launches, making us the largest
commercial buyer of launch services.  We have purchased launch services on the Shuttle, Atlas,
Titan, Delta, Long March, Ariane, and Proton.  This buying power has permitted us to make a
contribution to increasing the robustness of the launch vehicle industry for all users.
<P>  In addition, last year we committed to buy 10 Delta III launch vehicles from McDonnell
Douglas.  This enabled McDonnell Douglas to justify making a substantial corporate investment
to develop a cryogenic upper stage and other technologies that will enable them to convert the
Delta II, which can take a 4,000-pound vehicle to GTO [geostationary transfer orbit] into a Delta
III, which can transport an 8,000-pound vehicle to GTO.  
 <P> Thus, as of mid-1998, the U.S. government will have available for its use two launch vehicles
with this heavy-lift capability: the Atlas and the Delta III.  So, the government will benefit as
well as Hughes.  Obviously, in doing this deal, Hughes was acting in its own self-interest. 
Because we were the first and largest buyer of Delta III launches, we received attractive
contractual terms.  But I believe the Air Force will be a beneficiary too.
 <P> Also last year, Hughes completed a similar transaction with Boeing for the Boeing Sea
Launch vehicle, which will have the capacity to lift 12,000 pounds to geostationary transfer orbit. 
Boeing is combining a Zenit rocket from Ukraine, an Energia-built Block DM upper stage from
Russia, a mobile platform from Norway, and is doing the systems integration.  The Boeing Sea
Launch vehicle will be very flexible and will be berthed in southern California's Long Beach
harbor, just a short distance from our satellite integration and test facility.  This provides great
added value to us.
 <P> For both of these new launch vehicle procurements, the acquisition cycle time from idea to
contract, including board approvals, was about six months.  The time from contract to first
launch, in mid-1998, will be about three years.  The size of the Hughes team monitoring
McDonnell Douglas and Boeing is fewer than 10 people; there is also a small budget for
consultants.  
  <P>Thus, launch vehicles are one area where the government sector can benefit from certain
cost-efficiencies, new technologies, cycle-time reductions, and supply increases achieved by
industry.
<P>
Advanced, Cost-efficient Communications Satellites
<P>  Another area where industry can contribute added robustness and cost-efficiency to
government defense systems is communications satellites.  It is estimated that more than $30
billion will be invested in commercial communications satellites over the next five years. 
Growth in this business has been about 10 to 12 percent per year over a long period of time, and I
predict such growth will continue basically for two reasons.
<P>  One is the end of the Cold War.  That has led to the global economy that we have today, and
to the requirement that both developing and developed countries bolster their infrastructure  
transportation, power, and communications   in order to compete successfully.  For many
developing countries, communications gets a jump start through satellites.  There is an increased
acquisition of satellites by countries like Thailand and Malaysia, and even smaller countries that
haven't bought satellites before.
 <P> The other fundamental force driving the growth of commercial satellites is all the new
applications they offer that are generated by new satellite technologies.  These new applications
fall into three categories.  The first is direct-to-home television.  For example, Hughes developed
something called DIRECTV.  Coincidentally, the broadcast center for DIRECTV is a few miles
down the road, at Castle Rock.  Today we have 1.5 million U.S. subscribers.  Our plans are to go
global with the service, and, starting next month, we go into service in Latin America, from
Mexico all the way to Argentina.
 <P> DIRECTV uses the most sophisticated new technologies.  We have three satellites in orbit
transmitting compressed digital video.  Right now, in fact, DIRECTV is raining one gigabyte per
second on your head.  An 18-inch dish and associated indoor electronics costing a total of $500
are all that's needed to receive up to 200 channels of video.  There is going to be a lot of
DIRECTV, and other direct-to-home services, around the world.
 <P> The second category of new satellite applications, which also uses digital communications, is
satellite mobile telephony and data.  American Mobile Satellite Corporation, of which Hughes
owns 27 percent, has the first dedicated land-mobile system in orbit right now.  It's a GEO
[geostationary Earth orbit] system, and, currently, we are working on the second generation,
which will enable handheld communications from GEO.  We are also building mobile telephony
satellite systems for India and China, while others are building systems for Indonesia and the
Philippines.  These Asia-Pacific regional systems are currently driving the marketplace.  Hughes
also is building a medium-Earth orbit [MEO] system for a company called ICO, which will
compete with the LEO [low-Earth orbit] Iridium and Globalstar systems for global handheld
telephony.
 <P> The third new satellite application is the private network, which uses low-cost, very small
aperture terminals [VSATs].  I am talking about a per-terminal cost now of $10,000, going down
to $5,000, and ultimately to $1,000.  Worldwide, Hughes has installed about 200,000 of our own
VSATs, for about a 60-percent market share.  There are probably about 300,000 VSATs around
the world configured into a large number of private networks for the transmission of data, voice,
and video.  Now we are working on the next generation of private networks, a service we call
Spaceway, which will further drive down costs and permit, through an ATM [asynchronous
transfer mode] switch in the sky, very high speed interactive multimedia communications.  All
these applications are fueling the growth of communications satellites, and I believe this growth
will accelerate over the next few years.
 <P> This is a very competitive marketplace.  There are about five or six companies here in the
United States and in Europe that build satellites.  The Europeans are well subsidized, so the push
is on us to continually improve our productivity and also improve our technology.  As a
consequence, I calculate that over the last 10 years, the cost-effectiveness of Hughes satellites has
increased by a factor of three to five.  When you add digital compression and digital
communication into the equation, our satellites are about 25 times more cost-effective now than
they were 10 years ago.  The market shows great price-performance elasticity.  It is one of the
driving forces that is stimulating growth.   
<P>
Communications Satellites and the Evolving Acquisition Process
 <P> As I've described, the communications satellite business offers increasing cost-efficiencies
and technological capabilities.  These improvements can benefit our defense system, provided
that changes are made to the acquisition process.  A good example is the Global Broadcast
System [GBS], which I will address in more detail shortly.  But this is a key example of an area
where we are able to provide transmission capability of a gigabyte per second to ordinary
consumers, yet our warfighters don't have anything near that capability.  We are going to change
that very quickly.
 <P> It is my view that DoD and the Air Force are collectively reading these changes and
modifying the acquisition process accordingly.  In fact, many of today's presentations make clear
that a lot of the things I've been advocating have already been incorporated into defense plans. 
The cultural changes are being made   more slowly than anybody would like, but it is
happening.
<P>  Just as you see many different suppliers, I see many different buyers   Air Force, Navy,
NASA, and the commercial sector.  I have a unique perspective on the acquisition process
because Hughes not only builds satellite systems for the government and commercial markets,
but also owns and operates a proprietary fleet of 16 satellites.  Last night, we put a 17th in orbit,
Galaxy IX, which was launched by the Delta.
 <P> One myth I'd like to dispel right now is that there is a monolithic commercial procurement
process.  It varies all over the place.  For example, Intelsat has a very sophisticated procurement
process that involves hundreds of people, takes a long time, and is followed by extensive in-plant
supervision.  By contrast, Intelsat's most significant competitor, PanAmSat, has bought
approximately $2 billion worth of satellites and launch vehicles with a handful of people, most of
them outside consultants, and with practically no oversight.  Both compete in the same
marketplace.  In our commercial programs, we have everything in between.  This is evidence that
one size does not fit all, which is a wise view to take regarding procurement.  Each situation
should be tailored to the specific needs of the individual customer.  Efforts toward acquisition
reform should take into account this flexibility and custom tailoring.
  <P>
Positive Change: The UHF Follow-on Acquisition
 <P> One of the most effective acquisitions that I have been personally involved with in the DoD
area is the UHF Follow-on, procured by the U.S. Navy with a lot of help from the Air Force.  It
incorporated a lot of the changes we need to make.  For example, it procured a delivered-on-orbit
system, which enabled us to compete the launch vehicles and get a very competitive contract. 
Using Lockheed-Martin for the launch vehicles, it cost an average of under $70 million a year.  
 <P> It also permitted us to use our commercial bus.  We had designed our HS 601 to be dual-use,
so that the satellite, which is roughly in the 4,000- to 8,000-Watt range of power, was designed
with MilSpecs and with hardening so it could meet military requirements.  Because we were
permitted to use that bus, we were able to pass on tremendous savings to the U.S. Navy and to
DoD.
 <P> This procurement process also was flexible enough so that we could add payloads, and we
have done that.  Starting with the fourth vehicle, we added a MILSTAR-compatible EHF
payload, which extended the capability of the MILSTAR system.  There will be a total of seven
of these satellites with EHF payloads in orbit before it is all over, to further extend the MILSTAR
coverage.  Also, starting with UHF-8, we will be adding a GBS payload.  This is a good story,
because it entailed cooperation among the Air Force, Navy and others to accelerate the
deployment of GBS for the warfighter.  When DoD saw clearly what Hughes was doing in the
commercial sector with GBS   and others will follow   they wanted it for the warfighter.
 <P> A game plan evolved to have a full GBS capability in service probably in the year 2002 or
2003.  But because of the flexibility of the program we had in place, it was possible to add on a
smaller, early-entry GBS capability   but still a pretty good payload, with four 24-megabit-per-second transponders on each of the three UHFs that will be launched in the 1998-99 timeframe.      As a result, we will have global coverage and a pilot program, but a pilot program that is
sufficiently flexible that it could be used for warfighting if necessary.  Our troops will be getting
situational awareness intelligence and maybe the NFL football season when they are at sea or at
war.  
 <P> I feel this is the kind of flexible procurement process we can use in the future.  By the way,
this program has commercial warranties, so that when the first UHF satellite did not reach orbit
because of a malfunction of the launch vehicle, we were able to replace that satellite at no extra
cost to the government.  There is a good commercial feel to this program.
 <P> 
Acquisition Reform Is Working
  <P>I also see great progress in the SBIRS [Space-Based Infrared System] acquisition.  All I can
do is endorse the changes.  The teaming among the users, the warfighters, the acquirers and
industry to define an affordable and achievable SBIRS program, which is what we have now, is
part of the acquisition process. 
 <P> The acquisition process started back in early 1995 with competition and downselecting.  The
full-scale development contract will begin with the demval [demonstration and validation] work,
and will be completed 20 months later.  This is much faster than anything that has been achieved
in the past for this kind of acquisition.  So efforts to speed up acquisition cycle time are working.
 <P> I also think that teaming between industry and government is working as it relates to the use
of commercial technologies.  For instance, I see very good work being done in the MILSATCOM
architecture.  I predict the next-generation MILSTAR system, or MILSATCOM, will rely heavily
on the commercial space sector   for example, by leasing bent-pipe transponders and by buying
voice and video capacity on demand from the satellite systems with on-board signal processing
payloads, such as ICO, Iridium, and Spaceway.
 <P> That will be one way that industry will serve DoD's needs.  Another will be through
customized satellites.  There is no question that there will be a need for customized payloads to
accommodate such requirements as hardening and anti-jamming, and for the unique services that
DoD will be providing.  Nevertheless, I suspect that these customized payloads will be built
based on a lot of commercial communications technologies.  
 <P> Earlier, I spoke of the dual-use HS 601 bus we are using for the UHF Follow-on program. 
More of that sort of thing is going to be in the cards.  Many of the components that are being
developed for commercial applications will also be used in the MILSATCOM architecture of the
next century.  This will substantially reduce the cost of communications for DoD.  I am confident
of that.
 <P> In summary, acquisition reform is well underway and is working.  There has been much
progress, but much more is to come.  In today's times of evolving threats and limited resources, it
is an obligation of industry and government to give taxpayers what they want, and that is more
for less.  I thank you.
 <P> <I>MS. LANTZY: </I> When you decided to add Rad-hard MilSpec standards to the design of the HS
601, was it because of long-range marketing or other projections of future military needs?
 <P> <I>MR. DORFMAN:</I>  The answer is "Yes."  When we went to the board of directors for the money
to build the HS 601 on speculation, we justified it across the broad base of commercial and
government applications.  It was part of our strategy from the beginning.  Today we are up to 59
HS 601s that are on order, and 13 are for the U.S. government.  That is a number we are working
hard to increase, and we will.
 <P> <I>MS. LANTZY: </I> Thank you, Mr. Dorfman.  
<HR>
