<P><A HREF="index.html"><IMG
SRC="images/torcher2.gif" ALT="Return to AEF Home Page" ALIGN="TOP" BORDER="0" VSPACE="0" HSPACE="12" WIDTH="46" HEIGHT="59"></A>

<IMG
SRC="images/library.gif" ALIGN="TOP" VSPACE="16" HSPACE="18" WIDTH="345" HEIGHT="34">
</P>
<P><IMG SRC="backgrnd/spacer.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" VSPACE="3400" HSPACE="26" WIDTH="35" HEIGHT="4"><HR><H2 align="CENTER">Foundation Forums</H2><HR>
<P>
Colonel Michael A. Collings<BR>
Chief, AF Office of Outsourcing and Privatization<BR>
Deputy Chief of Staff for Logistics<BR>
Outsourcing and Privatization<BR>
AFA Symposium<BR>
Colorado Springs, Colo.<BR> 
May 24, 1996<BR>
<P>
  Good morning.  I d like to thank the Air Force Association for allowing the Outsourcing and
Privatization Office to have this opportunity to get our message out. 
 <P> In light of the declining Defense budget, a shortfall in the modernization account has led to the
realization that the Department of Defense needs a revolution in business affairs to support the
evolution in military affairs.  The services need to do their part for this transformation to doing
business better and more efficiently.  The Outsourcing and Privatization Office, which I head up,
is an important part of the Air Force s strategic business plan to address this challenge.  
 <P> The Air Force has gone through some turbulent times   downsizing, force structure and personnel
changes, and modernization accounts are at a low point.  Most recently Secretary of Defense Perry
said that we need to plus up our modernization efforts by about $60 billion a year, of which $40
billion would hopefully be picked up by Congress, leaving about a $20 billion to the services. 
That is about $7 billion for the Air Force.  We hope we can come up with initiatives for
outsourcing and privatization that would yield savings and help fund that modernization account. 
<P>
  These are formative events to this process: the Commission on Roles and Missions and the Base
Realignment and Closure Commission-95 which impacted the San Antonio Air Logistics Center and the
Sacramento ALC.  Believe me that is a hot potato right now.  
<P>  A look at the history of the DoD modernization account shows funding for modernization has declined
from 59 percent of the budget in 1983 to 43 percent in 1985, and today it is only 29 percent.  In
terms of Air Force Total Obligation Authority, we have suffered serious declines also in our
investment accounts.  
<P>  Dr. John White, the Deputy Secretary is leading the charge for the DoD Outsourcing and
Privatization Integrated Policy Team.  The Assistant Secretary of Defense for Economic Security,
Mr. John Goodman, is running the Integrated Process Team on a day-to-day basis.  The teams are
broken out by functional areas ranging from Education and Training to Depot Maintenance.
<P>  The Air Force IPT reports directly to the Assistant Vice Chief of Staff even though my office
symbol is LG-1.  We have an Executive Steering Group comprised of general officer or SES
equivalents representing the two-digit offices on the Air Staff and Secretariat.  They meet once
a month as a minimum.  We met last Wednesday to provide oversight for an outsourcing and
privatization initiative.  
 <P> The charter is to serve as the Air Force s single point of contact for outsourcing and
privatization and to help facilitate corporate strategic thinking to esolve problems and provide
headquarters oversight for outsourcing and privatization.  
<P>  Because of the enormity and complexity of the full blown outsourcing and privatization challenge,
our mission is to institutionalize the optimum Air Force use of public and private sector
resources.  In other words, we are to chart an official path for the Air Force, now and in the long
run, to take maximum advantage of the public and private sector capabilities.  
<P>  Outsourcing and privatization is a strategic program and has been a major topic of discussion at
the last two Corona Conferences.  It has full support from the Chief and the Secretary.  
<P>  Our goal is to achieve improved performance, normally with reduced costs, by doing business more
efficiently and cost-effectively.  I use the words "normally with reduced costs" because there may
be some functional areas where replacing that function provided by the government with a private
sector capability could in fact cost a little bit more than if it was institutionalized in
government, but in the aggregate, the whole process may end up saving the government more money. 
A prime example is the elimination of LogAir.  A few years back as a logistics commander, I thought
that my F-15s were going to die on the ramp if I didn t have LogAir distributing three pallets of
parts every day.  But, we ve gone with faster and more just-in-time logistics support.  It has in
fact cost us a little bit more for that portion, but because of the quick turn around times, we
have been able to reduce inventory and fix aircraft much faster.  
 <P> Our second goal is to generate savings for modernization through  increased efficiencies, where
possible.  At a time of declining DoD budgets, we ve concluded that money for modernization must
come partly from the savings generated from outsourcing and privatization.  We have been tracking
savings from outsourcing and privatization for the past two decades and the aggregate average
savings for those initiatives has been about 29 percent.  They range anywhere from 10 percent
savings to as high as 40 percent.  Most recently, we are in the process of awarding a contract for
an in-house operation to the most efficient organization at Altus Air Force Base [Okla.], and that
savings is going to be in the neighborhood of 45 percent.  
<P>  The terms outsourcing and privatization are defined a number of ways.  A lot of people use them
synonymously, but it is important to note a difference between them.  For the purpose of the Air
Force, we see outsourcing as the bigger of the two categories with privatization being an ultimate
form of outsourcing, one in which the public sector, either across the board or in particular
locations, transfers the assets and associated activities from the public to the private sector. 
When such a complete transfer normally occurs, we call it privatization.  When no assets are
transferred from the government, we refer to that transition as an arrangement of outsourcing. 
The distinction becomes significant in terms of strategic planning regarding outsourcing.  For
example, management should probably decide whether or not something can or should be privatized
before it commits to a lesser degree of outsourcing.  Along these same lines, if maximum efficiency
is sought, a large outsourcing arrangement should probably be considered before looking at a number
of smaller ones to cover the same targeted functions.  
<P>  What are some of the assumptions that we have undertaken within our outsourcing and privatization
program?  There must be a performance gap.  The underpinnings of the Air Force outsourcing and
privatization program implies commercial firms operate more rapidly and efficiently in some areas,
making outsourcing and prvatization the preferred approach for accomplishing certain Air Force
activities.  
 <P> The private sector role within the Air Force will grow in the future, and the savings should be
rolled into modernization programs.  
 <P> OSD has a similar view of potential O&P dividends and savings.  They see that competition will
drive savings, and it will drive performance.  Without competition, both from external, private
industry, and internal, the public sector, the basic program will not succeed in meeting
performance standards or bringing savings.  It allows commanders the flexibility to administer
certain functions, whether with a local contractor outside the gate or from within his own means,
for a more efficient organization.  There can also be some economies of scales by bundling service
contracts and functions.  Lastly, there can be better management focus.  Business analysts
frequently highlight how the retention of an organization s leadership is a scarce commodity and
should be valued as highly as infrastructure and other capital assets.  Where possible, leaders
should be focusing intensely on their core competencies and not be distracted by looking at things
that don t need to be accomplished as a part of their mission function.
 <P> There have been fundamental changes associated with corporate America s response:  an integrated
global economy and high rates of innovation and technological change.  Corporate America has
responded through reengineering of business processes, concentrating on core competencies,
networking,  downsizing and outsourcing.  We in the Air Force need to be able to capitalize on
their increasing ability to focus on their core competencies and provide that service to us.  
 <P> Deciding what to outsource in light of a "strategic sourcing" approach is very important.  I
alluded to that earlier.  In the past,  the Air Force has looked at functions from a base level
perspective and really didn t use a strategic point of view.  We need to think about what the Air
Force should look like in the future.  What are those core competencies that we need in the Air
Force?  
<P>  We need to conduct best value analysis, demonstrated by past performances   reliability,
timeliness, quality and lower costs   then establish and manage a responsible partnership with
industry.  We do that through acquisition reform, contract reform, and allowing longer lengths of
time for contract performance.  
 <P> In the private sector, an example is NORDAM based out of Tulsa, Oklahoma.  It has contracts with
United Airlines that just recently bought 125 Boeing 777s.  The contract structured between United
and NORDAM was for the life that United operates the 777s unless the fleet drops below five.  The
contract is performance based so that if United is not getting the service from NORDAM, they can
cancel the contract.  But, more important, after the first two or three years of that contract,
depending upon the commodity that is being repaired, there is a decrease of anywhere from 20 to
upwards of 35 percent in the cost to the customer and then a corresponding decrease of one to three
percent annually for process improvement.  This incentivizes the contractor to improve his
processes.  It is a longer management partnership with both the government and the private
contract.  
 <P> It forces the government to guarantee that a particular system will be around for that length of
time.  That is a new way of thinking, but a way to partner with industry and be able to get the
cost savings associated with outsourcing and privatization.  
<P>  There are some major considerations and major constraints to outsourcing.  First of all, we cannot
decrease the quality of Air Force operations.  As a matter of fact, we will actually look at
improving our readiness posture and our quality.  There are certain inherently governmental and
military essential categories that will not be outsourced or privatized.  
 <P> The Air Force Programming Directorate is reviewing all Air Force manpower slots to determine if
they are inherently governmental or militarily essential.  I believe some of those things will
change in the future.  
 <P> There are current legislative policies that do not allow outsourcing nd privatization.  An example
is fire fighting and some security.  
 <P> There is a fundamental shift in the nature of outsourcing.  We need to start thinking on a larger
scale and move from the tactical to the more strategic.  Instead of looking to work with each
individual vendor, we need to think about partnering our relationships.  By not focusing so much
on cost, we can find best value with a performance focus.  Through the restructure of individual
contracts, we change from many small outsourcing initiatives to larger activities.  It will mean
a move from simple to more complex activities.
 <P> We will fundamentally change both customer roles and the behavior of the provider.  We will develop
"contracting for service" as a core competency.  On the provider side of the house, it will
customize those core services to meet our individual customer requirements and needs.  
  It will focus on performance and not how work is to be done.  It allows the provider in private
industry to come up with ways to meet our performance needs.  It delegates management of
transactions and invests deeply in few high quality partners.  We can choose partners who know how
to exploit provider capabilities.
<P>
  An approach for optimum contracting would be to focus on the performance and value and to emphasize
flexibility.  It specifies an approach to employ specific measures and to specify performance
metrics tied to the end product.  It is not getting into the business of telling how to do it, but
allow them to provide the processes based on end performance.  
 <P> We emphasize flexibility, contract adjustment mechanisms, and provide rewards and penalties tied
to performance.  One of the greatest incentives tied to performance is another year of contract. 
The  performance period may be two to three years with the potential for added years of one-year
contracts based on performance.  It incentivizes that business relationship and lets the provider
invest in the business processes, knowing they are based on performance and a long-term business
relationship with you.  
<P>  Clearly, given the scope of the program, its success is largely contingent on how the Air Force
will manage key relationships with the MAJCOMs, bases, sister services, OSD, government civilians,
organized labor, Congress, the private sector and the general public   a multitude of critical
relationships.  
 <P> The closer integration of the private sector with the Air Force is a development that must be
understood and discussed within the context of all effected partners.   The major commands within the Air Force have a role.  We ve asked for their complete cooperation
in the program.  This includes pushing the envelope for new ideas to seek out innovative
possibilities and functions for outsourcing and privatization.  We are essentially doing a
comprehensive review of the corporate Air Force relationship with the private sector in order to
optimize outsourcing and privatization options.  At the same time, we want to institutionalize the
process of identifying resulting O&P programs into our POM process.  The MAJCOMs must be able to
provide the big picture for the wings, roll initiatives up from the wing level to be incorporated
MAJCOM or Air Force-wide.  
<P>  There are many current outsourcing and privatization initiatives within the Department of Defense. 
Within the Air Force, we have capitalized on partnering with industry to outsource most of the Base
Operating Support within our Air Education and Trainin Command.  At Vance Air Force Base [Texas],
everything on the base has been outsourced with the exception of the instructor pilots and the
command hierarchy.  Arnold Air Force Station [Tenn.] is another example of that.  
 <P> The outsourcing and privatization program is comprehensive and demanding.  Some important inroads
have been made, but tremendous amounts are left to do.  
<P>  We are tracking outsourcing and privatization at the MAJCOM level.  OSD has asked the service to
identify outsourcing and privatization initiatives as part of the POM process.  Currently, we have
aggregate savings from outsourcing and privatization of $1.2 billion in the 1998 POM.   
 <P> In order to achieve some near-term efficiencies in areas where the private sector should be able
to contribute more, the MAJCOMs have been asked to have a hard look at the outsourcing and
privatization for depot maintenance and housing.  We have considerable experience with outsourcing
at various bases.  We are trying to roll those examples into the headquarters so we can provide
the information to other MAJCOMs so we can capitalize on those initiatives.  We have a ways to go
to be able to collect all those lessons learned.  
<P>  In addition, we are making some major changes in how we look at the contracting and acquisition
of services outside of the Air Force.  Finally, we are in the process of developing a strategic
plan that will identify milestones for the outsourcing and privatization program.  The Air Force
policy directive has been signed by the Chief of Staff and the Secretary and has been disseminated
to the MAJCOMs for coordination.  We should complete that final coordination by the end of June
and have it on the street by the first part of July.  
<P>
  Based upon the tremendous downsizing of the Air Force from 1987 to 1997, we have two studies   one
by the Air Force Management Engineering Agency and the other by my division within the Air Staff,
looking at both the military and civilian side of the house for requirements that are tasked
against UTCs [Unit Type Code] for contingencies.  The studies took away what is inherently
governmental and military essential, looked at headquarters structures, and came up with a pool
of assets within the Air Force that are candidates for outsourcing and privatization   90,000
members .  The wedge in the 1998 POM equated to approximately 26,000 people.  
<P>  Here is a list of some promising candidates that we will be looking at from both the MAJCOM and
the headquarters Air Force level.  For example, the Precision Measuring Equipment Labs are being
studied right now.  
 <P> In summary, we talked about the background, the charter, assumptions, and the key programs and
roles of the MAJCOMs in outsourcing and privatization.  
<P>  Clearly, the Air Force Outsourcing and Privatization Program is part of an integrated strategic
business plan.  It is not going to go away.  In many ways, O&P is the catalyst for new, more
comprehensive ways of working with the private sector and whether or not a particular activity will
be outsourced or privatized or remain in house.  Overall, the Air Force and Department of Defense
and the American people will benefit from the increased competition resulting from this program. 
The ultimate goal is being able to roll savings into modernization.  
 <P> At this time, I'll take any questions or comments you have.  
 <P> <I>MS. LANTZY:</I>   Is there a conflict between BRAC,which closes bases and combines functions due to
downsizing the operational force, and privatization of ALC functions, which continues the same
functions through contract?
<P> <I>COLONEL COLLINGS:</I> Before the BRAC,  the Air Force position was to downsize all five depots to meet
the force structure reductions.  But BRAC said that the Air Force needed to close two of those
depots.  They also said to do that through privatizing or move it to any one of the other remaining
depots.  
 <P> The Air Force saw the opportunity to privatize.  By privatization of some workloads at San Antonio
and Sacramento, we were able to do a lot of things.  We were able to defer the cost of moving
workload to the other three depots.  Back in the 1970s, we aligned our depots to be technical
repair centers.  All of the hydraulic workload was moved to Sacramento.  We essentially had only
two sources of engine repair   fighter modular engines at San Antonio and larger aircraft engines
at Tinker AFB in Oklahoma City.  Because of that strategy to develop economies of scale and more
efficiently run our depots, candidates for privatization at San Antonio and Sacramento are not
necessarily items that we could assimilate into our three remaining depots without having
significant MILCON costs to build new infrastructure.  
<P>  To mitigate costs associated with that and to mitigate the risk of actually moving that workload
and temporarily leaving us without a capability, privatization in place was a viable option for
some of the work load areas.  It was the smartest thing for us to do.  
 <P> Is it in conflict with what the BRAC?  No, because in fact those ALCs will close.  The facilities
will be turned over and contractors will come into those facilities and use the generic equipment
that will be left behind by the Air Force to perform certain workloads.  
  <P><I>MS. LANTZY:</I>  What is the status of outsourcing or privatization at McClellan Air Force Base and
Kelly Air Force Base?
 <P> <I>COLONEL COLLINGS:</I>   We are proceeding on down the line.  We have five prototypes for privatization. 
In San Antonio, the two prototypes are the C-5 paint process and engine accessories.  At Sacramento
it is for software and electrical components such as generators.  We are preparing the RFPs and
they will be out later in the year.  
  <P><I>MS. LANTZY:</I>  What is the current status to privatize the ICBM depot maintenance at Hill Air Force
Base?
 <P> <I>COLONEL COLLINGS:</I> We are looking across the board at all areas for potential savings from
outsourcing and privat-ization.  Depot maintenance for the ICBMs at Hill is one of those areas that
is being looked at.  
 <P><I>MS. LANTZY:</I>  Other than the limits imposed by law, are there any other areas out of bounds for
outsourcing and privatization?  How are outsourcing and privatization opportunity targets
identified?
 <P> <I>COLONEL COLLINGS:</I>  Outside of those that are prohibited by law, I would say, "No."  The Chief put
everything on the table for us to look at for outsourcing and privatization.  I doubt that we will
have mercenaries flying our fighters.  We will continue to have fighter pilots,  bomber pilots,
tanker pilots and the maintenance associated with that will remain blue suit.  
<P>  We are looking at all of the support side of the house but not that part that deploys to fight our
nation s wars.  Everything that is not a forward deploy unit will be looked at for outsourcing and
privatization.  
<P>  For the second question, they are hopefully being identified by the MAJCOMs.  I know that we are
looking at innovative ways of doing things.  One of the problems that we have is the integration
of contractors with blue suiters doing work of a similar type function in the same area.  For
example, we are looking at the logistics on how to segregate those functions that have to be
performed by blue suiters and those functions that are only necessary to support the peacetime
sustainment of that particular base or function.  Transportation is a good example and supply is
another.  
<P>  We are looking at ways to realign what the normal transportation and supply squadrons look like
to be able to take advantage of outsourcing and privtization.  General Viccellio [Commander, AFMC]
and his folks are looking at having core deployment bases.  He would take all of his UTC taskings
and move them to four core bases within his command.  That would be his deployment bases and then
the rest of those commercial activities and base support functions at his remaining facilities
would be looked at for outsourcing and privatizing.
  <P><I>MS. LANTZY:</I>   Do the Army and Navy have similar programs?
<P> <I>COLONEL COLLINGS:</I> The Navy is just now starting their program and it differs significantly from
the Air Force s.  The Air Force is asking the MAJCOMs to come in with initiatives while the Navy
went into their POM ramping up a program for $1.2 billion savings annually by 2002.  It is a
top-down directed program and they are setting up an office that will be run by an admiral as an
implementation office.  In other words, they have already decided to earmark about 90,000 Navy
positions to outsource or privatize over the next six years. 
<P>  The Army s program is in its infancy, and they are not sure what direction they want to go.  They
are pretty happy with the way they ve done things right now.  They ve transferred most of their
BOS and garrison support into the Guard and Reserve.  They don t see a large arena for outsourcing
and privatization.  
 <P><I>MS. LANTZY:</I>  Does privatization include specific goals to meet SBA goals or are larger companies
going to be the norm?
   <P> <I>COLONEL COLLINGS:</I> That is a good question.  When bundling contracts, small businesses feel they
are not going to have the capability to compete.  There are ways to structure contracts to get
economies of scale by having a larger contractor and still have a portion of that contract set
aside for small businesses.  That benefits small business and also allows the government to avoid
some of the administration costs associated with four, five or six small contracts.  The prime
contractor can also sub out to small business.
<P><I>MS. LANTZY:</I>   In view of budget shortfalls, is Space Command considering lifting supply
normalization requirements from base operating service contractors and allowing them to purchase
their own supplies and materials?
 <P> <I>COLONEL COLLINGS:</I>  I will defer that question to Space Command.  But, across the Air Force, we are
looking at the supply community, normal retail supply functions that are not associated with our
combat weapon systems, for outsourcing in the private sector.  There is no sense in having a base
service store that supplies paper, pens and paper clips to our folks when we can go downtown and
get it from a commercial store faster and cheaper.  We then don t need that infrastructure on our
facilities.
 <P><I>MS. LANTZY:</I>  Will outsourcing contract acquisition use the contract pre-qualification concept to
shorten the acquisition process?  
 <P> <I>COLONEL COLLINGS:</I>  If Ms. Druyun and her folks from the acquisition community were here, they could
answer that better with some of the Lightning Bolt Initiatives.  We are looking at all kinds of
ways  to shorten the acquisition lead time.  Our A-76 process, which is used for outsourcing or
privatizing outside of depot maintenance, is viewed as a cumbersome and long process.  OMB has just
come out with a revised A-76 that has given some latitude to field commanders and in some cases
can shorten the process.  
<P>  Yes, we are all working toward shortening the acquisition process throughout several initiatives
across the Air Force.
  <P><I>MS. LANTZY:</I>  Will local companies compete for contractor support or use the local good old boy
network and sole source the work?
<P> <I>COLONEL COLLINGS:</I> The paradigm of the past is shifting, and the more competition that we have the
better off the Air Force is and the better off the private sector is.  We will get a better
product, faster, and cheaper and our efficiencies will go up and our performance is better. 
Believe me, this is a win-win situation for both government, the Air Force and the private sector. 

<P>  To be able to foster a good partnership and working relationship between us and the private sector
is something that we need to do.  We ned to build a relationship by opening up business books, show
how we, the government, guarantee you, private industry, can be in that business for awhile, and
incentivize you to invest in your processes and work that relationship over a long term.
 <P><I>MS. LANTZY:</I>  Thank you Colonel Collings.  
