<TITLE>Colorado Springs-Money</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY
BACKGROUND="backgrnd/vbar2.gif" BGCOLOR="#C0C0C0" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#0000FF" LEFTMARGIN="0" TOPMARGIN="0">
<P><A HREF="index.html"><IMG
SRC="images/torcher2.gif" ALT="Return to AEF Home Page" ALIGN="TOP" BORDER="0" VSPACE="0" HSPACE="12" WIDTH="46" HEIGHT="59"></A>

<IMG
SRC="images/library.gif" ALIGN="TOP" VSPACE="16" HSPACE="18" WIDTH="345" HEIGHT="34">
</P>
<P><IMG SRC="backgrnd/spacer.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" VSPACE="4450" HSPACE="26" WIDTH="35" HEIGHT="4"><HR><H2 align="CENTER">Foundation Forums</H2><HR>
<P>Honorable Arthur L. Money<BR>
Assistant Secretary of the Air Force (Acquisition)<BR>
Air Force Acquisition Reform<BR>
AFA Symposium<BR>
Colorado Springs, Colo.<BR> 
May 24, 1996<BR>
<P>
  I've been on the job 120 days.  Today, my plan is to lay the groundwork for the
situation that the Air Force is facing and that you are facing as suppliers.
 <P> We are now at the lowest funding level we ve seen for the history of the Air
Force.  The DoD budget, as a share of Gross Domestic Product, is at the lowest it
has been since 1950, and that has been the case for the last four years.
<P>  In constant-year dollars, there have been peaks and valleys, but the slide is down
hill.  The President s Budget went over to the Hill for FY97 at $242.6 billion and
there are probably going to be some additional adds to that.  This budget is not
good news, but it is a reality.  
<P>  For the DoD budget, there is really a fourth Service   DoD organizations.  That
is a trend that has gone way too far.  Every time something doesn t quite go
right, there has been a tendency to create a DoD organization versus holding
accountable the Service that should be doing it.  I believe that pendulum is going
to start coming back a tad in the near future.  
 <P> Let's talk about the Air Force budget, roughly $60 billion.  This is as low as it
has been since 1962.  The trend shows things getting better.  The 1998 POM
[Program Objective Memorandum] which goes out to 2003 has some slight growth,
though this is the going in position and it may change.
<P>  The Total Obligation Authority [TOA] has been pretty flat.  Roughly ten years ago,
the Air Force TOA was  $120 billion while today it is roughly $60 billion and has
been at that level for a number of years.  
 <P> For the first few years of this decline, it was a calculated risk, and frankly,
it was probably okay and fairly easy to do.  Right now, we really are eating our
lunch.
 <P> How does the Air Force money get divided up?  There is a lot for "other" stuff  
family housing, personnel, BRAC [Base Realignment and Closure] and so forth.  In
FY97, BRAC will actually start producing a positive savings versus a drain.  The
O&M budget is roughly $22 billion and the investment budget is $19 billion.  This
is an indicator we are spending more money maintaining and operating things rather
than investing in the future.  It was probably okay for the first few years of a
flat budget, it is no longer satisfactory.  So, when we talk about acquisition
reform, we are also talking about Lean Logistics and whatever we can do to get the
O&M number down.
<P>  How does this impact us?  The only discretionary funds in the Air Force and within
DoD are the investment accounts.  You don t fool with MILPERS.  You don t fool
with O&M.  The only thing that gives is the investment account.  Four years ago,
my predecessors faced an investment budget of $30 billion, and today it is $19.
<P>  The history of our TOA shows a big peak about 1985 to 1987.  Again,  this is what
the numbers will say, but I don t believe it is reality in the context of the POM. 
This gives you a flavor of the mix  for aircraft, missiles, and other procurement
  it means space.  Space funding is tied up with space boostrs, accesses and the
missile procurement area, the TT&C and so forth.  A lot of it is also covered in
RDT&E [Research and Development, Test and Evaluation].
 <P> Just a month ago we had the FY96 Authorization Bill approved, and even though
Congress wanted to accelerate the FY97 budget process and finish before the August
adjournment, they are a couple of weeks behind.
 <P> Where did we put our money in the budget that is currently being marked and going
into committee review on the Hill this week?   The numbers went for programs like
the C-17, F-22, and Milstar and included a number of other space-related
activities.  Eighteen programs account for $11 billion of the $19 billion
investment budget.  Space related activities account for around 25 percent of the
$19 billion when you include both RDT&E and procurement.  
The others include Air Superiority, Precision Munitions, Intelligence and the
Information Dominance area.  
 <P> The Air Force has been doing a lot of long-range planning.  The current Chief,
General Ron Fogleman, has reinstituted and reenergized our look at where we are
going in the future.  Acquisition traditionally looks to the future while taking
a requirement, procuring, developing, and buying something that will get fielded
within three to five years.  Historically, it has been more like 7 to 10 years for
systems that will be operated for the next 30 to 50 years.  
 <P> If we are not thinking out through this timeframe, we are not doing our job very
well.  If you look at the long-term requirements   MAPs, [Mission Area Plan] and
technology plans   you can see where the demand is believed to be, and it is
clearly above the funding line.  This is not a good news story for a long, long
time.  That should set the stage for why we need to do more, better, faster, and
cheaper than the acquisition side can currently do.
 <P> A lot of hard choices have been made.  The first day I was on the job, we received
PBD-604 that was the biggest cut the Pentagon has taken in several years.  Over
the FYDP [Five Year Defense Program] it amounted to $20 billion a year, or roughly
$100 billion.  We had a goal to reduce our budget by $6.7 billion.  You say,
"Well, that is only 6.7 percent; it should be fairly easy to do."  
<P>  But, that was a real buster when you start putting things in a protected category. 
Instead of spreading the butter across all programs, we decided to eliminate some
programs, defer a lot of programs and reduce others.  When including these changes
with what has happened in programs since 1985, you can see the Air Force has
reduced aircraft purchases by 90 percent, ICBM upgrades by 43 percent, and reduced
the number of aircraft by 26 percent.  There has been a lot of downsizing.  The
initial impetus was to get us in line with the BUR [Bottom Up Review], but the
last impetus was taking this $6.7 billion out of the budget.  
 <P> Why did some programs get hit and not others?  If you take 6 percent away across
everything, you d break every program.  Instead of doing that, we decided either
to defer or eliminate some programs.  
 <P> Our personnel end-strength is also going down.  The Air Force today is as small
as it has been since its inception.  In 1947, the Air Force was 388,000 people. 
Today it is 381,000.  There has been a great reduction in active duty personnel. 
I know industry has gone through the same thing.  At the same time, the Ops Tempo
is as great as it has ever been.
 <P> In FY96 the Air Force has operated in 60 countries.  In the last two years, it has
also operated in about 30 more countries primarily for humanitarian purposes but
also in support of military or special forces operations.  In addition, there were
roughly 2,500 AWACS sorties in South America, 252,000 overall sorties over Iraq,
and 3,500 sorties over Bosnia since December.  The main point is that personnel
numbers are down and budgets are down, but the Ops Tempo is as great as ever.  
<P>  F-16s are designed for 8,000 flying hours, but we are rapidly expending all those
hours on these types of operations.  The equipment is being run ragged and so are
the people.  
 <P> Hopefully that lays the groundwork for our current environment.  Out of the
long-range, strategic planning procss over the last couple of years, we have
clearly labeled the core competencies of the Air Force.
 <P> Desert Storm showed that if we don t have Air Superiority, we won t win.  The same
is true for Space Superiority.  We will need access to space and space control
especially with systems like GPS being tied to precision munitions and Precision
Employment.  Global Mobility or Global Reach is getting troops, or supplies or
whatever is needed anywhere in the world rapidly.  Information Dominance is
probably the most ethereal and nebulous concept.  It ranges from unclassified to
highly classified activities, but essentially involves being aware of the
situation you are involved with, starting with global awareness and going down to
the cockpit.  Tools like JSTARS [E-8 Joint Surveillance and Target Attack Radar
System], AWACS [E-3 Sentry], and Revet Joint [RC-135] fall into that area.  
 <P> Based on each of these competencies, the Air Force is aligning its Panel, Council
and Board Structure along these lines.  The major commands will each fit into one
of these stovepipes and resources will cut across RDT&E, logistics, procurement,
C4I, or facilities and personnel.  There is a balancing act that takes place in
how to fund, organize, train and equip these operations.
 <P> We also face a fleet of aging aircraft with the B-52s being 34 years old, F-16As
28 years old and C-5s somewhere between 25 and 15 years old.  How do we modernize
with O&M being where it is and with the procurement or investment accounts being
discretionary accounts?  
 <P> In FY96, which still has a few months to go, we have had roughly a $900 million
Bosnian bill that comes out of the investment account.  Hurricane Opal created
roughly $80 million worth of damage down at Eglin [AFB, Fla.] which  came out of
investment accounts.  That is how the books are balanced each year.  I don t see
that changing.  Despite our need for modernization, bill payers will be forced to
handle future natural disasters or contingencies in the same way.  
 <P> There is a very detailed, well-thought out strategy, contrary to some beliefs, 
about what we are paying for now.  The Chief calls it a Time-phased and Balanced
Strategy versus a priority list.  Even with $2 billion of the $19 billion
investment account going to the F-22 this year, the F-22 is a long-range need. 
That is just the way the programs flow.  Near-term means over the next two or
three years, mid-term is five to eight and long-term is nine or more years.  
 <P> In the near-term, the C-17 is paramount  $2 billion in FY97.  There is also a
modest fighter recapitalization program.  We are trying to keep up with F-16
attrition rates, 20 per year, and F-15s, three or four per year, plus there is
some modernization going on in those fighter aircraft.  At the same time we want
to get SBIRS [Spaced-Based Infrared System] into orbit.  SBIRS was in the 2005-06
timeframe, but we ve been directed by Congress to move that to 2003.  This creates
a bill to be paid.  That is part of the National Missile Defense issue you ve
heard General Horner mention. 
 <P> In the mid-term, the emphasis is on the Conventional Bomber Upgrade.  With
precision munitions, the paradigm of bombers is changng rapidly.  Within about a
month we will have the capability to independently target 16 different targets
during one pass of the bomber.  Bombers are getting very smart and the munitions
that go with them are getting very accurate.  In Vietnam, 0.1 percent of the
weapons dropped were precision weapons while it was roughly 2 percent in Desert
Storm and 98 percent in Bosnia.  The trend is clear   no more dumb munitions are
being bought.  In fact, JDAM [Joint Direct Attack Munition] has put a GPS
capability in a tail kit on the remaining dumb bombs in the inventory, and
consequently you can get about a 10-meter accuracy.  These two issues are changing
another paradigm.  Close air support, for example, could probably be done now at
40,000 feet with an accurate or precise weapon versus coming in at a hundred feet. 
Things like this are starting to change how we do business.  
  Also, in the mid-term is our program for access to space  EELV [Evolved Expendable
Launch Vehicle].  Today we have a program to take the four contractors down to
two, and in roughly two and a half years we will select a winner.  That is going
on now so we will have access to space in a much more efficient manner in five or
10 years.  This is part of the balancing of resources that is taking place in
Space.  
 <P> Our long-term efforts involve the Airborne Laser [ABL], a theater missile defense
to attack missiles where it is launched or shortly into its flight.  The Joint
Strike Fighter is an F-16 replacement.  This joint program is very critical with
the F-16s which we are running into the ground.  The F-22s air superiority fighter
incorporates stealth and a super cruise capability greater than Mach-1 to avoid
enemy defenses.  
 <P> These programs are part of the answer to General Horner s concerns for survivable
platforms.  In conjunction with these programs, though, we do have standoff
weapons to reach out two to four hundred miles away to attack a surface-to-air
missile battery. 
 <P> Besides these mentioned, the Time-phased Balanced Plan includes roughly 300 on
going programs.  It ranges from modernizations for F-16s that have already been
in the fleet for 20 years to new starts.   
 <P> What is the strategy?  I can guarantee you as time goes along, there are going to
be fewer and fewer new starts.  Fewer new starts means modernization occurs
through sparing   modify the existing weapons systems.  If I were you, I would be
thinking about how to modernize whatever program I just delivered and keep it up
to the state of the art.  
 <P> Here in Colorado Springs that may be with the C4I, or maybe with more information
related activities, different programs than those of the aircraft folks.  I was
at Lockheed-Marietta a couple of weeks ago and we were talking about the C-5s. 
I doubt very much we will buy another C-5 or anything like a C-5 class.  We can t
afford it.  I recommended they come in with ideas on how to modernize the C-5s so
we can keep them around for 40 or 50 years.  
 <P> The U-2s will probably be 75 years old before they are retired.  B-52s are already
38, and they will probably be 50 plus years old when retired.  The F-15s will be
45 years old before they are retired.  Modernizing aging aircraft is the name of
the game.
 <P> At the same time we must continue with acquisition reforms, such as the Lightning
Bolt Initiatives.  We are also looking at what we can do in the Lean Logistics
area, the O&M area.  If we can get O&M costs down, that gives us more
discretionary money for the investments accounts.  Over time, there is going to
be a blurring between acquisition and logistics.  Logistics is going through a bit
of a paradigm shift as well from "sustainment" to "readiness."  General Horner
mentioned how he mode of attack in war will be to very rapidly defeat the enemy
within hours, not days.  The whole depot system of the services is to support an
attrition war   the World War II or Cold War mentality of a very long protracted
war requiring a very strong sustainment activity.  That is now shifting to a very
highly ready force so you can execute very quickly.  
<P> This leads into more privatization and outsourcing.  A typical example is our
current consideration for leasing engines for B-52s instead of using depot
support.  If we can do that for a bomber on the line, we can do a lot more in this
regard.  
<P>  Privatization will continue to be a very hot topic.  Anybody in the Pentagon and
at AFMC [Air Force Materiel Command] would probably tell you, "We haven't got this
figured out very well."  There are some additional constraints that further
complicate things so we have a lot of learning to do in both these areas.
 <P> In 1994, Bill Perry [Honorable William J. Perry, SECDEF] had a mandate for change,
which essentially said we ve got to redo the way we are doing acquisition as we
can't afford it.  In 1995, Darleen Druyun, Acting Assistant Secretary of the Air
Force for Acquisition following the death of Clark Fiester, said, "We needed to
take bold actions," and the Lightning Bolt Initiatives came out at this time.  
 <P> I've been in this job now about 120 days.   We have realized a cost avoidance of
roughly $13 billion through acquisition reforms so there is serious activity going
on here.  We ve actually realized some honest-to-God savings, but there are a lot
of future savings that are out there.  I believe this number is now more like $14
billion because of the GPS Block-2F upgrade which will save a billion dollars.
 <P> We are reducing cycle time and lowering costs, but I don t disagree at all with
General Horner; we have a long way to go.
 <P> Let me shift to the theme of the conference, an acquisition community that is
better, faster, cheaper and smoother   smoother comes from General Ashy s [Gen.
Joseph W. Ashy, USSPACECOM] recent briefing.
 <P> How does that manifest itself?  We are looking for Better Acquisition Strategies. 
 One of the Lightning Bolts was to have a milestone before we go out with an RFP
[Request for Proposal] to really think through the strategy on a particular
procurement.  Have we done all of them?  No.  Have we done all the A-CAT-1D
initiatives?  You bet.  All 1-Cs?  Yes!  We are working our way into A-CAT-2s.  
<P>  We are willing to first identify and take on some risk and then manage the risk
versus being totally risk-averse.  We can t afford to be totally risk-averse. 
That paradigm started shifting long ago.  We are putting more energy into it.  We
clearly want to minimize oversight and go from oversight to end-sight.
<P>The Lightning Bolts were put in to provide a jolt to the system and to start the
change.  To get a culture change, you have to unfreeze something through a crisis. 
Once people move to the new system, it will slowly refreeze itself.  In 1995, the
Lightning Bolts jumpstarted the acquisition culture, whether in the Pentagon, at
AFMC or in industry.  
<P>  I've had the opportunity to talk with a lot of people in industry, and there are
some folks still in denial, but there are some folks who are very proactive and
willing to change.  Utopia would be where it becomes business as usual, but even
then people will ask, "Do you want me to do my job or do acquisitionreform?" 
Until doing both is the normal way of doing business, how do we do it?  Through
communicating, training and teamwork.
<P>  One of the first Lightning Bolts was to do RFP reform.  We were sending out
7,000-page RFPs and wondering why we were getting 80 volumes back.  Instead of
specifying the key performance parameters, we were into the detailed "how-to"
mode.  That has been the case for years.  
<P>  We've put very senior people on these RFP scrub teams at AFMC and now at every Air
Logistics Center, every Product Center and every Laboratory.  These RFP scrub
teams are trained on what to get out of the RFPs.  The average RFP was reduced to
242 pages, a 61 percent reduction.  The Statement of Work, more of the "how-to"
business, is being replaced by a Statement of Objectives and reduced by 94
percent.  
<P>  The JASSM [Joint Air-to-Surface Standoff Missile] program, which is currently
under source selection, had a one-page Statement of Objectives.  We only listed
four things we wanted it to do  a certain range, a certain accuracy, a certain
payload and to be carried on certain platforms.
<P>  For the CDRLs [Contract Data Requirements List], the average number was reduced
to 11, down 77 percent.  During my 35 years in industry, nothing would drive me
nuts faster than all these CDRLs when nobody would ever do anything about it other
than ding you if they weren t in at the right time.  I can guarantee a lot of that
stuff was never used or looked at.  Why were we paying for it?  We had a
significant reduction, and we can still do a lot more.  For MilSpecs and
Standards, we only have a few left, a 95 percent reduction.  Most MilSpecs were
"how-to" documents.  We will still have a few left.  There are some that are being
negotiated, and maybe the pendulum has gone a little too far on this and we will
swing back a notch or two. 
<P>  We are getting good feedback from the customers and from industry regarding  these
improvements.  However, the culture metric is not so good.  That is no big
surprise.  People are reluctant to change especially if they are threatened.
 <P> I really believe evidence is showing we are on the right track.  We may not have
it figured out totally, but we are on the right track and shouldn t face major
course corrections.  
 <P> Clearly Faster Cycle Times is an important issue.  At Hanscom [AFB, Mass.], ESC
[Electronic Systems Center] kicked off a program called CCPL.  Three teams, each
made up of 10 to 15 companies, is tasked with getting systems under contract and
delivered within the technology cycle of the C4 system   18 months.  We want
systems within 18 months so they are in the field before becoming obsolete.  We
don t want any more horror stories where we keep stretching our programs and our
funding.  The greatest impact on acquisition reform will come from requirement
reform.  We still take six years to get an ORD [Operational Requirement Document]. 
We need good ideas of what we want.   Besides acquisition reform, you are going
to hear more and more about requirements reform and financial reform.  
 <P> I am really in awe of how well people do their jobs in this present system.  The
financial system is arcane and totally out of balance.  Over the years, every
indiscretion or abuse has generated another restriction, regulation or statute. 
Unless we start financial reform, we will only be able to go so far with
acquisition reform.  
 <P> Last night, John Hamre, the DoD Comptroller, Paul Kaminski, the Defense
Acquisition Executive, and the three SAEs, Service Acquisition Executives, and the
financial people, the FMs, had a meeting to talk about what we can do to start
financial reform.  
 <P> Let me go back to acquisition reform and speak to that.  Cutting cycle times will
lower costs.  That may mean driving down the staff.  We were directed to reduce
our staffs, and actually that may be good news though not for the folks who are
personally affected.  With less staff around a program, there may not be as much
being asked for nor as much mischief such as CDRLs.  
 <P> Where is this $13 billion coming from?  For the JDAMs program on Mk-82 or Mk-84
dumb bombs, we started with a unit cost of $40,000 per copy.  We tried a new
approach and quit telling them how to do it and just gave them three or four
performance parameters.  After a heated competition which included a drop-off
instead of a fly-off to demonstrate capabilities, a fixed price contract was
signed for $14,000 a copy for the first 60,000 units.  The last 20,000 off the
line may cost around $10,000 a copy.  There are some real savings coming from that
one program.
 <P> The savings from the C-17 multi-year contract was roughly a billion dollars.  For
the GPS, we have saved $80 million through consolidations and the Block 2F will
add another billion dollars savings over the system lifetime.  The Milstar 
program counters one of the myths in the business   it is easier to start
acquisition reform with a new program.  Here is an existing program that saved
upward of half a billion dollars by reducing the number of inspection points.  We
are into significant cost avoidance and potential savings. 
 <P> Where is this savings going?  We have been paying bills.  I mentioned the Bosnian
bills and the hurricanes.  The majority of that $13 billion has enabled us to fund
some other programs that wouldn t have been possible without these savings.  We
are paying for modernization through these savings.  This is really a good news
story.
 <P> Two years ago, the C-17 was very nearly canceled.  A couple of things happened. 
We have good program managers on both sides, industry and government.  Competition
certainly helped.  The Deputy Secretary of Defense said there was no lock on the
program and started to look at NDAA, Non-developmental Airlift Aircraft.  That
started driving down costs from roughly $350 million per aircraft for the first
20, to $317 million.  The last units rolling off the line will be at $173 million
a copy.  That saved roughly $4.4 billion.  When OSD asked us to find further
savings, we recommended the multi-year contract.  Stability with the contractor
and their subs for materials and contracts could save upward of $876 million. 
This helped them and freed money to go into other programs.  That contract will
take care of the program until 2002 for 120 aircraft and move to an efficient
production rate of 12 per year as well.
 <P> Milstar is an ongoing, very mature program.  The government and the contractors,
Lockheed and TRW, sat down to get more cost out of this program and reduce program
oversight.  We were doing 13,000 inspections on every satellite.  Today, we are
down to about 2,000 inspections, and there is still probably room for improvement. 
That provided roughly $570 million in cost reductions.  We also eliminated some
Mil Standards with no loss of operational capability.  They got rid of the CDRLs
that were not needed. 
 <P> For GPS, the government had a bunch of different companies performing different
functions and now has one contractor responsible for the total system performance. 
After the competition, we will save on the order of $230 million on the satellite
and about $80 million on the ground.  
 <P> By the way, we have an AQ [AF Acquisitin] site on the World Wide Web where you can
get the latest procurements, what is going on, and what we are thinking about.  
<P>  I'll end this with two thoughts.  We are trying, but we don t have all the
original ideas so I am looking for ideas from you.  If you are not participating
in acquisition reform, you ought to consider joining.  The companies in denial and
the government folks in denial are potential dinosaurs who are going to be
extinct.  Some companies are very aggressive while others are fairly lethargic. 
Check your company to see if you have requested the Common Process Initiative. 
For those who may not know what it is, let me give you an example.  
<P>  At the Raytheon factory in Hanover, Massachusetts, where they build the air-to-air
missiles, each service   Air Force, Army and Navy   had their own Specs.  There
were eight separate soldering Specs.  Now there is one.  That is where this Common
Process Initiative came from.  All of DoD and in some cases NASA, is lining up. 
Whatever the factory builds, we are going to have one set of requirements, lining
up with commercial standards of business.  It will be ISO9000 and not MilSpec
9858.  Some companies see this as a great competitive advantage so they are doing
it for all their factories.  Some of the best known companies seem to be missing
out on these requests to modernize and get these things going.  
 <P> Please let us know what else could be improved.  We may not act on all of them,
but we will certainly listen to them all.  For every system you develop or are
currently working on, think about ways to modernize the process and start talking
with your program office rather than  waiting for a new start.  
 <P> From my standpoint, there have been a lot of Lighting Bolts to get things started,
but we re beyond using a purely top down approach to change.  We need your ideas.
  <P>Thank you very much.  
 <P> <I>MS. LANTZY:</I>  We have a few questions for Mr. Money.  How are RFPs selected for
Lightning Bolt review?  Is it by dollar value?
 <P><I>MR. MONEY:</I>  Originally that was true.  It was all the big programs, 99 of them. 
 We started with Acquisition Category 1D, where the Under Secretary of Defense is
the milestone authority.  A lot of joint programs such as JSF are that way.  As
you go down the system to A-CAT-1C, I am the milestone authority.  The C-17 is an
A-CAT-1C initiative.  There is some correlation between the size of the RFP and
the initiative.  Today, every RFP of $100K or more is being scrubbed.  Over the
next year, it may be that every RFP will be scrubbed.  There are people
permanently assigned to do the scrubbing at every place that generates RFPs.  
  <P> <I>MS. LANTZY:</I>  To deploy SMTS [Space and Missile Tracking System] by 2002 or 2003,
the Air Force will have to increase its funding.  Will the Air Force increase its
TOA or will it have to take money from other programs? 
  <P><I>MR. MONEY:</I>  We ve been directed by Congress to move SMTS, SBIRS LEO, to initial
operating capability in 2003.  We have budgeted for that.  Yes it did come out of
hide.  
 <P> <I>MS. LANTZY:</I>  What steps are being taken to make the acquisition process more
responsive to near-term requirements, especially in the area of rapidly emerging
technologies for command and control and information?
  <P><I>MR. MONEY:</I>  One way is this model program at ESC where contractors have already
been down selected.  There are three teams and an arrangement, a BOA.  As a
requirement comes in, a quick decision is made regarding what team ought to be
involved.  Then,  the team will develop a prototype  for a system.  If less than
$50 million, it will be sole-source.  If it is $50 million or more, a decision
will be made at a milestone roughly halfway down that 18-month path whether or not
to compete the system at the end of the development of the prototype.  In my
estimate, one of the biggest problem areas in Air Force and even across all of
OSD, is to field 4I stuff in the same lifespan of the technology.  
 <P> It is predicated on the requirement being well enough defined.  It takes getting
the MAJCOM requirements folks in the same room with the acquisition people and
banging that out over a short period to get a definitive definition of whatever
somebody can develop and acquire to get past the wandering requirement cycle that
just adds money and waste.  If it goes to the JROC [Joint Requirements Oversight
Council], there is an additional cycle involved but some streamlining is being
attempted there as well.
  <P> <I>MS. LANTZY:</I>  Acquisition budgets are so tight, why doesn t the Air Force just buy
launch services instead of the EELV procurement?
  <P><I>MR. MONEY:</I>  EELV could end up being not only a DoD launch system but also a
commercial launch system.  If it means the launch service folks should just launch
the satellite, that is being entertained right now in some locations, primarily
in NASA.  NASA and the DoD are working more and more in the AACB, the Astronautics
and Aeronautics Control Board, to determine who will be responsible for various
functions.  However, this is a core competency of the Air Force so it may always
be in the Air Force shop.  A decision hasn't been made.  
 <P> <I>MS. LANTZY:</I>  How much coordination is there between SAF/AQ Acquisition Reform
initiatives and Air Force Lean Logistics initiatives?  How are they being
coordinated? 
 <P><I>MR. MONEY:</I>  Probably not enough even though there is a lot of effort being put
into tying the two together.  I firmly believe and so does General Viccellio [AFMC
Commander] that there is definitely a blurring of what is logistics and what is
acquisition as we go more and more into modernization through sparing.  
  <P> <I>MS. LANTZY:</I>  Please comment on how the Air Force is coping with reduced SPOs
[System Program Offices] and FFRDCs[ Federally Funded Research and Development
Corporation].  Can we go back to the way things were in the 1950s and 60s or as
the NRO [National Reconnaissance Office] operates?  What added pressure will be
placed on industry?
  <P><I>MR. MONEY:</I>  I don t know what is meant by go back to the way things were in the
1950s, but I suspect that is not going to be in the cards.  The FFRDCs, and SPOs
are all roughly on the same glide path.  We are thinking no SPO should be greater
than 50 people.  The Titan SPO today is around 400 people, and it was probably 500
a year ago.  When we say SPO size, it is not just the blue suit folks.  It is also
the SEDAs and the FFRDCs.  Over time all three of those will be roughly the same. 
<P>  AQ today is on a slope to be a third of its current size by the year 2000.  That
is causing some pain.  Probably half of the 700-800 staff within AQ are PEMs,
Program Element Monitors, who monitor a program.  Their first responsibility is
to ensure the program is funded and supported on the Hill and within the building. 
During a mark-up cycle, as many as 3,000 questions come in on a particular weapon
system from the committees.  They work all night long to answer the mail during
these phases.  There is an immense concern that bringing down the workforce will
impact our ability to answer these questions from Congress   a little legislative
reform wouldn t hurt either.  A lot of folks are being stressed.  
<P>  One of the biggest and most pleasant surprises I ve had in my first 120 days is
to see the dedication, competency, and the professionalism of the Air Force peole.
  <P> <I>MS. LANTZY:</I>  How does Ms. Druyun s Executive Committee approval of all decisions
on programs fit into the concept of acquisition reform, IPT and empowerment?
 <P><I>MR. MONEY:</I>  The Executive Committee was instigated when Ms. Druyun was the acting
Assistant Secretary.  As time has gone on, the Committee s primary purpose is to
review acquisition strategy and the plan for it.  Program decisions are being
delegated.  This past week, I signed out a policy giving the ALC, product center
and lab commanders authority to go up to $500 million with his signature.  It not
being centralized at AQ.  In fact, it is going the other way.  The strategies for
major weapons systems will still be discussed by the Committee before we go to an
RFP cycle.
 <P> <I>MS. LANTZY:</I>  The modernization plan listed nine items of which two are non-aircraft
systems.  Of these, one is access to space, EELV and the other is SBIRs to support
national missile defense.  Yet one pillar of Air Force competence is listed as
Information Dominance.  Other than SBIRS, what is happening in this area.
  <P><I>MR. MONEY:</I>  There is an immense amount of activity   essentially everything that
is C4ISR.   ISR is intelligence, surveillance, and reconnaissance.  GPS is a space
system, but we carry that in Information Dominance as it ties to weapon systems. 
Roughly 25 percent of the budget is in Space.  Today there is about 34 percent of
the budget in aircraft systems and about 10 to 15 percent for Precision Employment
or munitions.  Global Mobility has been roughly 25 percent.  Information Dominance
is roughly 10 percent, and it will be growing as time goes along.  In the
long-term over the next 10 years, you will see Space continue to grow and you will
definitely see Information Dominance grow.  We will certainly hit a steady state
or a decline in Global Mobility with C-130s continuing to be bought at roughly six
to eight a year and C-17s being fielded.  The growth areas will be   growth is a
relative term by the way   in Space and Information Dominance.  
<P>  Within AQ there are organizations called MADs, Mission Area Directors.  Their job
is to think about the ongoing program and the family of programs, and where it is
going in a modernization sense.  They work with ACC [Air Combat Command], Space
Command or whomever is the customer.  We have an Information Dominance MAD, a
Space MAD,  a Global Reach and a Global Power MAD.  We just stood up the
Information Dominance organization and moved 50 or so people into it.  That will
continue to grow.  Space will also continue to grow a bit.  Global Reach, the
mobility part, will decline.  We are putting people and money where our mouth is. 
<P>Thank you very much.    
<HR>
