<P><IMG SRC="backgrnd/spacer.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" VSPACE="4100" HSPACE="26" WIDTH="35" HEIGHT="4"><HR><H2 align="CENTER">Foundation Forums</H2><HR>
Dr. Gene H. McCall<BR>
Chairman<BR>
USAF Scientific Advisory Board<BR>
Global Presence--The New World Vistas Perspective<BR>
Mid-America AFA Symposium<BR>
St. Louis<BR>
May 3, 1996<BR>
<P>
  <I>GEN. SHAUD:</I>   The story behind this study is interesting.  Back in 1945, before there was an
AFA or an independent Air Force, Hap Arnold asked another well qualified scientist-engineer
named Ted von Karman to do a study that he called "New Frontiers."  The idea was to look at
the next 50 years and figure out what technologies would be appropriate for the Army Air Corps
to follow.  Ted von Karman did that.  Our United States Air Force used that study produced by
von Karman much to its advantage over the past 50 years.
 <P>
 About a year ago, the Secretary of the Air Force, Dr. Sheila Widnall, and our Chief, General
Ron Fogleman, thought it would be interesting to task the Scientific Advisory Board to come up
with a study looking at technologies past the year 2000.  
 <P>
 Ted von Karman's document was dated December 15, 1945 and it was very important to the
Chief and the Secretary for Dr. Gene McCall s document to be dated December 15, 1995,
exactly 50 years later.  With that as background, let me turn over the lectern to Dr. McCall for
an an overview of his work.  To say that it will stimulate discussion is an understatement.
 <P>
<I>DR. McCALL:</I>   Thank you, General Shaud.   I characterize the New World Vistas study as
offering opportunities for the future.  As General Shaud mentioned, we were tasked jointly by the
Secretary and the Chief in November 1994 to look at technologies for the next century and to
predict the effects of technologic change on the Air Force.  
<P>
  There were several things that were a bit different from the early study.  One, we were to
consider this in light of the joint service team.  Very few future operations wont t involve
partners, at least the Army, Navy and Marines and frequently allies.  Also, affordability has
become a very large issue.  We simply could not go out and do everything that we could imagine
because we couldn't afford it.  
 <P>
 The study consisted of 12 panels.  The technology panels consisted of people who were to
come up with new technologies and new ideas, a rather free swinging group, and who then
submitted these technology ideas to the application panels, which were composed of people who
had more contact with the military.  We also had participation from the Army and the Navy and
from industry.  The people who worked on this study ranged from vice presidents of industry
down to Air Force Academy cadets.  They were all volunteers. 
 <P>
 Some background will give a perspective for the study.  The Cold War shaped much of the
last 50 years.  In March of 1946, Winston Churchill gave his famous Iron Curtain speech at
Fulton, Missouri.  Both the British and American governments were horrified at the speech.  He
said, "An iron curtain has descended over the continent."  It was not received well at the time.
 <P>
 During the Cold War, we responded to a threat from the Soviet Union mainly by examining
scenarios.  We constructed scenarios that were backed up by intelligence information, most of
them, I believe, were very accurate.  Then we derived requirements and needs for systems and
operational capabilities that we would have to have.  We always had a problem with cost because
we would design a system, estimate the cost, and of course it would be too much, and we'd
iterate this a few times and finally come up with something that we needed.  But we didn't really
think a lot about generic capabilities.  Through the process of developing a response to these
scenarios, we developed some really good generic capabilities which we used to great advantage
in operations such as Desert Storm or Eldorado Canyon.  
<P>
  Today, we say no "well-defined enemy" exists, but you should not interpret that to mean that
no enemy exists.  There are certainly 6,000 nuclear weapons outside of the United States and
many of them are pointed here even today.  But, we don't really understand quite how the world
works at the moment.  We are back to a situation very much like the end of World War II, where
again, there was no definite enemy out there.  There was no solidified boundaries and sides in the
world.  Then, we had to look at capabilities rather than scenarios, and that is what we've done
with the current study.   
 <P>
 A thread running through the entire study is that increased tempo results in increased
effectiveness.  This is not a new concept, although people rediscover it periodically.  We hear
terms such as getting inside your enemy's decision loop.  I looked back to see where I could find
the first reference to this concept, and the first I could find was in a set of memoranda written by
Admiral Nelson just before the battle of Trafalgar in 1805.  It was quite clear that he understood
the principles involved, numerically and not just the basic philosophical principle, and used it to
good effect in defeating the French fleet.  
 <P>
 We knew that commercial technologies were going to be important technologies.  Everyone
knows that.  We knew that information processing was going to be a key area, and you will see
that throughout the entire study.  It was not so clear that space was going to play such a large part
in the 21st century.  We now believe that not only space communications, but the Iridium and
Teledesic [commercial constellation of 66 satellites in Near Earth Orbit] systems can provide
worldwide data and voice communications from any point in the world to any other point
without the use of bulky satellite receivers and transmitters.  
 <P>
 The surveillance business is going into space in a big way.  There are commercial
organizations that plan to deliver hyper-spectral imagery with one-meter resolution to any one
who is willing to pay for it.  That is a militarily significant capability available to anyone with
cash in hand.  So what are we going to do about that?
 <P>
 There are two things.  First of all, we buy the service.  Second, we figure out a way to deny it
to others when it is necessary for us to do so.  
 <P>
 Reduced procurement budgets will affect us.  There are a lot of systems in the next century
that are here right now, the C-17, for example.  The KC-135 is not due for retirement until 2015. 
At that time, the average age of the fleet will be 79 years.  The airplane may have the same wings
on it, but it won't have the same radios in it.  We better have kept these systems updated, whether
they are KC-135s, F-15s or F-16s.  We need to keep them superior while we bring along new
systems like the F-22 and the JAST [Joint Strike Fighter] fighter.  
 <P>
 Today, there is a word that you hear a lot   revolutionary.  Unless you can call it
revolutionary, it is not going to get funded these days.  The word is so overused it is almost
meaningless.  I just offer you a few thoughts.  Evolutionary is not necessarily bad.  Let me give
you an example.  The nuclear weapon is undoubtedly the most revolutionary weapon every
invented.  It changed the face of the globe.  In my opinion, that never would have happened had
we been constrained to use the weapons of the sort dropped on Japan.  It happened because we
developed thermonuclear weapons that had hundreds of kilotons or megaton yields and we
developed intercontinental missiles that could deliver them halfway around the world in half an
hour.  Those were evolutionary steps applied to revolutionary technologies.  That is what made
the difference.  
 <P>
 From the Air Force point of view, the F-22 is an evolutionary step in the use of stealth,
advanced air-to-air weapons, advanced radar systems, advanced avionics characteristics and
advanced high-speed flight.  All of those evolving capabilities come together into a single
system, the F-22, which is going to be a superior air-to-air fighter for the next 30 years.
<P>
  However, we really have to identify things that are innovative.  It is certainly true in war that
the advantage usually goes to the innovator.  We need to be able to develop new technologies
and to understand how they work and to develop ways of demonstrating them that are much
cheaper than we do today.  We need to take smaller steps.  We need to learn from our failures. 
We need to let things fail, break the technologies to find out what the limits are and then build
things that are useful from them.  I also caution people that most revolutionary ideas will be
opposed by a majority of the decision makers.  I also caution them not to use that as a way of
identifying revolutionary ideas.  
 <P>
 A revolutionary technology is related to the current scale of change.  Computers have been
around for many years, but the exponential curve defining the recent explosion of information
technologies now points to a "revolutionary" change.  Even though things are changing very
rapidly, they may have a very long history that was necessary to make them revolutionary at this
point in time.
 <P>
 Let me use a couple of examples from information technologies.  Current information
technologies were certainly enabled by the development of the transistor in 1948.  The computer
is also an integral part of all information systems and the Stewart Program Computer was also
invented in 1948.  There is nearly a 50-year history from that time to when we say things are
exploding and the technology is exponentiating.
 <P>
 When I wrote the first draft of this report and sent it to General Fogleman, it came back with
a note asking "Does this have anything to do with Global Reach/Global Power?"  Even though
we really had covered it, I thought about it a bit.  Global Reach/Global Power does give you a
feeling for what we are about.  Some call it a bumper sticker, but out of that we can extract
strategic goals and talk about core competencies and generic capabilities that will allow us to
accomplish the goals, and eventually extract mission possibilities.  We also build Mission Area
Plans tied to all of that.  
<P>
  We held a meeting at Air University [Maxwell AFB, Ala.] during the study, and we tried to
map our technologies on to these Mission Area Plans.  You can do it, but it gets really
complicated.  Finally we gave up and asked, "Is there anyway we can arrange all of this so that it
makes more sense to discuss it among ourselves and with other people?"  We came up with what
we call "capabilities enabled by technology," which grouped the technologies so we can discuss
them as a capability area and explain them to other people.  
<P>
  The first is Global awareness.  This capability should give you a feeling for what it is, and
allow you to know whatever you need to accomplish the mission.  What is it?  It is a system of
sensors and satellites distributed around the world, largely space based.  It provides, continuous,
worldwide hyper-spectral observation with five to 10-meter accuracy.  
 <P>
 The good news about basing something in space is that there are no air-space violation
problems.  You can fly anywhere in the world at any time.  The bad news is you have to fly
everywhere in the world all the time because the satellite just keeps going around.  You can t just
put a satellite over a particular city at a particular time.  If you try to divert very much out of an
orbit, your satellite is not going to last very long because you use fuel.  If you put up enough
satellites for complete coverage all the time, the number gets up into 100 to 300 satellites.  That
number is consistent with what the communication people are going to be putting up for the
Iridium or Teledesic system.  
 <P>
 ATR (Automatic Target Recognition) lets you see fixed things on the ground and tell what
they are or at least whether they are militarily significant   tank or truck.  At 10-meter
resolution, we can't tell the difference between a house and a tank unless it moves.  Some
experiments show machines actually do a better job of interpreting the spectrum being emitted
than they do spatial resolution such as shapes.  The human brain works just the opposite because
we have such a limited spectral range in our eyes.  Using five to 10-meter resolution spectrum
data with some calculations allows a targeting accuracy which is equivalent to two or three-meter
spatial resolution.  
 <P>
 Why do we want to do this?  We began to look at the possibility of putting something like
this observation system on a commercial satellite of the Iridium type.  There are size constraints
based upon the size of the optical lenses.  It turns out that at five or 10-meters, the system would
weigh a couple hundred kilograms and could be mounted Teledesic satellite which allows the
communications, all the cross-linking and downlinking, through commercial facilities and could
be launched by commercial spacecraft.  
 <P>
 What does that buy you?  The MILSTAR system, a military communication system, consists
of six satellites, which cost $12 billion and are being launched over a 15 year period.  On the
other hand, the commercial satellite producers plan to take a satellite from design to orbit in 24
months, develop a production line which will produce the satellite every two days and will
launch satellites at an average rate of 150 a year.  That is a capability worth tagging on to.  It also
gives you another way of protecting them.  The MILSTAR system is designed to go through a
nuclear war.  That is why it costs so much.  It is worth doing.  
 <P>
 The commercial people also have problems with radiation in orbit, with jamming and many
of the other military type problems.  But, if you have 300 satellites and you lose six or seven of
them, it doesn't really matter.  You have massive redundancy in the system and in another couple
of weeks you can have them all back on orbit.
 <P>
 If we can do this, they will not just be individual satellites doing their own thing.  They
communicate and each satellite knows where the other satellite is and what it is doing.  Rather
than just getting 10 times the capability from 10 times as many satellites, we may get 100 times
the capability from 10 times as many satellites because of the interaction.
 <P>
 What can we do now?  We can build things like this so we can detect radio frequency
emitters, radars, for example, on the ground through an accuracy of about 10-meters anywhere in
the world if they radiate for one second.  It turns out that the accuracy of location depends on the
distance between satellites, not on the size of satellite antenna itself. 
 <P>
 Why do I want to do this?  In the future, we believe that the surface-to-air missile will
represent the greatest threat to the U.S. Air Force, whether it is a threat to airlifters or a threat to
combat aircraft.  For a SAM site, we can detect their radars to about 10 meters.  We can then
send a hypersonic weapon from 200-300 kilometers away to strike that site within 2 minutes. 
Our objective is to make the operation of a surface-to-air missile site the most dangerous
occupation known to man. 
<P>
  If we can get one-meter accuracy out of the commercial product, we can generate a map of
the world to one-meter in three dimensions.  To store a map of the world to a meter accuracy
with suitable compression requires 20 to 40 terabytes of information.  For those who might have
a gigabyte of storage on our desktop system, I am talking about 20-40,000 times as much
storage.  In another decade we will be able to get all of that in about a cubic foot of storage.  We
can put the one-meter world map on every airplane, boat or truck to go anywhere in the world at
any time.  Using GPS we can fly terrain avoidance directly off the GPS satellites with an
accuracy that is better than we can fly today with active terrain avoidance radar systems on
board.
 <P>
 What happens when the weather goes bad?  We looked at the possibility of space-based
radar.  It is possible, but very expensive.  There is a fundamental physical law that says doubling
the distance from the target to the radar, needs 16 times as much power to keep the signal and
noise ratio the same.  If I go into space where the distances are very large and the power systems
are poor because of a reliance on solar cells, it may require nuclear power, but that is still
expensive, if it is permitted.  Synthetic aperture radar is possible where we have the capability for
revisiting the site about once an hour.  It takes 100 satellites to provide continuous coverage
while it only takes about 10 systems for coverage once an hour.  We can begin to afford that sort
of thing.  
 <P>
 What about the weather?  In Desert Storm, approximately half of the F-117 missions were
aborted because of weather.  That is in a part of the world with the world's best weather.  If you
could eliminate that problem, you effectively double the size of the F-117 fleet.  Knowing the
weather well enough so you don't fly when you can't fly over the target essentially doubles your
tempo.  We know how to do that from space.  We can measure ceiling, visibility, layer structures,
rainfall state and winds   what I call flying weather   and predict the weather for a few
hours which is generally all we need to do.<P>
 Eventually, as an area heats up, we can begin to move in airplanes and other things next to a
border even if we can't overfly.  We can bring in unmanned air vehicles, put large radar
transmitters on them, and flood the theater area out to 100 nautical miles or more.  With the
UAVs, which can fly high, from 65,000 to perhaps even 80,000 feet, we can see maybe 300-400
nautical miles.  Satellites can then record and detect the reflected energy.  We can put the high-powered part in an airplane and the low-power, high resolution system in the satellite where it
belongs.  We can even distinguish ground clutter from cruise missiles.  We can then move
overhead with radar or electro-optic systems to get accuracies down around a centimeter if that is
what we want.
<P>
  We are looking for "informationese" where people get all the information they need to do
their job.  In the past, we built systems whose hardware will deliver information to a very limited
number of people.  We can't afford to do that anymore.  In principle, it should be possible for any
one to get any thing.  You may limit information flow by protocol, security reasons,
communication band widths and lots of other reasons, but you shouldn t restrict it based on the
hardware.  Today it costs more to do that than to give it to everybody.  The goal should be a
completely flat, uniform information system that you restrict as needed.  
<P>
  Even in the past, we wound up wanting to move information places it was never intended to
go, and we have spent a lot of money trying to do that.   
 <P>
 Now that a warfighter knows everything, although that is never going to be the case, there is
still a substantial need for human interaction and judgement.  Don't get the idea that we are
talking about automated systems.  In any case where the systems themselves are intelligent, we
generally imagine the system as being an advisor and the human as being a "decider."  That runs
through the entire study.  
 <P>
 A second thread that runs through this entire study implies we have to integrate these
systems.  We cannot afford to build systems that only handle one of these jobs.  There is no
nation that can afford to do that.  The only way to afford it, is if you combine things.  You build
integrated systems.  Instead of one ground station for each satellite, you must build a terrestrial
information system that handles all satellites.  You don't build a GPS receiver for a C-130 and a
different one for the F-16.  You use the same one for both systems.  Software may be a little
different; but it may be that you can put the F-16 software or the C-130 software everywhere.   
 <P>
 All of these capabilities for awareness feed into global planning, execution control.  We tend
to get the order wrong.  It is very easy for people to discuss high level global planning where you
can be vague.  But, you really need to start from the execution side and ask "What do I want to
task in the way of systems and what do I want to do in the way of missions?  Who are the people
who are going to be involved and what information do they have to have?"  Then you can specify
those requirements and build systems that make these people's job easier and allow them to work
with fewer people.  This is the kind of thing we want to do.
<P>
  We want to reduce planning time to hours or minutes, but be sensible about it.  We are not
just talking about reducing the air tasking order cycle time.  The time required to produce a set of
instructions or a set of priorities or a set of tasks to an operational unit should not depend on the
time to enter the data necessary to do it, or on the time necessary to run the computer program or
on the time required to communicate the task and priorities back to the units.  That is a
technological explanation of reduced planning time.  It may still take people time to think about
plans and generate them, but we should also have this continuous simulation which is running
alongside of these plans using real databases to help predict the outcome of your contingency
planning. 
 <P>
 Today's planning system must obviously work in a joint environment and this system works
for everything that flies in the air if the other services will bring their peculiar parts to tie into
this.  Our design for an aerospace planning and execution system is not for battle management. 
We are talking about execution as a single planning system, whether planning an attack mission,
an airlift or an intelligence mission.  If you plan a strike mission, a planning system should
immediately produce the requirements for your logistics, your airlift, sealift and so on.  If you are
planning an airlift humanitarian mission, the planning system should also give you some advice
on what kind of protection you need to the point of even tasking combat aircraft to get there at
the right place and right time.
<P>
  We need to use fiber-optic systems.  We may use satellites a lot today, but fiber-optic
networks are becoming cheaper to use.  We can produce 40 gigabit transmission rates through
one fiber.  That means we could handle the nation's U.S. communication requirements in only a
few fibers.  However, we use many fibers for massive redundant protection.  
 <P>
 We want to link satellites to large airplanes and the UAVs.  We frequently have this
discussion about whether we link satellites to high performance airplanes.  Today, if you wanted
to build a one megabit per second, which is very modest by today's standard, two-way link into
an F-16 from a satellite it would cost you a million dollars per copy.  We probably can't afford
that.  You can much more easily link a satellite with a large airplane, such as a tanker, an airlifter
or AWACS.  Almost always, the smaller high performance airplanes are close enough to a large
airplane that with high powered communications you can communicate without the satellites.  
<P>
  Satellites could communicate with each other and down to a set of large airplanes, which
would be the equivalent of gateways on the Internet to provide local area networks consisting of
fighter airplanes. 
 <P>
 I don't have to justify the importance of mobility for this audience, but it is throughput that
matters in airlift.  We could make airplanes fly twice as fast or could make them bigger.  If you
realize that a shipment generally takes most of its time on the ground rather than in the air, what
you need to do is minimize the ground time, not necessarily minimize the air time.  Efficient air
time can reduce the number of airlifters used.  We can increase the range and efficiency of an
airplane by about 50 percent through increased engine efficiencies which are increasing at about
a percent per year.  
 <P>
 I already mentioned terrain following systems, but let me say a few words about the
Uninhabited Combat Air Vehicle.  This is not your usual UAV.  The current unmanned vehicles
we have today are what I call toy airplanes.  They don't have very good performance, and they
crash a lot.  They do particular jobs, but that is about it.  This is a new high performance airplane
that would probably start as a plus or minus 10-G system and perhaps eventually go to a 20-G
airplane.  At that point, it can out fly most missiles, both air-to-air and surface-to-air.  
<P>
  Other than performance, why would you want to do this?  I don't think we will eliminate
human beings from combat air vehicles during the next 30 to 50 years because the human brain
is just so important in many cases.  In fact, the first place that one sees this sort of vehicle may be
in a flying wing for a manned vehicle to accomplish particular tasks, such as attacking SAM
sites.  
 <P>
 We have more design space and more design options in a system like this than in a manned
system.  We can design inlets that run right through the cockpit area, for example.  We don't have
to put in an ejection seat and all the life support equipment or canopies that increase the radar
cross section.  This approach may achieve a factor of 10-15 in reducing radar cross section.  This
will reduce the effective range of enemy radars by another factor of two over what we do today. 
That will require our adversaries to by four times as many radars to cover a particular area. 
<P>
  Why else would we want to do this?  In World War I and II, the sensor on the airplane was
the pilot's eyes for the most part.  The processor was the pilot's brain and it all happened on the
airplane.  Nowadays, more and more of the information available is coming from off board
sources.  It begins to make more sense to bring the pilot to the information instead of bring
information to the pilot.  Now we have one poor guy who is flying the airplane, trying to stay
alive, trying to find a target, trying to hit the target and then trying to get home.  The new
systems allow you to do this from a remote point.  We think it is possible, but we need better
human machine interfaces and we need better ways of interfacing with computers.
 <P>
 Directed energy will be entering the force shortly after the turn of the century.  We will soon
field the Airborne Laser [ABL] system on board a 747-400F.  It is designed to shoot down
theater missiles.  The revolutionary concept that made it possible compensates for atmospheric
turbulence    it takes the twinkle out of the star.  That is an Air Force developed science.  The
entire world is installing that capability into every telescope today, and they are coming to the
Phillips Laboratory at Albuquerque to find out how to do it.  The Air Force is ahead in many of
these technologies.  
 <P>
 We all hear about information warfare.  It is not going to replace what we know as warfare,
but is going to be more and more important in the future as an adjunct of warfare.  We must
integrate it with the rest of the force and not leave it sitting in a classified vault.  It must be part
of the air tasking order to target the proper things just as we target tanks, and buildings. 
 <P>
 Flexible fuzing will us to build weapons that are good for more than one target.  It allows for
a smaller, more effective force.  In a decade or so, it will probably mean 10 times smaller which
means an airplane can strike 10 times as many targets in a single sortie.  The future combat air
vehicles will be small enough to be delivered by airlifter.
 <P>
 There is a form of directed energy that is likely to appear in perhaps 30 years, a photo fighter. 
The skin is covered with small, solid state diode lasers that are all phased together like a phased-array radar.  Nothing moves, but we can direct the beam by changing the phasing on the lasers to
strike targets.  
 <P>
Finally, there will be ways to project power from space, probably using mirrors and ground
based lasers, at least until the lasers become a lot more efficient and a lot more reliable than they
are.  
 <P>
 We are going to have to step up to the problem of space control.  Much of American
infrastructure is going to be in space   communication system and earth observing system. 
The Air Force may be called upon to protect those civil assets from attack.  We may also be
called upon to attack assets that are threats to us.  Those assets may belong to countries that are
friendly from time to time so we may not want to destroy them but simply turn them off for
awhile.  Politically we may decide not to do it, but we ought to consciously realize that if we
don't, we are going to pay the price in the future. 
 <P>
 There will be a next generation GPS.  As GPS is so jammable, we may need a factor of about
1,000 in the signal to noise ratio.  Current technology can give a factor of 100 in signal strength
using direct broadcast TV technology.  The other factor of 10 we can get by using modern codes. 
Again, GPS is one of those technologies way up on that technology curve because the current
system was frozen in 1973.   GPS is a 20 to 30-year old system on orbit and producing dramatic
results.  
 <P>
 These new systems are nothing without the people to operate them and to make the decisions. 
I hope, that is the way it is always going to be.  I hope we are never going to send automatons to
war.  We need models of people that we can put into computers rather than designing things and
finding out that people can't use them very well.  
 <P>
 We also see a great deal of commercial involvement in the development of technology.  It
may mean cooperation with the entertainment industry such as Walt Disney Corporation because
that industry works very hard to make us feel as though we are in a virtual reality.  It also
happens that many of the best graduates of computer science departments nowadays are going
into the entertainment industry, not just because they pay a lot of money, but also because that is
where the action is.  They are the ones who can develop this high band width system.
 <P>
 There are also technologies we must develop within the Air Force or within DoD because the
commercial world is not going to do it for us.  Improving the efficiency of space launch is one
area.  We need to develop higher efficiency, and higher energy fuels.  
 <P>
 In the past, we have tended to build things to military specifications.  All of you have done
that.  We are saying that we would like to go to commercial, off-the-shelf [COTS] technologies. 
Commercial technologies must also imply commercial practices.  If you take an off-the-shelf
piece of technology and put it through an extensive military operational testing program, you are
not going to save a lot of money.  You save money by saying, "I know it is a good system and
therefore I am going to use it."  
  <P>
We also created a list called "work to stop."  After making that list, I quit walking down dark
alleys.  We identified things that are of interest to the Air Force, but we simply can't afford to do
anymore.  They are good programs, but they must be done outside.  Things like cockpit designs
and ejection seats technologies should be done by airplane manufacturers and not Air Force
research labs.  
 <P>
 Environmental remediation research is another area which will change.  Even though the Air
Force has a world class scientific program, we are going to be going instead toward pollution
prevention technologies  
 <P>
 The Air Force has not yet experienced a fundamental shift in thinking and operation the same
way the Army and the Navy did some years ago.  But, I think it s coming.  For example,
uninhabited combat air vehicles are important in terms of performance.  If the Air Force doesn't
develop them, somebody else is going to.  Right now ARPA [Advanced Research Projects
Agency] is developing the unmanned tactical aircraft.  The Air Force will end up with systems
that they are not comfortable with and may not handle the job but were built by somebody else
and given to them.  But, if we do it ourselves, it is going to be an exciting time.  
 <P>
 It will be different, involve a lot of change, and I hope it will provide equal enjoyment for all
of us. Thank you.
 <P>
 <I>GEN. SHAUD:</I>   Gene, thank you for leading us through this journey.  The Chief discusses the
need for "out of box thinking," and many oxen have been gored.  Gene, I want to thank you
personally for your contributions.  
  <P>
 We have been on quite a journey today.  Here in St. Louis, we have gathered together to talk
about a particular subject called Global Presence.  We talked about presence from space, and
presence with a team of active duty, Guard and Reserve.  We talked about the contributions of
industry to presence with such organizations as UPS, and we talked about the contribution that
the entrepreneurial spirit of the United States of America brings to these equations.  Finally,
from Gene McCall and the gang that took on New World Vistas, we bring the best of academe to
bear on Global Presence.  We have remarkable resources here in the United States of America
that we can bring to bear on a subject that is absolutely vital for national security.
  <P>
What does AFA and Aerospace Education Foundation have to do with all this?  AFA and
AEF have three core competencies.  One is advocacy.  For example, we are on the Hill talking
about F-22.  Our vehicle for advocacy is our Air Force Magazine.  It is where we can step up
and say, "Yes, we do have the best Air Force in the world and here is why."  
 <P> Second, we provide services   everything from baseball hats and insurance policies to
going on the Hill to talk about compensation initiatives.  
 <P> A third area of competency is education.  We get involved at all levels.  This conference in St.
Louis like our other symposia helps spread important information about aerospace power.  Our
Aerospace Education Foundation will publish the Forum Proceedings that goes to thousands of
people, including the Hill, to let them know what we are talking about here.  Not only that, we
will disseminate information about the conference over our Home Page on the World Wide Web,
//www.afa.org. 
 <P> This is what we do and what AFA and AEF are all about.  We are advocates.  We provide
services and we are in the education business., and we love every minute of it.  We really thank
you for your participation here with us.  
 <P><I>MR. SYMINGTON:</I>   John, thank you for coming to St. Louis to participate and moderate our
event.  This was designed as an education event.  It was a marvelous experience for everybody
who attended.  I attended a number of distinguished universities, and I don t believe my
professors ever got up to 70 percent of the competence and professionalism demonstrated by our
speakers here.  I do hope you are departing much more informed than when you arrived.

